9	[{"value": "<p>Aragorn is the son of Arathorn. He is one of the main protagonists of The Lord of the Rings. Aragorn was a Ranger of the North, first introduced with the name Strider at Bree, as the Hobbits continued to call him throughout The Lord of the Rings. He was eventually discovered to be the heir of Isildur and rightful claimant to the thrones of Arnor and Gondor. He was also a confidant of Gandalf and an integral part of the quest to destroy the One Ring and defeat the Dark Lord Sauron.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"text": "Let's hunt some Orc.", "attribute_name": "Aragorn", "attribute_group": ""}, "type": "blockquote"}, {"value": "<p>Aragorn led the Fellowship of the Ring following the loss of Gandalf in the Mines of Moria while fighting the Balrog. When the Fellowship was broken, he tracked the hobbits Meriadoc Brandybuck and Peregrin Took with the help of Legolas the elf and Gimli the dwarf to Fangorn Forest. Then he fought in the battle at Helm's Deep and the Battle of the Pelennor Fields. After defeating Sauron's forces in Gondor, he led an army of Gondor and Rohan against the Black Gate of Mordor to distract Sauron's attention so that Frodo Baggins and Samwise Gamgee could have a chance to destroy the One Ring.</p><p><br/></p><p>At the end of The Lord of the Rings, Aragorn was crowned King Elessar Telcontar (\\"Elfstone Strider\\") of Gondor. He married Elrond's daughter, Arwen, and assumed the Sceptre of Ann\\u00faminas as King of Arnor, uniting the two kingdoms for the first time since the reign of Isildur.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"size": "h2", "header_text": "History"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": "<p>The son of Arathorn II and his wife Gilraen, Aragorn was born on 1 March, T.A. 2931.[1] Through his ancestor Elendil (whom he closely resembled)[2] Aragorn was a descendant of the first king of N\\u00famenor, Elros Tar-Minyatur; the twin brother of Elrond</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>When Aragorn was two years old, his father was killed while pursuing orcs. Aragorn was afterwards fostered in Rivendell by Elrond. At the bidding of Elrond, his lineage was kept secret, as Elrond feared he would be killed like his father and grandfather if his true identity as Isildur's heir became known. Aragorn was renamed Estel (\\"hope\\" in Sindarin) to hide his existence from Sauron and his servants. He was not told about his heritage until he came of age in 2951.[1]</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "https://youtu.be/2H4Q_aA4QiQ", "type": "embed"}, {"value": "<p>Elrond revealed to Aragorn his true name and ancestry, and delivered to him the shards of Elendil's sword Narsil, and also the Ring of Barahir. He withheld the Sceptre of Ann\\u00faminas from him until he earned the right to possess it. Aragorn met and fell in love with Arwen, Elrond's daughter (whom he mistook for Tin\\u00faviel), when she returned from L\\u00f3rien, her mother's homeland.[1]</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Aragorn thereafter assumed his role as the sixteenth Chieftain of the D\\u00fanedain, the Rangers of the North, and went into the wild, living with the remnants of his hosts, whose kingdom had been destroyed through civil and regional wars centuries before.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Aragorn met Gandalf the Grey in 2956, and they became close friends.[1] The Rangers help to guard the Shire, inhabited by the diminutive, agrarian Hobbits. In the areas around the Shire and Bree he became known as \\"Strider\\".[3]</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>From 2957 to 2980, Aragorn undertook great journeys, serving in the armies of King Thengel of Rohan (King Th\\u00e9oden's father) and of Steward Ecthelion II of Gondor (father of Denethor). His tasks helped to raise morale in the West and to counter the growing threat of Sauron and his allies, and he acquired experience that he would later put to use in the War of the Ring. Aragorn served his lords during that time under the name Thorongil (Eagle of the Star). With a small squadron of ships from Gondor, he led an assault on Umbar in 2980, burning many of the Corsairs' ships and personally slaying their lord during the Battle of the Havens. After the victory at Umbar, \\"Thorongil\\" left the field, to the dismay of his men, and went East.[1]</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Aragorn also travelled through the Dwarves' mines of Moria and to Rh\\u00fbn and Harad, where (in his own words) \\"the stars are strange\\".</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>In 2980, he visited L\\u00f3rien, and there again met Arwen. He gave her an heirloom of his House, the Ring of Barahir,[4] and, on the hill of Cerin Amroth, Arwen pledged her hand to him in marriage, renouncing her Elvish lineage and accepting mortality, the \\"Gift of Men\\". Elrond withheld from Aragorn permission to marry his daughter until such time as his foster son should be king of Gondor and Arnor reunited. To marry a mortal, Arwen would be required to choose mortality and thus eventually separate the immortal Elrond from his daughter; and Elrond feared that in the end Arwen might find the prospect of death too difficult to bear.[1]</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Gandalf grew suspicious of the ring belonging to the hobbit Bilbo Baggins, which was later discovered to be Sauron's One Ring.[5] Gandalf asked Aragorn to track Gollum, who had previously possessed the Ring. This hunt led Aragorn across Rhovanion, and he finally captured Gollum in the Dead Marshes northwest of Mordor and brought him captive to King Thranduil\\u2019s halls in Mirkwood, where Gandalf questioned him.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}]	2	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
38	[{"value": "<p><b>Bilbo Baggins</b>\\u00a0is the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Title_character\\">title character</a>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protagonist\\">protagonist</a>\\u00a0of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s 1937 novel\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\">The Hobbit</a></i>, as well as a\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supporting_character\\">supporting character</a>\\u00a0in\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. In Tolkien's narrative\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conceit\\">conceit</a>, in which all the writings of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\">Middle-earth</a>\\u00a0are translations from the fictitious volume of\\u00a0<i>The\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Book_of_Westmarch\\">Red Book of Westmarch</a></i>, Bilbo is the author of\\u00a0<i>The Hobbit</i>\\u00a0and translator of various \\"works from the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvish_language\\">elvish</a>\\" (as mentioned in the end of\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\">The Return of the King</a></i>).</p><p></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"size": "h2", "header_text": "The Hobbit"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": {"caption": "Bilbo Baggins illustration", "style": "half", "image": 28}, "type": "image"}, {"value": "<p>In\\u00a0<i>The Hobbit</i>, Bilbo Baggins, a\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit\\">hobbit</a>\\u00a0in comfortable middle age at 50 years old, was hired despite his objections as a \\"burglar\\" by the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Istari\\">wizard</a>\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\">Gandalf</a>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_The_Hobbit_characters#Thorin.27s_company\\">13 Dwarves</a>\\u00a0led by their king\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thorin_Oakenshield\\">Thorin Oakenshield</a>\\u00a0on a quest to reclaim the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lonely_Mountain\\">Lonely Mountain</a>\\u00a0and its treasure from the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragon_(Middle-earth)\\">dragon</a>\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smaug\\">Smaug</a>. The adventure took Bilbo and the companions through the wilderness, to the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\">elf</a>\\u00a0haven of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\">Rivendell</a>, across the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misty_Mountains\\">Misty Mountains</a>\\u00a0and the black forest of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirkwood\\">Mirkwood</a>, to\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esgaroth\\">Lake-town</a>\\u00a0in the middle of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_Lake_(Middle-earth)\\">Long Lake</a>, and eventually to the Mountain itself. Here, after the dragon was killed and the Mountain was reclaimed, soon after that the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Five_Armies\\">Battle of Five Armies</a>\\u00a0took place.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>In his journey, Bilbo encountered other fantastic creatures, including\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troll_(Middle-earth)\\">trolls</a>, elves,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_animals#Great_Spiders\\">giant spiders</a>, a\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beorn\\">man who can change shape into a bear</a>,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\">goblins</a>,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eagle_(Middle-earth)\\">eagles</a>,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warg\\">wolves</a>\\u00a0and a slimy, murderous creature named\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gollum\\">Gollum</a>. Underground, near Gollum's lair, Bilbo accidentally found a\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\">magic ring of invisibility</a>, which he used to escape from Gollum.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>By the end of the journey, Bilbo had become wiser and more confident, having saved the day in many precarious situations. Bilbo's journey has been compared to a pilgrimage of grace. The Hobbit can be characterized as a \\"Christian\\u00a0<i>bildungsroman</i>\\u00a0which equates progress to wisdom gained in the form of a rite of passage.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-Saint_Benedict_Press-1\\">[1]</a>\\u00a0He rescued the dwarves from giant spiders with the magic ring and a short\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_weapons_and_armour#Sting\\">Elven-sword</a>\\u00a0he acquired. He used the ring to sneak around in dangerous places, as well as his wits to smuggle the dwarves out of the elves' prisons. When tensions arose over ownership of the recovered treasure, he tried unsuccessfully to bring the opposing sides to compromise, using the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_objects#Arkenstone\\">Arkenstone</a>, a stolen heirloom jewel, as leverage. This strained his relationship with Thorin, but the two were reconciled at Thorin's deathbed. At the end of the story, Bilbo returned to his home in\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\">the Shire</a>\\u00a0only to find that several of his relatives, believing him to be dead, were trying to claim his home and possessions. In addition to becoming wealthy from his share of the dwarves' treasure, he found that he, like\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adam\\">Adam</a>, had traded respectability for experience and wisdom. At the end, Gandalf proclaims Bilbo is no longer the Hobbit he was. This is certainly true as Bilbo has fully matured. Continuing the pilgrimage theme, a true pilgrimage does not end at the destination, but rather when the wanderer is absolved, blessed, and ready to return home.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-Saint_Benedict_Press-1\\">[1]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"size": "h2", "header_text": "The Lord of the Rings"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": "<p><i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring\\">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>, the first volume of\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, begins with Bilbo's \\"eleventy-first\\" (111th) birthday, 60 years after the beginning of\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\">The Hobbit</a></i>. The main character of the novel is\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\">Frodo Baggins</a>, Bilbo's cousin,<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-2\\">[nb 1]</a></sup>\\u00a0who celebrates his 33rd birthday and legally comes of age on the same day.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>In\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\">T.A.</a>\\u00a02989 (<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_Reckoning\\">S.R.</a>\\u00a01389), Bilbo, a lifelong bachelor, adopted Frodo, the orphaned son of his first cousin\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primula_Brandybuck\\">Primula Brandybuck</a>\\u00a0and his second cousin\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drogo_Baggins\\">Drogo Baggins</a>, and made him his heir. Though Frodo was actually \\"his first\\u00a0<i>and</i>\\u00a0second\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cousin#Cousin_chart\\">cousin once removed</a>\\u00a0either way\\",<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-LotR_party-3\\">[2]</a>\\u00a0the two regarded each other as uncle and nephew.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>All this time Bilbo had kept his magic ring, with no idea of its significance, using it mostly to hide from his obnoxious cousins, the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sackville-Baggins\\">Sackville-Bagginses</a>, when they came to visit.\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\">Gandalf</a>'s investigations revealed it to be the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\">One Ring</a>\\u00a0forged by the Dark Lord\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\">Sauron</a>. The Ring had prolonged Bilbo's life beyond the normal hobbit span, and at 111 he still looked 50. While the Ring did not initially corrupt him as it had its previous owners, it was beginning to affect him; over the years, it had begun to prey on his mind when out of his sight, and he lost sleep and felt \\"thin, sort of\\u00a0<i>stretched</i>\\u00a0\\u2026 like butter that has been scraped over too much bread\\".<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-LotR_party-3\\">[2]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>On the night of his and Frodo's birthday, Bilbo threw himself a party and invited all of the Shire. He signed his home,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bag_End\\">Bag End</a>, and estate over to Frodo. He then gave a farewell address to his neighbors, at the end of which he put on the Ring and vanished from sight. As Bilbo prepared finally to leave the house, he reacted with panic and suspicion when Gandalf tried to persuade him to leave the Ring with Frodo. Bilbo refused to give up the Ring, referring to it as his \\"precious\\" \\u2013 just as Gollum had. Gandalf lost his temper with his old friend and talked some sense into him. Bilbo admitted he would have liked to be rid of the Ring, and he left it behind, becoming the first person to do so voluntarily. He left the Shire that night, and was never seen in\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbiton\\">Hobbiton</a>\\u00a0again.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>His earlier adventure, his\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eccentric_(behavior)\\">eccentric</a>\\u00a0habits as a hobbit, and his sudden disappearance led to the enduring figure of \\"Mad Baggins\\" in hobbit folklore, who disappeared with a flash and a bang and returned with gold and jewels.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Freed of the Ring's power over his senses, Bilbo travelled first to\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\">Rivendell</a>, and then on to visit the dwarves of the Lonely Mountain. After he returned to Rivendell he spent much of the next 17 years living a pleasant life of retirement: eating, sleeping, writing poetry, and working on his memoirs,\\u00a0<i>There and Back Again</i>, known as\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\">The Hobbit</a></i>. He became a scholar of Elven lore, leaving behind the\\u00a0<i>Translations from the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvish_languages_(Middle-earth)\\">Elvish</a></i>, which forms the basis of what is known to us as\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Silmarillion\\">The Silmarillion</a></i>.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>When Frodo and his friends\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee\\">Samwise Gamgee</a>,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\">Peregrin Took</a>\\u00a0stopped in Rivendell on their quest to destroy the Ring, Bilbo was still alive but now visibly aged, the years having caught up with him after he surrendered the Ring. Upon seeing the Ring again, he suddenly tried to take it from Frodo; he returned to his senses when a terrified Frodo backed away, and he broke down in tears, apologizing for bringing the burden of the Ring onto Frodo.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>After the quest to destroy the Ring was fulfilled in\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\">The Return of the King</a></i>, Gandalf and the four Hobbits visited Rivendell on their way back to the Shire and found Bilbo still living there. He gave Frodo a set of manuscripts that later became\\u00a0<i>Translations from the Elvish</i>, and also gave Sam a small bag of gold that represented the last of his share from Smaug's vast hoard. Two years later Bilbo accompanied Gandalf,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\">Elrond</a>,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galadriel\\">Galadriel</a>, and Frodo to the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_Havens\\">Grey Havens</a>, there to take ship for\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tol_Eress%C3%ABa\\">Tol Eress\\u00eba</a>\\u00a0across the sea, on 29th 'September'\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\">T.A.</a>\\u00a03021. He had already celebrated his 131st birthday by this time, surpassing the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Took\\">Old Took</a>\\u00a0by one year and becoming the oldest Hobbit ever in Middle-earth. (The natural lifespan of Hobbits is about 100 years.)<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-4\\">[3]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}]	27	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
13	[{"value": "<p><b>Boromir</b>\\u00a0is a character in\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legendarium\\">legendarium</a>. He appears in the first two volumes of\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>\\u00a0(<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring\\">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\">The Two Towers</a></i>), and is mentioned in the last volume,\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\">The Return of the King</a></i>. He is the heir of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denethor\\">Denethor II</a>\\u00a0(the 26th\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stewards_of_Gondor\\">Ruling Steward</a>of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\">Gondor</a>) and the elder brother of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faramir\\">Faramir</a>. In the course of the story Boromir joins the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Boromir is portrayed as a noble character who believes passionately in the greatness of his kingdom, who would have defended its hosts to the last. Boromir's great stamina and physical strength, together with a forceful and commanding personality, made him a widely admired commander in Gondor's army: he was made Captain of the White Tower, and quickly became Captain-General, also bearing the title High Warden of the White Tower. He was also heir apparent to the Stewardship. Boromir led many successful forays against\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\">Sauron</a>'s forces, prior to his journey north to\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\">Rivendell</a>, which brought him great esteem in the eyes of his father, Denethor.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"size": "h2", "header_text": "Literature"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": "<p>Boromir, as a character, is portrayed as having been born in the year 2978 of the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\">Third Age</a>\\u00a0to\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denethor_II\\">Denethor II</a>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finduilas_of_Dol_Amroth\\">Finduilas</a>, daughter of Adrahil of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dol_Amroth\\">Dol Amroth</a>. His younger brother,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faramir\\">Faramir</a>, was born in the year\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\">T.A.</a>\\u00a02983. The following year, Denethor became Steward of Gondor, succeeding his father,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ecthelion_II\\">Ecthelion II</a>. Boromir simultaneously became heir apparent, inheriting the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horn_of_Gondor\\">Horn of Gondor</a>.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Boromir was named after the son of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denethor_I\\">Denethor I</a>, who was Steward around 500 years before the War of the Ring. The\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir_(Steward)\\">first Boromir</a>\\u00a0was known as a great captain who cleared\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ithilien\\">Ithilien</a>\\u00a0of orcs of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\">Mordor</a>\\u00a0and was feared even by the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witch-king\\">Witch-king</a>\\u00a0himself. Thus there were high expectations for Boromir the son of Denethor II.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"text": "It is a strange fate that we should suffer so much fear and doubt over so small a thing. Such a little thing.", "attribute_name": "Boromir", "attribute_group": ""}, "type": "blockquote"}, {"value": "<p>When Boromir's mother Finduilas died (<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\">T.A.</a>\\u00a02988), he was aged only 10. Denethor became sombre, cold and detached from his family. As their father withdrew, the relationship between Faramir and Boromir grew closer and greater in love. Denethor always favoured Boromir over Faramir\\u2014Denethor loved Boromir \\"too much, perhaps; the more so because they were unlike\\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir#cite_note-1\\">[1]</a>\\u2014but this caused no rivalry between the two brothers. Boromir always protected and helped Faramir. Boromir was judged to be the more daring one, as well as the more fearless.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>In response to prophetic dreams that came to Faramir and later to himself, Boromir claimed the quest of riding to\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\">Rivendell</a>\\u00a0from\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith\\">Minas Tirith</a>\\u00a0in\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\">T.A.</a>\\u00a03018. His journey lasted a hundred and eleven days, and he travelled through \\"roads forgotten\\" to reach Rivendell, though, as he said, \\"few knew where it lay\\".<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir#cite_note-2\\">[2]</a>\\u00a0Boromir lost his horse halfway along, while crossing the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greyflood\\">Greyflood</a>at the ruined city of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tharbad\\">Tharbad</a>\\u00a0where the bridge was broken. He had to travel the remaining way on foot<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir#cite_note-3\\">[3]</a>\\u00a0and barely arrived in time for the Council of Elrond. (Tolkien wrote of Boromir's journey that \\"the courage and hardihood required is not fully recognized in the narrative\\".)<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir#cite_note-4\\">[4]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}]	6	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
37	[{"value": "<p><b>Gandalf</b>\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English\\">/\\u02c8\\u0261\\u00e6nd\\u0251\\u02d0lf/</a><sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf#cite_note-2\\">[2]</a></sup>\\u00a0is a\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Character_(arts)\\">fictional character</a>\\u00a0and one of the protagonists in\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s novels\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\">The Hobbit</a></i>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. He is a\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\">wizard</a>, member of the\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\">Istari</a></i>\\u00a0order, as well as leader of the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>\\u00a0and the army of the West. In\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, he is initially known as\\u00a0<b>Gandalf the Grey</b>, but returns from death as\\u00a0<b>Gandalf the White</b>.</p><p></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"size": "h2", "header_text": "The Fellowship of the Ring"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": "<p>Returning to\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\">the Shire</a>, in\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\">T.A.</a>\\u00a03018, Gandalf confirmed his suspicions by throwing\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\">the Ring</a>\\u00a0into\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\">Frodo</a>'s hearth-fire and reading the writing that appeared on\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring#Appearance\\">the Ring's surface</a>. He told Frodo the full history of the Ring, and urged him to take the Ring to\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\">Rivendell</a>; for he would be in grave danger if he stayed in the Shire. Gandalf said he would attempt to return for Frodo's 50th birthday party, in order to accompany him on the road thereafter; and that meanwhile Frodo should arrange to leave quietly, as the servants of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\">Sauron</a>\\u00a0would be searching for him.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Outside the Shire, Gandalf encountered\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radagast_the_Brown\\">Radagast the Brown</a>, another of the Istari, who brought the news that the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl\\">Nazg\\u00fbl</a>\\u00a0had ridden forth and crossed the River\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anduin\\">Anduin</a>\\u2014and a request from\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\">Saruman</a>\\u00a0that Gandalf come to\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isengard\\">Isengard</a>. Gandalf left a\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_objects#Gandalf.27s_letter\\">letter</a>\\u00a0to Frodo (urging his immediate departure) with\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barliman_Butterbur\\">Barliman Butterbur</a>\\u00a0at the inn in\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bree_(Middle-earth)\\">Bree</a>, and headed towards Isengard. There Saruman revealed his true colours, urging Gandalf to help him obtain the Ring for his own use. Gandalf refused, and Saruman imprisoned him at the top of the tower of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthanc\\">Orthanc</a>. Eventually Gandalf was rescued by\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gwaihir\\">Gwaihir</a>\\u00a0the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eagle_(Middle-earth)\\">Eagle</a>.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Gwaihir set Gandalf down in\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\">Rohan</a>, where Gandalf appealed to King\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C3%A9oden\\">Th\\u00e9oden</a>\\u00a0for a horse. Th\\u00e9oden, under the malign influence of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr%C3%ADma_Wormtongue\\">Gr\\u00edma Wormtongue</a>, Saruman's spy, told Gandalf to take any horse he pleased, but to leave quickly. It was then that Gandalf met the great horse\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shadowfax_(Middle-earth)\\">Shadowfax</a>, one of the\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mearas\\">mearas</a></i>, who would be his mount and companion for most of the rest of the war. Gandalf pursued the horse for two days<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf#cite_note-AppB-6\\">[6]</a>\\u00a0before Shadowfax permitted Gandalf to ride him. Gandalf then rode hard for the Shire, but did not reach it until Frodo had already set out. Knowing that Frodo and his companions would be heading for Rivendell, Gandalf began to make his own way there. He learned at Bree that the Hobbits had fallen in with\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\">Aragorn</a>. He faced the Nazg\\u00fbl at\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weathertop\\">Weathertop</a>\\u00a0but escaped after an all-night battle, drawing four of them northward. Frodo, Aragorn and company faced the remaining five on Weathertop a few nights later. Gandalf reached Rivendell just before Frodo's arrival.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>In Rivendell, Gandalf helped\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\">Elrond</a>\\u00a0drive off the Nazg\\u00fbl pursuing Frodo and played a great part in the following\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_Elrond\\">council</a>\\u00a0as the only person who knew the full history of the Ring. He also revealed that Saruman had betrayed them and was in league with Sauron. When it was decided that the Ring had to be destroyed, Gandalf volunteered to accompany Frodo\\u2014now the Ring-bearer\\u2014in his quest. He also persuaded Elrond to let Frodo's cousins\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\">Merry</a>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\">Pippin</a>\\u00a0join the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\">Fellowship</a>.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Taking charge of the Fellowship (comprising nine representatives of the free hostss of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\">Middle-earth</a>, \\"set against the Nine Riders\\"), Gandalf and Aragorn led the Hobbits and their companions south. After an unsuccessful attempt to cross Mount\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caradhras\\">Caradhras</a>\\u00a0in winter, they crossed\\u00a0<i>under</i>\\u00a0the mountains through the Mines of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moria_(Middle-earth)\\">Moria</a>, though only\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gimli_(Middle-earth)\\">Gimli</a>\\u00a0the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwarf_(Middle-earth)\\">Dwarf</a>\\u00a0was enthusiastic about that route. In Moria, they discovered that the Dwarf colony established there earlier had been overrun by\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\">Orcs</a>. The Fellowship fought with the Orcs and Trolls of Moria and escaped them.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>At the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bridge_of_Khazad-d%C3%BBm\\">Bridge of Khazad-d\\u00fbm</a>, they encountered \\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balrog#Durin.27s_Bane\\">Durin's Bane</a>,\\" a fearsome\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balrog\\">Balrog</a>\\u00a0from ancient times. Gandalf faced the Balrog to enable the others to escape. After a brief exchange of blows, Gandalf broke the bridge beneath the Balrog with his\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magic_(Middle-earth)#Magic_items\\">staff</a>. As the Balrog fell, it wrapped its whip around Gandalf's legs, dragging him over the edge. As his friends looked on in horror, Gandalf fell into the abyss, crying \\"Fly, you fools!\\" as he went.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>After a long fall, Gandalf and the Balrog crashed into a deep subterranean lake far under Moria. Gandalf pursued the Balrog through the tunnels for eight days until they climbed to the peak of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minor_places_in_Middle-earth#Celebdil\\">Zirakzigil</a>. Here they fought for two days and nights. In the end, the Balrog was defeated and cast down onto the mountainside. Gandalf himself died shortly afterwards, and his body lay on the peak while his spirit travelled \\"out of thought and time\\".</p>", "type": "paragraph"}]	26	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
27	[{"value": "<p><b>Saruman the White</b>\\u00a0is a fictional character and a major antagonist in\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s fantasy novel\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. He is leader of the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\">Istari</a>, wizards sent to\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\">Middle-earth</a>\\u00a0in human form by the godlike\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vala_(Middle-earth)\\">Valar</a>\\u00a0to challenge\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\">Sauron</a>, the main antagonist of the novel, but eventually he desires Sauron's power for himself and tries to take over Middle-earth by force. His schemes feature prominently in the second volume,\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\">The Two Towers</a></i>, and at the end of the third volume,\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\">The Return of the King</a></i>. His earlier history is given briefly in the posthumously published\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Silmarillion\\">The Silmarillion</a></i>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unfinished_Tales\\">Unfinished Tales</a></i>.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Saruman is one of several characters in the book illustrating the corruption of power; his desire for knowledge and order leads to his fall, and he rejects the chance of redemption when it is offered. The name\\u00a0<i>Saruman</i>\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA\\">[\\u02c8saruman]</a>\\u00a0means \\"man of experience\\" in the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercian_(Anglo-Saxon)\\">Mercian dialect</a>\\u00a0of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_English_language\\">Anglo-Saxon</a>;<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-1\\">[1]</a>\\u00a0he serves as an example of technology and modernity being overthrown by forces more in tune with nature. Saruman is represented by a white hand.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"size": "h2", "header_text": "Characterisation"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": "<p>Tolkien described Saruman at the time of\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>\\u00a0as having a long face and a high forehead, \\"...he had deep darkling eyes ... His hair and beard were white, but strands of black still showed around his lips and ears.\\"<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Orthanc-24\\">[24]</a></sup>\\u00a0His hair is elsewhere described as having been black when he first arrived in Middle-earth. He is referred to as 'Saruman the White' and is said to have originally worn white robes, but on his first entry in\\u00a0<i>The Fellowship of the Ring</i>\\u00a0they instead appear to be \\"woven from all colours [, they] shimmered and changed hue so that the eye was bewildered\\" and he names himself 'Saruman of Many Colours'.<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Saru1-25\\">[25]</a></sup></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "https://youtu.be/TQq4LjSF2rc", "type": "embed"}, {"value": "<p>The power of Saruman's voice is noted throughout the book. Jonathan Evans calls the characterization of Saruman in the chapter\\u00a0<i>The Voice of Saruman</i>\\u00a0a \\"tour de force\\".<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Evans-20\\">[20]</a>\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Sale\\">Roger Sale</a>\\u00a0says of the same chapter that \\"Tolkien valiantly tried to do something worth doing which he simply cannot bring off.\\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-26\\">[26]</a>\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Shippey\\">Tom Shippey</a>\\u00a0writes that \\"Saruman talks like a politician ... No other character in Middle-earth has Saruman's trick of balancing phrases against each other so that incompatibles are resolved, and none comes out with words as empty as 'deploring', 'ultimate', worst of all, 'real'. What is 'real change'?\\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-elcoun-27\\">[27]</a>Shippey contrasts this modern speech pattern with the archaic stoicism and directness that Tolkien employs for other characters such as the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwarf_(Middle-earth)\\">Dwarven</a>\\u00a0King\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D%C3%A1in_II_Ironfoot\\">D\\u00e1in</a>, which Shippey believes represent Tolkien's view of heroism in the mould of\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beowulf\\">Beowulf</a></i>.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-elcoun-27\\">[27]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>After the defeat of his armies, having been caught in the betrayal of Sauron, Saruman is offered refuge by Gandalf, in return for his aid, but having chosen his path, is unable to turn from it.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Spacks2-28\\">[28]</a>\\u00a0Evans has compared the character of Saruman to that of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satan\\">Satan</a>\\u00a0in\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Milton\\">John Milton</a>'s\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paradise_Lost\\">Paradise Lost</a></i>\\u00a0in his use of rhetoric and in this final refusal of redemption, \\"conquered by pride and hatred\\".<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Evans-20\\">[20]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}]	18	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
33	[{"value": "<p><b>Sauron</b>,\\u00a0pronounced\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA\\">[\\u02c8sa\\u028ar\\u0254n]</a>,<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-1\\">[1]</a></sup>\\u00a0is the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Title_character\\">title character</a><sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-3\\">[note 1]</a></sup>\\u00a0and main antagonist of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. In the same work, he is identified as the\\u00a0<b>Necromancer</b>, mentioned in Tolkien's earlier novel\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\">The Hobbit</a></i>. In Tolkien's\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Silmarillion\\">The Silmarillion</a></i>\\u00a0(published posthumously by Tolkien's son\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christopher_Tolkien\\">Christopher Tolkien</a>),<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-4\\">[3]</a></sup>\\u00a0he is also described as the chief lieutenant of the first\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dark_Lord_(fiction)\\">Dark Lord</a>,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morgoth\\">Morgoth</a>. Tolkien noted that the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainur_(Middle-earth)\\">\\"angelic\\" powers of his constructed myth</a>\\u00a0\\"were capable of many degrees of error and failing\\", but by far the worst was \\"the absolute\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satan\\">Satanic</a>\\u00a0rebellion and evil of Morgoth and his satellite Sauron\\".<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-5\\">[4]</a></sup></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"size": "h2", "header_text": "Biography"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": {"size": "h3", "header_text": "Before creation of the world"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": "<p>The\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainulindal%C3%AB\\">Ainulindal\\u00eb</a></i>, the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creation_myth\\">cosmological myth</a>\\u00a0prefixed to\\u00a0<i>The Silmarillion</i>, explains how the supreme being\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eru_Il%C3%BAvatar\\">Eru</a>\\u00a0initiated his creation by bringing into being innumerable spirits, \\"the offspring of his thought\\", who were with him before anything else had been made. The being later known as Sauron originated as an \\"immortal (angelic) spirit\\".<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters243-6\\">[5]</a></sup>\\u00a0In his origin, Sauron therefore perceived the Creator directly. As Tolkien noted: \\"Sauron could not, of course, be a 'sincere'\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atheist\\">atheist</a>. Though one of the minor spirits created before the world, he knew Eru, according to his measure.\\"<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-ME-ref.7CMR.7Cp._397-7\\">[6]</a></sup></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>In the terminology of Tolkien's\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_language\\">invented language</a>\\u00a0of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quenya\\">Quenya</a>, these angelic spirits were called\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainur_(Middle-earth)\\">Ainur</a>. Those who entered the physical world were called\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vala_(Middle-earth)\\">Valar</a>, especially the most powerful ones. The (mostly) lesser beings who entered the world, of whom Sauron was one, were called\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maia_(Middle-earth)\\">Maiar</a>. In Tolkien's letters, the author noted that Sauron \\"was of course a '<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divinity\\">divine</a>' person (in the terms of this mythology; a lesser member of the race of Valar)\\".<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters205-8\\">[7]</a>\\u00a0Tolkien noted that he was of a \\"far higher order\\" than the Maiar who later came to Middle-earth as the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\">Wizards</a>\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\">Gandalf</a>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\">Saruman</a>.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters243fn-9\\">[8]</a>\\u00a0As created by Eru, the Ainur were all good and uncorrupt, as\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\">Elrond</a>\\u00a0stated in\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>: \\"Nothing is evil in the beginning. Even Sauron was not so.\\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-10\\">[9]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Rebellion originated with the Vala\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morgoth\\">Melkor</a>. According to a story meant as a parable of events beyond\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\">Elvish</a>\\u00a0comprehension,<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-11\\">[10]</a>\\u00a0Eru let his spirit-children perform a great Music, the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainulindal%C3%AB\\">Music of the Ainur</a>, developing a theme revealed by Eru himself. For a while the cosmic choir made wondrous music, but then Melkor tried to increase his own glory by weaving into his song thoughts and ideas that were not in accordance with the original theme. \\"Straightway discord arose around him, and many that sang nigh him grew despondent ... but some began to attune their music to his rather than to the thought which they had at first.\\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-12\\">[11]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>The discord Melkor created would have dire consequences, as this singing was a kind of template for the world: \\"The evils of the world were not at first in the great Theme, but entered with the discords of Melkor.\\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-13\\">[12]</a>\\u00a0However, \\"Sauron was not a beginner of discord; and he probably knew more of the Music than did Melkor, whose mind had always been filled with his own plans and devices.\\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-14\\">[13]</a>\\u00a0Apparently Sauron was not even one of the spirits that immediately began to attune their music to that of Melkor, since it is noted elsewhere that his fall occurred later (<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#Sauron.27s_fall\\">see below</a>).</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>The cosmic Music now represented the conflict between\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Good_and_evil\\">good and evil</a>. Finally, Eru abruptly brought the Song of Creation to an end. To show the spirits, faithful or otherwise, what they had done, Eru gave independent being to the now-marred Music. This resulted in the manifestation of the material World,\\u00a0<i>E\\u00e4</i>, where the drama of good and evil would play out and be resolved.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"size": "h3", "header_text": "First Age"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": "<p>In the terminology of Tolkien's\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_language\\">invented language</a>\\u00a0of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quenya\\">Quenya</a>, these angelic spirits were called\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainur_(Middle-earth)\\">Ainur</a>. Those who entered the physical world were called\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vala_(Middle-earth)\\">Valar</a>, especially the most powerful ones. The (mostly) lesser beings who entered the world, of whom Sauron was one, were called\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maia_(Middle-earth)\\">Maiar</a>. In Tolkien's letters, the author noted that Sauron \\"was of course a '<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divinity\\">divine</a>' person (in the terms of this mythology; a lesser member of the race of Valar)\\".<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters205-8\\">[7]</a>\\u00a0Tolkien noted that he was of a \\"far higher order\\" than the Maiar who later came to Middle-earth as the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\">Wizards</a>\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\">Gandalf</a>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\">Saruman</a>.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters243fn-9\\">[8]</a>\\u00a0As created by Eru, the Ainur were all good and uncorrupt, as\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\">Elrond</a>\\u00a0stated in\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>: \\"Nothing is evil in the beginning. Even Sauron was not so.\\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-10\\">[9]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"size": "h4", "header_text": "Sauron's fall"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": "<p>Melkor opposed the other Valar, who remained faithful to Eru and tried to carry out the Creator's designs. Within the larger universe, they eventually focused on developing the world of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arda_(Middle-earth)\\">Arda</a>\\u00a0(Earth, or the entire solar system). Around this time, Sauron fell victim to Melkor's corrupting influence: \\"In the beginning of Arda, Melkor seduced him to his allegiance.\\"<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-18\\">[17]</a></sup></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>As for Sauron's motives, Tolkien noted that \\"it had been his virtue (and therefore also the cause of his fall ...) that he loved order and coordination, and disliked all confusion and wasteful friction\\". Thus \\"it was the apparent will and power of Melkor to effect his designs quickly and masterfully that had first attracted Sauron to him\\".<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-19\\">[18]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>For a while, Sauron apparently kept up the pretence that he was a faithful servant of the Valar, all the while feeding Melkor information about their doings. Thus, when the Valar made\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almaren\\">Almaren</a>\\u00a0as their first physical abode in the world, \\"Melkor knew of all that was done; for even then he had secret friends and spies among the Maiar whom he had converted to his cause, and of these the chief, as after became known, was Sauron.\\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-ME-ref.7CMR.7Cp._52-15\\">[14]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Melkor soon destroyed Almaren, and the Valar established a new abode in the Uttermost West: the Blessed Realm of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valinor\\">Valinor</a>. They still did not perceive Sauron's treachery, for he too became \\"a being of Valinor\\".<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters151-20\\">[19]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>At some point, Sauron left the Blessed Realm and went to\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\">Middle-earth</a>, the central continent of Arda, where Melkor had established his stronghold. In one text, Tolkien wrote of Sauron that \\"in Valinor he had dwelt among the hosts of the gods, but there Morgoth had drawn him to evil and to his service\\".<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-21\\">[20]</a>\\u00a0Sauron deserted his service to the Valar and openly joined their great enemy: \\"Because of his admiration of Strength he had become a follower of Morgoth and fell with him down into the depths of evil.\\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters243fn-9\\">[8]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"size": "h4", "header_text": "The Lieutenant of Melkor"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": "<p>After joining his new master in Middle-earth, Sauron proved to be a devoted and capable servant: \\"While Morgoth still stood, Sauron did not seek his own supremacy, but worked and schemed for another, desiring the triumph of Melkor, whom in the beginning he had adored. He thus was often able to achieve things, first conceived by Melkor, which his master did not or could not complete in the furious haste of his malice.\\"<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-ME-ref.7CMR.7Cp._420-22\\">[21]</a></sup>\\u00a0\\"In all the deeds of Melkor the Morgoth upon Arda, in his vast works and in the deceits of his cunning, Sauron had a part.\\"<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-23\\">[22]</a></sup></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>In chapter three of\\u00a0<i>The Silmarillion</i>, Tolkien writes that by the time the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\">Elves</a>\\u00a0awoke in the world, Sauron had become Melkor's lieutenant and was given command over the newly built stronghold of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angband\\">Angband</a>. To protect the Elves, the Valar made war on Melkor and captured him, but could not find Sauron.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Thus, \\"when Melkor was made captive, Sauron escaped and lay hid in Middle-earth; and it can in this way be understood how the breeding of the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\">Orcs</a>\\u00a0(no doubt already begun) went on with increasing speed\\". In the Blessed Realm, Melkor feigned reform, but eventually escaped back to Middle-earth, holding the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silmaril\\">Silmarils</a>\\u00a0of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F%C3%ABanor\\">F\\u00ebanor</a>. By then, Sauron had \\"secretly repaired Angband for the help of his Master when he returned; and there the dark places underground were already manned with hosts of the Orcs before Melkor came back at last, as Morgoth the Black Enemy\\".<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-24\\">[23]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Shortly after the return of Morgoth, the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noldor\\">Noldorin</a>\\u00a0Elves also left the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blessed_Realm_of_Valinor\\">Blessed Realm of Valinor</a>\\u00a0in the Uttermost West, against the counsel of the Valar, to wage war on Morgoth, who had stolen the Silmarils. In that war, Sauron served as Morgoth's chief lieutenant, surpassing all others in rank, such as\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gothmog\\">Gothmog</a>, the Lord of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balrog\\">Balrogs</a>. Known as\\u00a0<b>Gorthaur the Cruel</b>, Sauron was at that time a master of illusions and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shapeshifting\\">shapeshifting</a>;\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Werewolf_(Middle-earth)\\">werewolves</a>\\u00a0and vampires were his servants, chief among them\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Draugluin\\">Draugluin</a>, Father of Werewolves, and his vampire herald\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thuringwethil\\">Thuringwethil</a>.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>When Morgoth left Angband to corrupt the newly discovered\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man_(Middle-earth)\\">Men</a>, Sauron directed the war against the Elves. He conquered the Elvish island of Tol Sirion and its watchtower\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith_(First_Age)\\">Minas Tirith</a>, so that it became known as\\u00a0<i>Tol-in-Gaurhoth,</i>\\u00a0the Isle of Werewolves.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}]	16	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
32	[{"value": "<p><b>Shelob</b>\\u00a0is a fictional\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spider_(Middle-earth)\\">giant spider</a>\\u00a0from\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\">Middle-earth</a>\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legendarium\\">legendarium</a>. She appears at the end of the fourth book, second volume (<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\">The Two Towers</a></i>), of\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. Her lair lies in\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cirith_Ungol\\">Cirith Ungol</a>\\u00a0(\\"the pass of the spider\\") leading into\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\">Mordor</a>.\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gollum\\">Gollum</a>\\u00a0deliberately leads\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\">Frodo Baggins</a>\\u00a0there in hopes of recovering the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\">One Ring</a>\\u00a0when Shelob attacks Frodo. The plan is foiled when\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee\\">Samwise Gamgee</a>\\u00a0greatly injures Shelob with Frodo's Elvish dagger,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sting_(Middle-earth)\\">Sting</a>, and the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phial_of_Galadriel\\">Phial of Galadriel</a>.</p><p></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"size": "h2", "header_text": "Literature"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": "<p>Shelob was an \\"evil thing in spider form...[the] last child of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ungoliant\\">Ungoliant</a>\\u00a0to trouble the unhappy world\\",<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelob#cite_note-TTT_book_4_ch_9-1\\">[1]</a></sup>\\u00a0living high in the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ephel_D%C3%BAath\\">Ephel D\\u00faath</a>\\u00a0mountains on the borders of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\">Mordor</a>. There are numerous references to her predating the events of\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>\\u00a0by many ages. Although she resided in Mordor and was unrepentantly evil, she was independent of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\">Sauron</a>\\u00a0and his influence.<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelob#cite_note-2\\">[2]</a></sup></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>This creature makes her first appearance in the chapter \\"The Stairs of Cirith Ungol\\", though she is formally introduced in the next chapter \\"Shelob's Lair\\" where the author says \\"But still she was there, who was there before Sauron, and before the first stone of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barad-d%C3%BBr\\">Barad-d\\u00fbr</a>; and she served none but herself, drinking the blood of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\">Elves</a>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man_(Middle-earth)\\">Men</a>, bloated and grown fat with endless brooding on her feasts, weaving webs of shadow; for all living things were her food, and her vomit darkness\\". Her descendants include the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spider_(Middle-earth)\\">Giant Spiders</a>\\u00a0defeated by\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins\\">Bilbo Baggins</a>\\u00a0in\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\">The Hobbit</a></i>.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Shelob's lair was\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Torech_Ungol\\">Torech Ungol</a>, below Cirith Ungol (\\"Pass of the Spider\\"), along the path that\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sam_Gamgee\\">Sam Gamgee</a>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\">Frodo Baggins</a>\\u00a0took into Mordor, where Shelob had encountered Gollum during his previous trip to Mordor, and he apparently worshipped her. The\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\">Orcs</a>\\u00a0of the Tower of Cirith Ungol called her \\"Shelob the Great\\" and \\"Her Ladyship\\", and referred to Gollum as \\"Her Sneak\\". Sauron himself was aware of her existence, but left her alone, as a useful guard on the pass, and occasionally fed prisoners to her. In the story, Gollum led the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit\\">Hobbits</a>\\u00a0into her lair to himself recover the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\">One Ring</a>\\u00a0after she consumed them. She cornered them; but Frodo used the Phial of Galadriel's light to drive her off, and used Sting to cut the webs blocking the tunnel. Gollum waylaid the pair and tried to strangle Sam, while Shelob paralysed Frodo; whereafter Sam fought off Gollum and then wielded Sting against Shelob. Seeking to crush Sam, she instead impaled herself upon\\u00a0<i>Sting</i>; and was nearly blinded by the Phial of Galadriel; whereupon she fled. Thinking Frodo dead, Sam took the Ring from his friend and left his body behind, but discovered by listening to a pair of Orcs that Frodo was alive but senseless, under a minor influence of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Venom\\">venom</a>.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "https://youtu.be/pA0ffVBw584", "type": "embed"}, {"value": {"size": "h2", "header_text": "Name"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": "<p>As Tolkien admitted in a letter to his son, Shelob \\"is of course only 'she + lob',\\" -\\u00a0<i>lob</i>\\u00a0being an archaic English word for spider, influenced by\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_English\\">Old English</a>\\u00a0<i>loppe</i>\\u00a0or \\"spider\\". The word is not related to \\"cob\\" nor \\"cobweb\\".\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_English\\">Old English</a>\\u00a0<i>attercoppe</i>\\u00a0(meaning \\"spider\\") is derived from\\u00a0<i>atter</i>\\u00a0meaning \\"poison\\" and\\u00a0<i>coppe</i>\\u00a0meaning \\"head\\"; Tolkien used \\"attercop\\" as well as \\"cob\\" and \\"lob\\" in\\u00a0<i>The Hobbit</i>, where Bilbo Baggins sings songs taunting the giant spiders in Mirkwood: \\"Attercop, Attercop, Old Tomnoddy\\" and \\"Lazy Lob and Crazy Cob\\".<sup>[<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\\">citation needed</a></i>]</sup></p>", "type": "paragraph"}]	23	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
29	[{"value": "<p><b>Th\\u00e9oden</b>\\u00a0is a fictional character in\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fantasy\\">fantasy</a>\\u00a0novel,\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. The King of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\">Rohan</a>, he appears as a major supporting character in\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\">The Two Towers</a></i>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\">The Return of the King</a></i>.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"size": "h2", "header_text": "Appearances"}, "type": "header"}, {"value": "<p>Th\\u00e9oden is introduced in\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\">The Two Towers</a></i>, the second volume of\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>, as the King of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\">Rohan</a>. By the time of the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_of_the_Ring\\">War of the Ring</a>, Th\\u00e9oden had grown weak with age, and was largely controlled by his chief advisor\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr%C3%ADma\\">Gr\\u00edma</a>\\u00a0(or\\u00a0<i>Wormtongue</i>\\u00a0as most others in the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riddermark\\">Riddermark</a>\\u00a0called him), who was secretly in the employ of the corrupt wizard\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\">Saruman</a>. In\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unfinished_Tales\\">Unfinished Tales</a></i>, it is implied that the failure of the king's health was \\"...induced or increased by subtle poisons, administered by Gr\\u00edma\\".<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C3%A9oden#cite_note-1\\">[1]</a></sup>\\u00a0As Th\\u00e9oden sat powerless, Rohan was troubled by\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\">Orcs</a>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dunlendings\\">Dunlendings</a>, who operated under the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Will_(philosophy)\\">will</a>\\u00a0of Saruman, ruling from\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isengard\\">Isengard</a>.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>When his son\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C3%A9odred\\">Th\\u00e9odred</a>\\u00a0was mortally wounded at a\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fords_of_Isen#First_Battle_of_the_Fords_of_Isen\\">battle at the Fords of Isen</a>, Th\\u00e9oden's nephew\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89omer\\">\\u00c9omer</a>\\u00a0became his heir. However, \\u00c9omer was out of favour with Wormtongue, who eventually had him arrested.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>When\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\">Gandalf the White</a>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\">Aragorn</a>, along with Legolas and Gimli, appeared before him in\\u00a0<i>The Two Towers</i>, Th\\u00e9oden initially rebuffed the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Istari\\">wizard</a>'s advice to oppose Saruman. When Gandalf revealed Wormtongue for what he was, however, Th\\u00e9oden returned to his senses. He restored his nephew, took up his sword\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weapons_of_Middle-earth#Herugrim\\">Herugrim</a>, and in spite of his age, led the Riders of Rohan into the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_the_Hornburg\\">Battle of the Hornburg</a>. After this he became known as Th\\u00e9oden Ednew, the Renewed.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>In\\u00a0<i>The Return of the King</i>, Th\\u00e9oden led the Rohirrim to the aid of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\">Gondor</a>\\u00a0at the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_the_Pelennor_Fields\\">Battle of the Pelennor Fields</a>. In that battle he routed the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harad\\">Harad</a>\\u00a0cavalry, personally killing their chieftain and banner-bearer in the process. He challenged the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witch-king_of_Angmar\\">Witch-king of Angmar</a>, the leader of the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl\\">Nazg\\u00fbl</a>, and was mortally wounded when his horse\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snowmane\\">Snowmane</a>\\u00a0fell upon him. He was avenged by his niece\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn\\">\\u00c9owyn</a>\\u00a0and the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit\\">hobbit</a>\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\">Meriadoc \\"Merry\\" Brandybuck</a>, who had ridden to war in secret; together, they destroyed the Witch-king. Before mustering the Rohirrim to ride to Gondor's aid, Th\\u00e9oden enlisted Merry into his army, but did not let the hobbit ride into\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_the_Pelennor_Fields\\">battle at Pelennor</a>. In his last moments, he bid farewell to Merry and appointed \\u00c9omer the next king.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Th\\u00e9oden's body lay in\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith\\">Minas Tirith</a>\\u00a0until it was buried in Rohan after the defeat of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\">Sauron</a>. He was the last of the Second Line of the kings, judging from direct descent from\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eorl_the_Young\\">Eorl the Young</a>.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}]	20	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
30	[{"value": "<p><b>Treebeard</b>\\u00a0(<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\">Sindarin</a>:\\u00a0<i>Fangorn</i>) is a fictional character from\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\">Middle-earth</a>\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tolkien%27s_legendarium\\">fantasy writings</a>. The eldest of the species of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ent\\">Ents</a>, he is said to live in the ancient\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fangorn\\">Forest of Fangorn</a>\\u00a0and stands fourteen feet (4 m) in height. He is treelike in appearance, with leafy hair and a rigid structure.<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\">[1]</a></sup>\\u00a0His home of Fangorn Forest lies next to\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isengard\\">Isengard</a>, where\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\">Saruman the White</a>\\u00a0resides. Treebeard's motto is \\"Do not be hasty.\\"<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\">[1]</a></sup></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>In\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\">The Two Towers</a></i>\\u00a0he meets with\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\">Peregrin Took</a>, two\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit\\">Hobbits</a>\\u00a0of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\">the Shire</a>\\u00a0known also as Merry and Pippin.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\">[1]</a>\\u00a0Treebeard is known to have a strong hatred of\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\">Orcs</a>, and, after Saruman's betrayal of the Ents, of Saruman as well.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\">[1]</a><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-AofAW2-2\\">[2]</a>\\u00a0During his initial encounter with the two hobbits, he is so agitated that he misidentifies them as orc spies. He then carries them to the white wizard.</p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Spirits were sent by\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eru_Il%C3%BAvatar\\">Eru Il\\u00favatar</a>\\u00a0to inhabit the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree\\">trees</a>, which the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vala_(Middle-earth)\\">Vala</a>\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yavanna\\">Yavanna</a>\\u00a0had created along with other plants or\\u00a0<i><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_plants\\">olvar</a></i>. The Vala longed for their protection since\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morgoth\\">Morgoth</a>\\u00a0or\\u00a0<i>Melkor</i>\\u00a0was destroying the trees and olvar, which could not defend themselves from him. The Ents were created by Il\\u00favatar at the behest of Yavanna as the\\u00a0<i>Shepherds of the Forest</i>\\u00a0or\\u00a0<i>Tree-herders</i>.\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ent#Entwives\\">Entwives</a>\\u00a0were also created for the Ents, but, in the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Age\\">Second Age</a>, were driven out by\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\">Sauron</a>.<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\">[1]</a></sup><sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-AofAW2-2\\">[2]</a></sup><sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-3\\">[3]</a></sup></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>Treebeard is the oldest of three remaining original Ents.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\">[1]</a><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TBLOTR-4\\">[4]</a>\\u00a0He is said to have once roamed all of the forests in Middle-earth, which included the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misty_Mountains\\">Misty Mountains</a>,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirkwood\\">Mirkwood</a>,\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\">Mordor</a>, and the Blue Mountains. After the loss of the Entwives by the end of the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\">Third Age</a>, he and the remaining Ents dwelt in the Forest of Fangorn. This led the remaining Ents into isolation and all information from the outside world was cut off.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\">[1]</a>\\u00a0The arrival of Merry and Pippin shifted Treebeard's attention to take action against Saruman for hacking down his trees. He led the Ents to war against Saruman and his Orcs. Treebeard later realised that while Saruman had learned much from him, the Wizard had shared no useful information of his own.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\">[1]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": {"text": "A large Man-like figure, at least fourteen foot high, very sturdy, with a tall head, and hardly any neck. Whether it was clad in stuff like green and grey bark, or whether that was its hide, was difficult to say. Arms, at a short distance from the trunk, were not wrinkled, but covered with a brown smooth skin. The large feet had seven toes each. Grey beard, deep brown eyes, shot with a green light.", "attribute_name": "JRR Tolkien", "attribute_group": ""}, "type": "blockquote"}, {"value": "<p>Treebeard had been friends with Saruman. It is described in\\u00a0<i>The Two Towers</i>\\u00a0that Saruman visited Treebeard in Fangorn Forest and had talked with him on various subjects of concern. Saruman gathered information from Treebeard about the Forest of Fangorn; its intertwining paths were of particular concern to him.<sup><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\">[1]</a></sup></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "<p>After Merry and Pippin's meeting with Treebeard, Treebeard called an\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entmoot\\">Entmoot</a>, which lasted three days, to decide to call an attack on Isengard and Saruman.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\">[1]</a><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-AofAW2-2\\">[2]</a><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TBLOTR-4\\">[4]</a>\\u00a0Since\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leaflock\\">Leaflock</a>\\u00a0and\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skinbark\\">Skinbark</a>\\u00a0were the oldest of the Ents along with Treebeard, they refused to fight, however, Treebeard thought he was going to his doom during \\"the last march of the Ents.\\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\">[1]</a><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TBLOTR-4\\">[4]</a>\\u00a0Treebeard hoped that some of the younger Ents would come instead of just the two, and, during the night he spread the word. They later launched an assault on Isengard.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\">[1]</a><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-AofAW2-2\\">[2]</a><a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TBLOTR-4\\">[4]</a></p>", "type": "paragraph"}, {"value": "https://youtu.be/BbV2Hr0qRdo", "type": "embed"}, {"value": "<p>After Treebeard ordered the Ents to march to Isengard, the Ents felled Saruman's walls and destroyed every object in and around Isengard; the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthanc\\">Tower of Orthanc</a>\\u00a0could not be breached, but Saruman was trapped within. Treebeard stopped the attack on the tower when he realised their efforts were in vain; the tower was too strong. The Ents were ordered to unleash the waters of the\\u00a0<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_rivers#I\\">River Isen</a>, which flooded Isengard.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-AofAW2-2\\">[2]</a>\\u00a0When Merry and Pippin departed Treebeard he requested them to watch for the Entwives.<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\">[1]</a>\\u00a0At one point in the book, Tolkien gives hints on the whereabouts of the Entwives. It is speculated that they were spotted by Samwise Gamgee's cousin Hal in the North Farthing.\\u00a0</p>", "type": "paragraph"}]	21	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
34	[{"type": "paragraph", "value": "<p>I am May, I was raised in the Mekong Delta. I first worked as a social worker and then after university he became an English teacher. After growing up, working throughout the Mekong Delta, I decided to become a tour guide. Since 2009, I has been a freelance biking tour guide all over Myanmar for different tour companies. I understands the country, people and their customs. This allows me to take visitors into the countryside to meet local people and experience the real rural life.</p><p>As a child of the countryside I can easily help guests get closer with local people, their culture and way of life,...through biking. Everyone falls in love with the places that I leads them to.</p><p></p>"}]	58	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
36	[{"type": "paragraph", "value": "<p>Travel Writer, Photographer, Earth Advocate and Beauty Seeker.\\u00a0<br/>More about me on my blog - (URL HIDDEN)<br/></p>"}]	57	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
11	[{"type": "paragraph", "value": "<p>I am working as an English speaking guide in the region as well as different regions in Myanmar for nearly 8 years. I loveM and proud of its amazing nature, a deep orient culture blended with local traditional customs and its unforgettable history. Showing them to you, my travelers, is my passion. Your satisfaction about the trip is my happiness. You will come back to visit a place when you like a place so much. Thus making you falling in love with my country is my mission. I will customize your trip upon your special requests to help you with just a limited time, but so much to enjoy.<br/></p>"}]	54	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
31	[{"type": "paragraph", "value": "<p>I have travelled a lot for business and leisure and I can appreciate genuine hospitality. I love people who have the natural curiosity to explore other countries and I would be pleased to offer them an opportunity to relax and enjoy themselves.<br/></p>"}]	59	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
35	[{"type": "paragraph", "value": "<p>My name is Than, i am a tour guide in Yangon city Myanmar. i would like to introduce to all of people on the world about our country. So please contact me for your enjoyable trip to Myanmar.</p><p><br/></p><p>Thank you for your attention !</p>"}]	56	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
28	[{"type": "paragraph", "value": "<p>My name is Su. Extrovert introvertis which means I am very extrovert but whenever i have free time, I just want to spend time alone.</p><p><br/></p><p>I love traveling, speaking different languages and meeting new people. I am working as freelancer which has given me flexible schedule and the opportunity to interact with lots of foreigners.</p><p><br/></p><p>I love music. Playing guitar on singing is my favorite thing to entertain when I am free.</p><p><br/></p><p>I love doing work out and i pay lots attention to healthy eating.</p><p><br/></p><p>Last year, I worked as a tour guide in a travel agency with an original idea about tourism. That job helped me understand the insights of clients (and expats living in Yangon also) and improved my communication ability.</p><p><br/></p><p>I am signing up for this website because I do really enjoy guiding people in a friendly way. If you take me as your tourguide, you need to know in advance that I am not a 'traditional' guide who comes with tons of info, I will probably not know everything but will always try my best to satisfy your curiosity/questions about Myanmar.</p>"}]	55	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
41	[{"type": "paragraph", "value": "<p>Hi there, my name is Wynee. I have been working as a tour guide for over a decade, I have lots of experience taking tourists to some of the amazing places in Myanmar. I hold Psychology degree from Yangon University and I love vegeterian food.</p>"}]	77	yan.pye.aung@gmail.com
