bit\\\\\\">hobbit</a>\\\\u00a0in comfortable middle age at 50 years old, was hired despite his objections as a \\\\\\"burglar\\\\\\" by the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Istari\\\\\\">wizard</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_The_Hobbit_characters#Thorin.27s_company\\\\\\">13 Dwarves</a>\\\\u00a0led by their king\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thorin_Oakenshield\\\\\\">Thorin Oakenshield</a>\\\\u00a0on a quest to reclaim the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lonely_Mountain\\\\\\">Lonely Mountain</a>\\\\u00a0and its treasure from the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragon_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">dragon</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smaug\\\\\\">Smaug</a>. The adventure took Bilbo and the companions through the wilderness, to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">elf</a>\\\\u00a0haven of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, across the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misty_Mountains\\\\\\">Misty Mountains</a>\\\\u00a0and the black forest of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirkwood\\\\\\">Mirkwood</a>, to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esgaroth\\\\\\">Lake-town</a>\\\\u00a0in the middle of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_Lake_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Long Lake</a>, and eventually to the Mountain itself. Here, after the dragon was killed and the Mountain was reclaimed, soon after that the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Five_Armies\\\\\\">Battle of Five Armies</a>\\\\u00a0took place.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>In his journey, Bilbo encountered other fantastic creatures, including\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troll_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">trolls</a>, elves,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_animals#Great_Spiders\\\\\\">giant spiders</a>, a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beorn\\\\\\">man who can change shape into a bear</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">goblins</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eagle_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">eagles</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warg\\\\\\">wolves</a>\\\\u00a0and a slimy, murderous creature named\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gollum\\\\\\">Gollum</a>. Underground, near Gollum's lair, Bilbo accidentally found a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">magic ring of invisibility</a>, which he used to escape from Gollum.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>By the end of the journey, Bilbo had become wiser and more confident, having saved the day in many precarious situations. Bilbo's journey has been compared to a pilgrimage of grace. The Hobbit can be characterized as a \\\\\\"Christian\\\\u00a0<i>bildungsroman</i>\\\\u00a0which equates progress to wisdom gained in the form of a rite of passage.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-Saint_Benedict_Press-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0He rescued the dwarves from giant spiders with the magic ring and a short\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_weapons_and_armour#Sting\\\\\\">Elven-sword</a>\\\\u00a0he acquired. He used the ring to sneak around in dangerous places, as well as his wits to smuggle the dwarves out of the elves' prisons. When tensions arose over ownership of the recovered treasure, he tried unsuccessfully to bring the opposing sides to compromise, using the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_objects#Arkenstone\\\\\\">Arkenstone</a>, a stolen heirloom jewel, as leverage. This strained his relationship with Thorin, but the two were reconciled at Thorin's deathbed. At the end of the story, Bilbo returned to his home in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0only to find that several of his relatives, believing him to be dead, were trying to claim his home and possessions. In addition to becoming wealthy from his share of the dwarves' treasure, he found that he, like\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adam\\\\\\">Adam</a>, had traded respectability for experience and wisdom. At the end, Gandalf proclaims Bilbo is no longer the Hobbit he was. This is certainly true as Bilbo has fully matured. Continuing the pilgrimage theme, a true pilgrimage does not end at the destination, but rather when the wanderer is absolved, blessed, and ready to return home.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-Saint_Benedict_Press-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"size\\": \\"h2\\", \\"header_text\\": \\"The Lord of the Rings\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p><i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>, the first volume of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, begins with Bilbo's \\\\\\"eleventy-first\\\\\\" (111th) birthday, 60 years after the beginning of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>. The main character of the novel is\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>, Bilbo's cousin,<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[nb 1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0who celebrates his 33rd birthday and legally comes of age on the same day.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a02989 (<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_Reckoning\\\\\\">S.R.</a>\\\\u00a01389), Bilbo, a lifelong bachelor, adopted Frodo, the orphaned son of his first cousin\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primula_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Primula Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and his second cousin\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drogo_Baggins\\\\\\">Drogo Baggins</a>, and made him his heir. Though Frodo was actually \\\\\\"his first\\\\u00a0<i>and</i>\\\\u00a0second\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cousin#Cousin_chart\\\\\\">cousin once removed</a>\\\\u00a0either way\\\\\\",<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-LotR_party-3\\\\\\">[2]</a>\\\\u00a0the two regarded each other as uncle and nephew.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>All this time Bilbo had kept his magic ring, with no idea of its significance, using it mostly to hide from his obnoxious cousins, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sackville-Baggins\\\\\\">Sackville-Bagginses</a>, when they came to visit.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>'s investigations revealed it to be the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>\\\\u00a0forged by the Dark Lord\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>. The Ring had prolonged Bilbo's life beyond the normal hobbit span, and at 111 he still looked 50. While the Ring did not initially corrupt him as it had its previous owners, it was beginning to affect him; over the years, it had begun to prey on his mind when out of his sight, and he lost sleep and felt \\\\\\"thin, sort of\\\\u00a0<i>stretched</i>\\\\u00a0\\\\u2026 like butter that has been scraped over too much bread\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-LotR_party-3\\\\\\">[2]</a></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>On the night of his and Frodo's birthday, Bilbo threw himself a party and invited all of the Shire. He signed his home,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bag_End\\\\\\">Bag End</a>, and estate over to Frodo. He then gave a farewell address to his neighbors, at the end of which he put on the Ring and vanished from sight. As Bilbo prepared finally to leave the house, he reacted with panic and suspicion when Gandalf tried to persuade him to leave the Ring with Frodo. Bilbo refused to give up the Ring, referring to it as his \\\\\\"precious\\\\\\" \\\\u2013 just as Gollum had. Gandalf lost his temper with his old friend and talked some sense into him. Bilbo admitted he would have liked to be rid of the Ring, and he left it behind, becoming the first person to do so voluntarily. He left the Shire that night, and was never seen in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbiton\\\\\\">Hobbiton</a>\\\\u00a0again.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>His earlier adventure, his\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eccentric_(behavior)\\\\\\">eccentric</a>\\\\u00a0habits as a hobbit, and his sudden disappearance led to the enduring figure of \\\\\\"Mad Baggins\\\\\\" in hobbit folklore, who disappeared with a flash and a bang and returned with gold and jewels.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Freed of the Ring's power over his senses, Bilbo travelled first to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, and then on to visit the dwarves of the Lonely Mountain. After he returned to Rivendell he spent much of the next 17 years living a pleasant life of retirement: eating, sleeping, writing poetry, and working on his memoirs,\\\\u00a0<i>There and Back Again</i>, known as\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>. He became a scholar of Elven lore, leaving behind the\\\\u00a0<i>Translations from the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvish_languages_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elvish</a></i>, which forms the basis of what is known to us as\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Silmarillion\\\\\\">The Silmarillion</a></i>.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>When Frodo and his friends\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee\\\\\\">Samwise Gamgee</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Peregrin Took</a>\\\\u00a0stopped in Rivendell on their quest to destroy the Ring, Bilbo was still alive but now visibly aged, the years having caught up with him after he surrendered the Ring. Upon seeing the Ring again, he suddenly tried to take it from Frodo; he returned to his senses when a terrified Frodo backed away, and he broke down in tears, apologizing for bringing the burden of the Ring onto Frodo.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>After the quest to destroy the Ring was fulfilled in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\\\\\">The Return of the King</a></i>, Gandalf and the four Hobbits visited Rivendell on their way back to the Shire and found Bilbo still living there. He gave Frodo a set of manuscripts that later became\\\\u00a0<i>Translations from the Elvish</i>, and also gave Sam a small bag of gold that represented the last of his share from Smaug's vast hoard. Two years later Bilbo accompanied Gandalf,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galadriel\\\\\\">Galadriel</a>, and Frodo to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_Havens\\\\\\">Grey Havens</a>, there to take ship for\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tol_Eress%C3%ABa\\\\\\">Tol Eress\\\\u00eba</a>\\\\u00a0across the sea, on 29th 'September'\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a03021. He had already celebrated his 131st birthday by this time, surpassing the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Took\\\\\\">Old Took</a>\\\\u00a0by one year and becoming the oldest Hobbit ever in Middle-earth. (The natural lifespan of Hobbits is about 100 years.)<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-4\\\\\\">[3]</a></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}]", "latest_revision_created_at": "2018-01-20T21:55:52.473Z", "owner": 1, "pk": 38, "path": "000100010001000F", "content_type": 12, "depth": 4, "slug": "tun", "search_description": "", "go_live_at": null, "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T22:23:37.638Z", "numchild": 0, "url_path": "/homepage/hosts/tun/", "seo_title": "", "email_address": "yan.pye.aung@gmail.com", "show_in_menus": false, "live": false, "has_unpublished_changes": true, "title": "Than Tun", "locked": false}	\N	38	2
245	f	2018-01-20 22:12:02.879092+00	{"host_language_relationship": [], "expired": false, "image": 18, "expire_at": null, "body": "[{\\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Saruman the White</b>\\\\u00a0is a fictional character and a major antagonist in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s fantasy novel\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. He is leader of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Istari</a>, wizards sent to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>\\\\u00a0in human form by the godlike\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vala_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Valar</a>\\\\u00a0to challenge\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>, the main antagonist of the novel, but eventually he desires Sauron's power for himself and tries to take over Middle-earth by force. His schemes feature prominently in the second volume,\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\\\\\">The Two Towers</a></i>, and at the end of the third volume,\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\\\\\">The Return of the King</a></i>. His earlier history is given briefly in the posthumously published\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Silmarillion\\\\\\">The Silmarillion</a></i>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unfinished_Tales\\\\\\">Unfinished Tales</a></i>.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Saruman is one of several characters in the book illustrating the corruption of power; his desire for knowledge and order leads to his fall, and he rejects the chance of redemption when it is offered. The name\\\\u00a0<i>Saruman</i>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA\\\\\\">[\\\\u02c8saruman]</a>\\\\u00a0means \\\\\\"man of experience\\\\\\" in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercian_(Anglo-Saxon)\\\\\\">Mercian dialect</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_English_language\\\\\\">Anglo-Saxon</a>;<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0he serves as an example of technology and modernity being overthrown by forces more in tune with nature. Saruman is represented by a white hand.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"size\\": \\"h2\\", \\"header_text\\": \\"Characterisation\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Tolkien described Saruman at the time of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>\\\\u00a0as having a long face and a high forehead, \\\\\\"...he had deep darkling eyes ... His hair and beard were white, but strands of black still showed around his lips and ears.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Orthanc-24\\\\\\">[24]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0His hair is elsewhere described as having been black when he first arrived in Middle-earth. He is referred to as 'Saruman the White' and is said to have originally worn white robes, but on his first entry in\\\\u00a0<i>The Fellowship of the Ring</i>\\\\u00a0they instead appear to be \\\\\\"woven from all colours [, they] shimmered and changed hue so that the eye was bewildered\\\\\\" and he names himself 'Saruman of Many Colours'.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Saru1-25\\\\\\">[25]</a></sup></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/TQq4LjSF2rc\\", \\"type\\": \\"embed\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>The power of Saruman's voice is noted throughout the book. Jonathan Evans calls the characterization of Saruman in the chapter\\\\u00a0<i>The Voice of Saruman</i>\\\\u00a0a \\\\\\"tour de force\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Evans-20\\\\\\">[20]</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Sale\\\\\\">Roger Sale</a>\\\\u00a0says of the same chapter that \\\\\\"Tolkien valiantly tried to do something worth doing which he simply cannot bring off.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-26\\\\\\">[26]</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Shippey\\\\\\">Tom Shippey</a>\\\\u00a0writes that \\\\\\"Saruman talks like a politician ... No other character in Middle-earth has Saruman's trick of balancing phrases against each other so that incompatibles are resolved, and none comes out with words as empty as 'deploring', 'ultimate', worst of all, 'real'. What is 'real change'?\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-elcoun-27\\\\\\">[27]</a>Shippey contrasts this modern speech pattern with the archaic stoicism and directness that Tolkien employs for other characters such as the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwarf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Dwarven</a>\\\\u00a0King\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D%C3%A1in_II_Ironfoot\\\\\\">D\\\\u00e1in</a>, which Shippey believes represent Tolkien's view of heroism in the mould of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beowulf\\\\\\">Beowulf</a></i>.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-elcoun-27\\\\\\">[27]</a></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>After the defeat of his armies, having been caught in the betrayal of Sauron, Saruman is offered refuge by Gandalf, in return for his aid, but having chosen his path, is unable to turn from it.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Spacks2-28\\\\\\">[28]</a>\\\\u00a0Evans has compared the character of Saruman to that of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satan\\\\\\">Satan</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Milton\\\\\\">John Milton</a>'s\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paradise_Lost\\\\\\">Paradise Lost</a></i>\\\\u00a0in his use of rhetoric and in this final refusal of redemption, \\\\\\"conquered by pride and hatred\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Evans-20\\\\\\">[20]</a></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}]", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T21:35:51.073Z", "owner": 1, "pk": 27, "path": "0001000100010004", "content_type": 12, "depth": 4, "slug": "saruman", "search_description": "", "go_live_at": null, "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T21:35:51.120Z", "numchild": 0, "url_path": "/homepage/hosts/saruman/", "seo_title": "", "email_address": "yan.pye.aung@gmail.com", "show_in_menus": false, "live": false, "has_unpublished_changes": true, "title": "Saruman", "locked": false}	\N	27	2
246	f	2018-01-20 22:12:22.818626+00	{"host_language_relationship": [], "expired": false, "image": 6, "expire_at": null, "body": "[{\\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Boromir</b>\\\\u00a0is a character in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legendarium\\\\\\">legendarium</a>. He appears in the first two volumes of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>\\\\u00a0(<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\\\\\">The Two Towers</a></i>), and is mentioned in the last volume,\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\\\\\">The Return of the King</a></i>. He is the heir of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denethor\\\\\\">Denethor II</a>\\\\u00a0(the 26th\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stewards_of_Gondor\\\\\\">Ruling Steward</a>of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondor</a>) and the elder brother of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faramir\\\\\\">Faramir</a>. In the course of the story Boromir joins the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Boromir is portrayed as a noble character who believes passionately in the greatness of his kingdom, who would have defended its hosts to the last. Boromir's great stamina and physical strength, together with a forceful and commanding personality, made him a widely admired commander in Gondor's army: he was made Captain of the White Tower, and quickly became Captain-General, also bearing the title High Warden of the White Tower. He was also heir apparent to the Stewardship. Boromir led many successful forays against\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>'s forces, prior to his journey north to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, which brought him great esteem in the eyes of his father, Denethor.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"size\\": \\"h2\\", \\"header_text\\": \\"Literature\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Boromir, as a character, is portrayed as having been born in the year 2978 of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">Third Age</a>\\\\u00a0to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denethor_II\\\\\\">Denethor II</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finduilas_of_Dol_Amroth\\\\\\">Finduilas</a>, daughter of Adrahil of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dol_Amroth\\\\\\">Dol Amroth</a>. His younger brother,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faramir\\\\\\">Faramir</a>, was born in the year\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a02983. The following year, Denethor became Steward of Gondor, succeeding his father,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ecthelion_II\\\\\\">Ecthelion II</a>. Boromir simultaneously became heir apparent, inheriting the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horn_of_Gondor\\\\\\">Horn of Gondor</a>.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Boromir was named after the son of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denethor_I\\\\\\">Denethor I</a>, who was Steward around 500 years before the War of the Ring. The\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir_(Steward)\\\\\\">first Boromir</a>\\\\u00a0was known as a great captain who cleared\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ithilien\\\\\\">Ithilien</a>\\\\u00a0of orcs of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>\\\\u00a0and was feared even by the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witch-king\\\\\\">Witch-king</a>\\\\u00a0himself. Thus there were high expectations for Boromir the son of Denethor II.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"text\\": \\"It is a strange fate that we should suffer so much fear and doubt over so small a thing. Such a little thing.\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Boromir\\", \\"attribute_group\\": \\"\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>When Boromir's mother Finduilas died (<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a02988), he was aged only 10. Denethor became sombre, cold and detached from his family. As their father withdrew, the relationship between Faramir and Boromir grew closer and greater in love. Denethor always favoured Boromir over Faramir\\\\u2014Denethor loved Boromir \\\\\\"too much, perhaps; the more so because they were unlike\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir#cite_note-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u2014but this caused no rivalry between the two brothers. Boromir always protected and helped Faramir. Boromir was judged to be the more daring one, as well as the more fearless.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>In response to prophetic dreams that came to Faramir and later to himself, Boromir claimed the quest of riding to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>\\\\u00a0from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith\\\\\\">Minas Tirith</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a03018. His journey lasted a hundred and eleven days, and he travelled through \\\\\\"roads forgotten\\\\\\" to reach Rivendell, though, as he said, \\\\\\"few knew where it lay\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[2]</a>\\\\u00a0Boromir lost his horse halfway along, while crossing the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greyflood\\\\\\">Greyflood</a>at the ruined city of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tharbad\\\\\\">Tharbad</a>\\\\u00a0where the bridge was broken. He had to travel the remaining way on foot<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir#cite_note-3\\\\\\">[3]</a>\\\\u00a0and barely arrived in time for the Council of Elrond. (Tolkien wrote of Boromir's journey that \\\\\\"the courage and hardihood required is not fully recognized in the narrative\\\\\\".)<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir#cite_note-4\\\\\\">[4]</a></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}]", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T21:19:17.059Z", "owner": 1, "pk": 13, "path": "0001000100010003", "content_type": 12, "depth": 4, "slug": "boromir", "search_description": "", "go_live_at": null, "first_published_at": "2017-01-09T10:58:20.579Z", "numchild": 0, "url_path": "/homepage/hosts/boromir/", "seo_title": "", "email_address": "yan.pye.aung@gmail.com", "show_in_menus": false, "live": false, "has_unpublished_changes": true, "title": "Boromir", "locked": false}	\N	13	2
244	f	2018-01-20 22:10:15.96832+00	{"host_language_relationship": [], "expired": false, "image": 60, "expire_at": null, "body": "[{\\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Shelob</b>\\\\u00a0is a fictional\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spider_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">giant spider</a>\\\\u00a0from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legendarium\\\\\\">legendarium</a>. She appears at the end of the fourth book, second volume (<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\\\\\">The Two Towers</a></i>), of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. Her lair lies in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cirith_Ungol\\\\\\">Cirith Ungol</a>\\\\u00a0(\\\\\\"the pass of the spider\\\\\\") leading into\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gollum\\\\\\">Gollum</a>\\\\u00a0deliberately leads\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>\\\\u00a0there in hopes of recovering the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>\\\\u00a0when Shelob attacks Frodo. The plan is foiled when\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee\\\\\\">Samwise Gamgee</a>\\\\u00a0greatly injures Shelob with Frodo's Elvish dagger,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sting_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Sting</a>, and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phial_of_Galadriel\\\\\\">Phial of Galadriel</a>.</p><p></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"size\\": \\"h2\\", \\"header_text\\": \\"Literature\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Shelob was an \\\\\\"evil thing in spider form...[the] last child of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ungoliant\\\\\\">Ungoliant</a>\\\\u00a0to trouble the unhappy world\\\\\\",<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelob#cite_note-TTT_book_4_ch_9-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0living high in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ephel_D%C3%BAath\\\\\\">Ephel D\\\\u00faath</a>\\\\u00a0mountains on the borders of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>. There are numerous references to her predating the events of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>\\\\u00a0by many ages. Although she resided in Mordor and was unrepentantly evil, she was independent of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>\\\\u00a0and his influence.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelob#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[2]</a></sup></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>This creature makes her first appearance in the chapter \\\\\\"The Stairs of Cirith Ungol\\\\\\", though she is formally introduced in the next chapter \\\\\\"Shelob's Lair\\\\\\" where the author says \\\\\\"But still she was there, who was there before Sauron, and before the first stone of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barad-d%C3%BBr\\\\\\">Barad-d\\\\u00fbr</a>; and she served none but herself, drinking the blood of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elves</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Men</a>, bloated and grown fat with endless brooding on her feasts, weaving webs of shadow; for all living things were her food, and her vomit darkness\\\\\\". Her descendants include the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spider_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Giant Spiders</a>\\\\u00a0defeated by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins\\\\\\">Bilbo Baggins</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Shelob's lair was\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Torech_Ungol\\\\\\">Torech Ungol</a>, below Cirith Ungol (\\\\\\"Pass of the Spider\\\\\\"), along the path that\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sam_Gamgee\\\\\\">Sam Gamgee</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>\\\\u00a0took into Mordor, where Shelob had encountered Gollum during his previous trip to Mordor, and he apparently worshipped her. The\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Orcs</a>\\\\u00a0of the Tower of Cirith Ungol called her \\\\\\"Shelob the Great\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"Her Ladyship\\\\\\", and referred to Gollum as \\\\\\"Her Sneak\\\\\\". Sauron himself was aware of her existence, but left her alone, as a useful guard on the pass, and occasionally fed prisoners to her. In the story, Gollum led the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit\\\\\\">Hobbits</a>\\\\u00a0into her lair to himself recover the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>\\\\u00a0after she consumed them. She cornered them; but Frodo used the Phial of Galadriel's light to drive her off, and used Sting to cut the webs blocking the tunnel. Gollum waylaid the pair and tried to strangle Sam, while Shelob paralysed Frodo; whereafter Sam fought off Gollum and then wielded Sting against Shelob. Seeking to crush Sam, she instead impaled herself upon\\\\u00a0<i>Sting</i>; and was nearly blinded by the Phial of Galadriel; whereupon she fled. Thinking Frodo dead, Sam took the Ring from his friend and left his body behind, but discovered by listening to a pair of Orcs that Frodo was alive but senseless, under a minor influence of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Venom\\\\\\">venom</a>.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/pA0ffVBw584\\", \\"type\\": \\"embed\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"size\\": \\"h2\\", \\"header_text\\": \\"Name\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>As Tolkien admitted in a letter to his son, Shelob \\\\\\"is of course only 'she + lob',\\\\\\" -\\\\u00a0<i>lob</i>\\\\u00a0being an archaic English word for spider, influenced by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_English\\\\\\">Old English</a>\\\\u00a0<i>loppe</i>\\\\u00a0or \\\\\\"spider\\\\\\". The word is not related to \\\\\\"cob\\\\\\" nor \\\\\\"cobweb\\\\\\".\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_English\\\\\\">Old English</a>\\\\u00a0<i>attercoppe</i>\\\\u00a0(meaning \\\\\\"spider\\\\\\") is derived from\\\\u00a0<i>atter</i>\\\\u00a0meaning \\\\\\"poison\\\\\\" and\\\\u00a0<i>coppe</i>\\\\u00a0meaning \\\\\\"head\\\\\\"; Tolkien used \\\\\\"attercop\\\\\\" as well as \\\\\\"cob\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"lob\\\\\\" in\\\\u00a0<i>The Hobbit</i>, where Bilbo Baggins sings songs taunting the giant spiders in Mirkwood: \\\\\\"Attercop, Attercop, Old Tomnoddy\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"Lazy Lob and Crazy Cob\\\\\\".<sup>[<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\\\\\\">citation needed</a></i>]</sup></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}]", "latest_revision_created_at": "2018-01-20T22:10:09.305Z", "owner": 1, "pk": 32, "path": "0001000100010009", "content_type": 12, "depth": 4, "slug": "moe-thu", "search_description": "", "go_live_at": null, "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T21:55:58.885Z", "numchild": 0, "url_path": "/homepage/hosts/moe-thu/", "seo_title": "", "email_address": "test.boo33@gmail.com", "show_in_menus": false, "live": false, "has_unpublished_changes": true, "title": "Moe Thu", "locked": false}	\N	32	2
