31	f	2017-01-12 20:27:03.937+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "minas-tirith", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/minas-tirith/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Minas Tirith</b>\\\\u00a0(<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English\\\\\\">/\\\\u02c8m\\\\u026an\\\\u0259s\\\\u00a0\\\\u02c8t\\\\u026ar\\\\u026a\\\\u03b8/</a>;\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\\\\\">Sindarin</a>:\\\\u00a0/\\\\u02c8minas \\\\u02c8tiri\\\\u03b8/), originally named\\\\u00a0<b>Minas Anor</b>, is a fictional city and castle in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>\\\\u00a0writings. It became the heavily fortified\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_city\\\\\\">capital</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondor</a>\\\\u00a0in the second half of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">Third Age</a>. It was originally built to guard the former capital,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Osgiliath\\\\\\">Osgiliath</a>, from attack from the west, but became the capital when Osgiliath fell into ruin following the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_wars_and_battles#Kin-strife\\\\\\">Kin-strife</a>\\\\u00a0and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor#Decline\\\\\\">Great Plague</a>. It is often referred to as the\\\\u00a0<b>White City</b>\\\\u00a0(though that name is not in the book) and the\\\\u00a0<b>City of the Kings</b>. The\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)#hosts\\\\\\">Rohirrim</a>sometimes translated this into\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohirric\\\\\\">their own language</a>\\\\u00a0as \\\\\\"the\\\\u00a0<b>Mundburg</b>\\\\\\". In the climax of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>\\\\u00a0the city comes under a very large and determined attack by the allied forces of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>.<br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Description\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The name\\\\u00a0<i>Minas Tirith</i>\\\\u00a0means \\\\\\"The Tower of Guard\\\\\\" or \\\\\\"The Tower of Watch\\\\\\" in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elvish</a>\\\\u00a0language\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\\\\\">Sindarin</a>.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith#cite_note-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0It was originally named\\\\u00a0<i>Minas Anor</i>, \\\\\\"The Tower of the Setting Sun\\\\\\", in connection with\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Morgul\\\\\\">Minas Ithil</a></i>, \\\\\\"The Tower of the Rising Moon\\\\\\". Minas Ithil was later conquered by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>\\\\u00a0and was renamed\\\\u00a0<i>Minas Morgul</i>, \\\\\\"The Tower of Black Sorcery\\\\\\".</p><p>The city of Minas Tirith covered an entire hill, the Hill of Guard, and was built on seven levels, culminating in the Citadel at the summit. Each level was about 100\\\\u00a0ft (30\\\\u00a0m) higher than the one below it, and each surrounded by a white wall, with the exception of the wall of the First Circle (the lowest level), which was black. The outer face of this outer wall, the lowest, was made of black stone, the same material used in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthanc\\\\\\">Orthanc</a>; it was vulnerable only to earthquakes capable of rending the ground where it stood.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[2]</a></sup></p><p>Each wall held a gate, and each gate faced a different direction from the one in the next lower wall. The city's main street snaked up the hill and through each of the gates.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"style\\": \\"full\\", \\"caption\\": \\"White Tree of Gondor in Minas Tirith\\", \\"image\\": 17}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Great Gate\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Great Gate was the main gate on the first level of the City of Minas Tirith. It was in the City Wall \\\\u2014 or Othram \\\\u2014 facing eastward across the Pelennor Fields toward the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anduin\\\\\\">Anduin</a>.</p><p>In front of the Great Gate there was a large paved area called the Gateway. The main roads to Minas Tirith met here: the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#North-way\\\\\\">North-way</a>\\\\u00a0that became the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#Great_West_Road\\\\\\">Great West Road</a>\\\\u00a0to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>; the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#South_Road\\\\\\">South Road</a>\\\\u00a0to the southern provinces of Gondor; and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#Causeway_.28Osgiliath.29\\\\\\">road to Osgiliath</a>.</p><p>The Great Gate was very strong, constructed of iron and steel and guarded by stone towers and bastions. The iron doors of the Gate rolled back to open. Passwords were required to enter the Great Gate and each of the six other gates of Minas Tirith. The Great Gate was breached during the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">War of the Ring</a>.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>'s forces under the command of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witch-king_of_Angmar\\\\\\">Witch-king of Angmar</a>\\\\u00a0besieged the City on 13th 'March'. Before dawn on 15th 'March', the battering ram\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grond_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Grond</a>\\\\u00a0smashed into the Great Gate three times while the Witch-king spoke words of power. \\\\\\"As if stricken by some blasting spell it burst asunder: there was a flash of searing lightning, and the doors tumbled in riven fragments to the ground.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith#cite_note-3\\\\\\">[3]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0The Witch-king rode through the Gate where\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0awaited him, but then the Rohirrim arrived and the Witch-king went to fight them in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_the_Pelennor_Fields\\\\\\">Battle of the Pelennor Fields</a>\\\\u00a0where he was slain.</p><p>A temporary barricade was erected in place of the Great Gate. After the War, on 1st 'May',\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\\\\\">Aragorn</a>\\\\u00a0received the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crown_of_Gondor\\\\\\">Crown of Gondor</a>\\\\u00a0in front of the gate and then entered the City.</p><p>The Great Gate was rebuilt of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mithril\\\\\\">mithril</a></i>\\\\u00a0(the hardest of all metals in Tolkien's writing) and steel by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gimli_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Gimli</a>\\\\u00a0and Dwarves of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erebor\\\\\\">Erebor</a>\\\\u00a0from the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lonely_Mountain\\\\\\">Lonely Mountain</a>\\\\u00a0who had settled in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glittering_Caves\\\\\\">Glittering Caves</a>.</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": "2017-01-09T10:57:05.960Z", "show_in_menus": false, "title": "Minas Tirith", "pk": 12, "content_type": 6, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-09T10:57:05.919Z", "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 4, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "path": "0001000100030002"}	\N	12	1
29	f	2017-01-12 20:16:17.711+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "rivendell", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/rivendell/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Rivendell is an Elven realm in Middle-earth, a fictional world created by J. R. R. Tolkien. It is an important place in Tolkien's legendarium, and is featured in The Hobbit, The Lord of the Rings, The Silmarillion, and Unfinished Tales. It was established and ruled by Elrond Half-elven in the Second Age of Middle-earth (four or five thousand years before the events of The Lord of the Rings), and was protected by the powers of its lord and his elven ring Vilya.</p><p><br/></p><p>Elrond lived in Rivendell with his family \\\\u2014 his wife Celebr\\\\u00edan (until she departed for Valinor), their sons Elladan and Elrohir, and their daughter Arwen \\\\u2014 as well as a sizeable number of other Elves, both Noldor and Sindar. In addition to the family of Elrond, notable Elves who lived in Rivendell included Glorfindel, Gildor, and Erestor. In some writings, featured in Unfinished Tales, Galadriel and Celeborn also lived in Rivendell for a time before they became rulers of Lothl\\\\u00f3rien.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/t9L8Er_oqAQ\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Etymology\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><i>Rivendell</i>\\\\u00a0is a direct translation or\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calque\\\\\\">calque</a>\\\\u00a0into English of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\\\\\">Sindarin</a>\\\\u00a0name\\\\u00a0<b>Imladris</b>, both meaning \\\\\\"deep valley of the cleft\\\\\\". The name Rivendell is formed by two English elements: \\\\\\"riven\\\\\\" (split, cloven) and \\\\\\"dell\\\\\\" (valley), making the whole word purport \\\\\\"deeply cloven valley\\\\\\". Imladris was also rendered \\\\\\"<i>Karningul</i>\\\\\\" in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Westron\\\\\\">Westron</a>, the \\\\\\"Common Tongue\\\\\\" of Middle-Earth represented as English in the text of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings.</i>\\\\u00a0It is also referred to as\\\\u00a0<i>The Last Homely House,</i>\\\\u00a0alluding to the elves' old cities, in Beleriand and Aman, and the wilderness (Rhovanion) that lies east of the Misty Mountains.<br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Legacy\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the period of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Counterculture\\\\\\">counterculture</a>\\\\u00a0in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_World\\\\\\">Western World</a>\\\\u00a0of the 1960s and 1970s, a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commune\\\\\\">commune</a>\\\\u00a0called\\\\u00a0<i>Maos Lyst</i>\\\\u00a0(<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mao_Zedong\\\\\\">Mao</a>'s Delight) was founded in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denmark\\\\\\">Denmark</a>\\\\u00a0in 1968, its inhabitants replacing their surnames with\\\\u00a0<i>Kl\\\\u00f8vedal</i>, Danish for Rivendell, inspired by Tolkien's Elven outpost.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell#cite_note-6\\\\\\">[6]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0Several of them later became well-known cultural personalities in the country.</p><p>The Canadian progressive rock band\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rush_(band)\\\\\\">Rush</a>\\\\u00a0memorializes Rivendell in the song \\\\\\"Rivendell\\\\\\" on their second studio album\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fly_by_Night_(album)\\\\\\">Fly By Night</a></i>. The song focuses on the tranquillity and seemingly endless time a weary traveller could find there.</p><p>The Austrian folk band Rivendell takes the material for their lyrics almost entirely from Tolkien's books.</p><p>A Californian manufacturer of bicycles,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell_Bicycle_Works\\\\\\">Rivendell Bicycle Works</a>, also uses the name, inspired by the book and a United States backpacking supply company founded in the 1970s called\\\\u00a0Rivendell Mountain Works. They take many of the names of their bicycle models from Tolkien.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell#cite_note-7\\\\\\">[7]</a></sup></p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "title": "Rivendell", "pk": 19, "content_type": 6, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 15, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "path": "0001000100030008"}	\N	19	1
294	f	2018-01-26 04:23:51.636614+00	{"path": "0001000100030006", "go_live_at": null, "content_type": 6, "depth": 4, "show_in_menus": false, "image": 44, "numchild": 0, "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:05:17.882Z", "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "live": true, "slug": "mawlamyine", "expired": false, "title": "Mawlamyine", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Mawlamyine (Moulmein/Moulmien) is the capital of Mon State in Southeastern Myanmar. Mawlamyine is the fourth largest city in Myanmar with a population of 326,000. It was captured by the British in 1826 during the First Anglo-Burmese War and served as their capital from 1827 to 1852. Even though the population is quite large the city itself looks and feels like only a small town, making it pleasant to walk around. Mawlamyine is pronounced \\\\\\"more-la-mine\\\\\\".<br/></p>\\"}]", "expire_at": null, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-06-13T03:18:25.036Z", "owner": 1, "pk": 17, "url_path": "/homepage/places/mawlamyine/", "locked": false}	\N	17	1
27	f	2017-01-12 20:05:17.843+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "fangorn", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/fangorn/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Fangorn (Sindarin: [Fangaorne]; \\\\\\"Beardtree\\\\\\") in J.R.R. Tolkien's Legendarium, was a forest located in the fictional world of Middle-earth and was the home of the tree shepherds, the Ents. It was named after the oldest Ent, Treebeard or Treebeard after it. Tolkien did, however, state that there was confusion about the two.</p><p><br/></p><p>The Forest of Fangorn provided an important role in The Lord of the Rings novel as did Mirkwood and Lothl\\\\u00f3rien in the Third Age, a time when Sauron challenged Middle-earth to battle and domination. The forest provided the means by where adventure expanded with the breaking up of the Fellowship. Merry Brandybuck and Peregrin Took were the first to discover the Ents were alive but were dwindling in numbers due to the loss of the Entwives. They were lost because of the events of the Last Alliance of Elves and Men. The forest was again severely damaged during the War of the Ring by the forces of Saruman who lived close by in the fortress of Isengard.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Etymology\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>\\\\\\"Fangorn\\\\\\" was the original name for the Ent Treebeard, who was the eldest of his species and who looked after vast areas of his home and the surrounding land which was named Fangorn Forest. Additionally, Fangorn translated in the fictional language of Sindarin from \\\\\\"fanga\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"beard\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"orne\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"tree\\\\\\". Sindarin was a language Tolkien created and described the Elves of Middle-Earth to possess; who \\\\\\"awoke\\\\\\" the Ents and taught them language. In other parts of Middle-earth Fangorn Forest was called the \\\\\\"Entwood\\\\\\" by the Rohirrim.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Fangorn Forest apparently had several names as told by Treebeard who referred to the forest by various Quenya names in Lord of the Rings, some of which were Ambar\\\\u00f3na, Tauremornal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb, Tauremorna and Aldal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb. \\\\\\"Ambar\\\\u00f3na\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"uprising, sunrise, orient\\\\\\" from \\\\\\"amba\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"upwards\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"r\\\\u00f3na\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"east\\\\\\". \\\\\\"Aldal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"tree twilight\\\\\\" from \\\\\\"alda\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"tree\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"l\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"dusk, twilight\\\\\\".[1] \\\\\\"Tauremorna\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"gloomy forest\\\\\\" from \\\\\\"taur\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"forest\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"morna\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"gloomy, somber\\\\\\".[1] \\\\\\"Tauremornal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"gloomy twilight forest\\\\\\".</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Geography\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Forest of Fangorn was located at the south-eastern end of the Misty Mountains near the Gap of Rohan. The mountains formed the western border of Fangorn. At the end of the mountain range stood the stronghold of Isengard near the southwestern corner of the forest and this was where Saruman lived.[citation needed] To the east and south of Fangorn was the land of Rohan, and Lothl\\\\u00f3rien lay to the north and slightly east. Fangorn Forest stretched for many miles and held many paths.</p><p><br/></p><p>Tolkien stated that two significant rivers ran through the forest. To the north the Limlight flowed from the woods and then formed the northern border of Rohan. The river then merged into the larger Anduin. In the south, the Entwash spread deep into the forest arriving from Methedras, a mountainous region located near the Misty Mountains. The river then flowed from Fangorn and was directed through Rohan to the Anduin River. The valley of Derndingle was located to the south-west. There was a path where the Entwash passed into a region called Wellinghall and this was where the Entwash passed the home of Treebeard, the shepherd of the forest.</p><p><br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\", \\"value\\": {\\"attribute_group\\": \\"\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Treebeard\\", \\"text\\": \\"Some of us are still true Ents, and lively enough in our fashion, but many are growing sleepy, going tree-ish, as you might say. Most of the trees are just trees, of course; but many are half awake. Some are quite wide awake, and a few are, well, ah, well getting Entish. That is going on all the time.\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Fangorn Forest was said to be humid, and trunks and branches grew thick where very little light penetrated the forest. Similarly, Fangorn was said to be a dangerous and evil place like Mirkwood (where huge spiders roamed the forest and other evil creatures lay), but this was not the case following the events of The Lord of the Rings. The forest was home to many different kinds of trees. Huorns also lived in the forest, similar to Ents but more discreet. Most lived deep in the Forest of Fangorn. The Ents and Huorns drank from the river Entwash, and from it the Ents brewed their legendary drink, the Ent-draughts.</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "title": "Fangorn", "pk": 17, "content_type": 6, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 13, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "path": "0001000100030006"}	\N	17	1
26	f	2017-01-12 20:00:16.513+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "edoras", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/edoras/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The capital of Rohan is the hill fort of Edoras which is located on a hill in a valley of the White Mountains. Meduseld, the Golden Hall of the King of Rohan, is located there. \\\\\\"Edoras\\\\\\" is Old English for \\\\\\"enclosures\\\\\\",[4] which Tolkien held to be a translation of an unknown Rohirric name of the same meaning. The city of Edoras was built by Rohan's second King, Brego son of Eorl the Young. Before Edoras was completed, Rohan's capital was at Aldburg in the Folde. Meduseld is described as having a golden thatch. Edoras is built at the end of the valley of Harrowdale, which lies under the great mountain Starkhorn. The river Snowbourn flows past the city on its way east towards the Entwash. The city is protected only by a high wall of timber, and a one-way road allows access to the city. Just before the gates, two rows of mounds line the road, which are the graves of the former Kings of Rohan. \\\\\\"Meduseld\\\\\\", a modernised form of the Old English Maeduselde,[5] is similarly meant to be a translation of an unknown Rohirric name meaning \\\\\\"mead hall\\\\\\". Meduseld is a large hall with roof that appears golden from far off. The walls are richly decorated with tapestries depicting the history and legends of the Rohirrim, and it serves as a house for the King and his kin, a meeting hall for the King and his advisors, and a gathering hall.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"style\\": \\"half\\", \\"caption\\": \\"The Uffington White Horse, whence the banner and shield of the House of Eorl \\\\u2013 a \\\\\\"white horse upon green\\\\\\" \\\\u2013 is derived.\\", \\"image\\": 11}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Edoras is Rohan's only real city. It is at Meduseld that Aragorn, Gimli, Legolas, and Gandalf meet with King Th\\\\u00e9oden in the account of the early stages of the War of the Ring.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Another settlement is Aldburg, capital of the Eastfold and original settlement of Eorl the Young. A third settlement is Snowbourne, named after the river of the same name which runs nearby. It is similar in appearance to the hill-fort of Edoras. Dunharrow is a refuge in the White Mountains. Helm's Deep is a valley in the White Mountains in which the Hornburg, a major fortress of Rohan, is located.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\", \\"value\\": {\\"attribute_group\\": \\"Reciting a forgotten poem on Eorl the Young\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Aragorn\\", \\"text\\": \\"Where now the horse and the rider? Where is the horn that was blowing?\\\\r\\\\nWhere is the helm and the hauberk, and the bright hair flowing?\\\\r\\\\nWhere is the hand on the harp-string, and the red fire glowing?\\\\r\\\\nWhere is the spring and the harvest and the tall corn growing?\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Internal history\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the thirteenth century of the Third Age (T.A.), the Kings of Gondor made close alliances with the Northmen of Rhovanion, a hosts said in The Lord of the Rings to be akin to the Three Houses of Men (later the D\\\\u00fanedain) from the First Age.</p><p><br/></p><p>In the twenty-first century, a remnant tribe of such Northmen calling itself the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od moved from the valleys of Anduin to the north west of Mirkwood, clearing out what remained of the recently defeated witch kingdom of Angmar, east of the Misty Mountains. While there, some dispute arose between them and the Dwarves over the treasure-hoard of Scatha the dragon.</p><p><br/></p><p>Later, in 2509, Cirion the Steward of Gondor sent summons to the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od for aid in throwing off a combined invasion of Men from the north east of Middle-earth, and Orcs from Mordor.</p><p><br/></p><p>Eorl the Young, king of the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od, answered the summons, and arrived unexpected at a decisive battle at the Field of Celebrant, routing the orc army, and then destroying it as it fled.</p><p><br/></p><p>As a reward, Eorl was given the plains of Calenardhon, and he moved his kingdom there. This land had earlier been part of Gondor proper, but had been devastated by the plague of 1636, and the survivors to a large extent slain in the invasion mentioned above.</p><p><br/></p><p>The first line of kings lasted for 249 years, until the ninth king Helm Hammerhand died. His sons had been killed earlier, and his nephew Fr\\\\u00e9al\\\\u00e1f Hildeson began the second line of kings, which lasted until the end of the Third Age.</p><p><br/></p><p>In 2758, Rohan was invaded by Dunlendings under Wulf, son of Freca, of mixed Dunland and Rohan blood. The King, Helm Hammerhand, took refuge in the Hornburg until aid from Gondor and Dunharrow (a refuge of the Rohirrim) arrived a year later and defeated the invaders.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/SLxeNktacYs\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>It was soon after this that Saruman arrived and took over Isengard, and was welcomed as a strong ally, since it would take Rohan close to 200 years to recover its strength after the invasion.</p><p><br/></p><p>In 3014, Saruman began using his influence to weaken the King, Th\\\\u00e9oden, as part of a campaign to invade or take over the kingdom. In 3019, he launched a great invasion of Rohan, with victory in the two first battles (at the Fords of Isen; Th\\\\u00e9oden's son, Th\\\\u00e9odred was killed during these attacks) and defeat at the Battle of the Hornburg, where the Huorns came to the aid of the Rohirrim.</p><p><br/></p><p>On the heels of this victory, Th\\\\u00e9oden rode with an army to Minas Tirith and helped break its siege in the Battle of the Pelennor Fields, where he was slain. \\\\u00c9omer, the nephew of King Th\\\\u00e9oden, then took up the reign, beginning the third line. Also in this battle, \\\\u00c9owyn, niece of King Th\\\\u00e9oden and sister of \\\\u00c9omer, slew the Lord of the Nazg\\\\u00fbl. \\\\u00c9omer rode with the armies of Gondor to the Black Gate of Mordor and took part in the Battle of the Morannon against the forces of Sauron, who were defeated when the Ruling Ring was destroyed.</p><p><br/></p><p>The rule of the Stewards of Gondor was then over. King \\\\u00c9omer and the new king of Gondor, Elessar, renewed their oath of alliance, and reaffirmed Cirion's grant of Calenardhon to the Rohirrim. At this time, \\\\u00c9owyn married Faramir, Prince of Ithilien and Steward of Gondor, thus joining the lines of Gondor and Rohan.</p><p><br/></p><p>In the Fourth Age, Rohan remained in peaceful coexistence with the Reunited Kingdom. A Dwarven community developed in the caves of Helm's Deep, which became prosperous from its mining of precious materials.</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "title": "Edoras", "pk": 16, "content_type": 6, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 12, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "path": "0001000100030005"}	\N	16	1
30	f	2017-01-12 20:23:50.81+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "mordor", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/mordor/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_world\\\\\\">fictional world</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>,\\\\u00a0<b>Mordor</b>\\\\u00a0(pronounced\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA\\\\\\">[\\\\u02c8m\\\\u0254rd\\\\u0254r]</a>; from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\\\\\">Sindarin</a>\\\\u00a0<i>Black Land</i>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quenya\\\\\\">Quenya</a>\\\\u00a0<i>Land of Shadow</i>) was the region occupied and controlled by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>, in the southeast of northwestern Middle-earth to the East of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anduin\\\\\\">Anduin</a>, the great river.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orodruin\\\\\\">Orodruin</a>, a volcano in Mordor, was the goal of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>\\\\u00a0(and later\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee\\\\\\">Sam Gamgee</a>) in the quest to destroy the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>.</p><p>Mordor has three enormous mountain ranges surrounding it, from the north, from the west and from the south. The mountains both protected the land from an unexpected invasion by any of the hosts living in those directions and kept those living in Mordor from escaping. Tolkien was reported to have identified Mordor with the volcano of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stromboli\\\\\\">Stromboli</a>\\\\u00a0off Sicily, in terms of geographic equivalency with the real world.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"style\\": \\"full\\", \\"caption\\": \\"Barad-d\\\\u00fbr looking over Mount Doom\\", \\"image\\": 16}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Geography\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Three sides of Mordor were bounded by mountain ranges, arranged in a rough rectangle: the Ered Lithui (translated as 'Ash Mountains') on the north, and the Ephel D\\\\u00faath (literally, \\\\\\"Fence of Shadow\\\\\\") on the west and the south. In the northwest the pass of Cirith Gorgor led into the enclosed plain of Ud\\\\u00fbn. Sauron built the Black Gate of Mordor (the Morannon) across the pass, joining the Towers of the Teeth, two earlier guard towers built by Gondor to keep a watch on this entrance. The passage through the inner side of Ud\\\\u00fbn into the interior of Mordor was guarded by another gate, the Isenmouthe. Outside the Morannon lay the Dagorlad or Battle Plain.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the interior within this mountainous border lay Sauron's main fortress Barad-d\\\\u00fbr, the arid plateau of Gorgoroth, and Mount Doom. To the east lay the plain of Lithlad. A narrow pass led through the Ephel D\\\\u00faath, guarded by Minas Morgul (earlier Minas Ithil). A higher, more difficult pass, Cirith Ungol, just to the north, was guarded by a tower originally built by Gondor. This pass, \\\\\\"the pass of the spider\\\\\\", was also blockaded by Torech Ungol, the lair of the giant spider Shelob. The fortress Durthang lay in the northern Ephel D\\\\u00faath above Ud\\\\u00fbn.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/jk9wwlzuwJE\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>N\\\\u00farn, the southern part of Mordor, was less arid and more fertile. Streams here fed the salt Sea of N\\\\u00farnen. Sauron's slaves farmed this region to support his armies.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Inside the Ephel D\\\\u00faath ran a lower parallel ridge, the Morgai, separated from the Ephel D\\\\u00faath by a narrow valley that Frodo and Sam followed northward after escaping from Cirith Ungol. Water trickled into this vale from the Ephel D\\\\u00faath, and the text describes it as a \\\\\\"dying land not yet dead\\\\\\". The vegetation included \\\\\\"low scrubby trees\\\\\\", \\\\\\"coarse grey grass-tussocks\\\\\\", \\\\\\"withered mosses\\\\\\", \\\\\\"great writhing, tangled brambles\\\\\\", and thickets of briars with long, stabbing thorns. The fauna included maggots, midges, and flies marked with \\\\\\"a red eye-shaped blotch\\\\\\".</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Adjacent to Mordor were, to the west, the narrow land of Ithilien (a province of Gondor); to the northwest the Dead Marshes; to the northeast Rh\\\\u00fbn; to the southeast Khand; and to the south Harad.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In The Atlas of Middle-earth, Karen Wynn Fonstad assumed that the lands of Mordor, Khand, and Rh\\\\u00fbn lay where the inland Sea of Helcar had been, and that the Sea of Rh\\\\u00fbn and Sea of N\\\\u00farnen were its remnants. This assumption stemmed from a First Age world-map drawn by Tolkien in the Ambarkanta, where the Inland Sea of Helcar occupied a large area of Middle-earth between the Ered Luin and Orocarni, with the western end being close to the head of the Great Gulf (later the Mouths of Anduin).[2] The atlas was however published before The hostss of Middle-earth, in which the Sea of Rh\\\\u00fbn and Mordor exist already in the First Age.</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": "2016-10-24T15:19:13.969Z", "show_in_menus": false, "title": "Mordor", "pk": 8, "content_type": 6, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-09T10:57:20.972Z", "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 5, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "path": "0001000100030001"}	\N	8	1
28	f	2017-01-12 20:11:19.675+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "shire", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/shire/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Shire is a region of J. R. R. Tolkien's fictional Middle-earth, described in The Lord of the Rings and other works. The Shire refers to an area settled exclusively by Hobbits and largely removed from the goings-on in the rest of Middle-earth. It is located in the northwest of the continent, in the large region of Eriador and the Kingdom of Arnor. In the languages invented by Tolkien, its name in Westron was S\\\\u00fbza \\\\\\"Shire\\\\\\"[1] or S\\\\u00fbzat \\\\\\"The Shire\\\\\\",[2] while its name in Sindarin was i Drann.[3]</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Geography\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>According to Tolkien, the Shire measured 40 leagues (193 km, 120 miles[4]) from the Far Downs in the west to the Brandywine Bridge in the east, and 50 leagues (241 km, 150 miles) from the northern moors to the marshes in the south.[5] This is confirmed in an essay by Tolkien on translating The Lord of the Rings,[6] where he describes the Shire as having an area of 18,000 square miles (47,000 km2).[7]</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/Ti5OaadrS9I\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The original territory of the Shire was bounded on the east by the Baranduin River, on the north by uplands rising to the old centre of Arnor, on the west by the White Downs, and on the south by marshland south of the River Shirebourn. After the original settlement, hobbits also expanded to the east into Buckland between the Baranduin and the Old Forest, and (much later) to the west into the Westmarch between the White Downs and the Tower Hills.[8]</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Shire was originally divided into four Farthings. The outlying lands of Buckland and the Westmarch were formally added after the War of the Ring.[5] Within the Farthings there are some smaller unofficial clan homelands: the Tooks nearly all live in or near Tuckborough in Tookland, for instance. A Hobbit surname often indicates where the family came from: Samwise Gamgee's last name derives from Gamwich, where the family originated. Buckland was named for the Oldbucks (later called the Brandybucks).</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Shire is described as a small but beautiful, idyllic and fruitful land, beloved by its inhabitants. The Hobbits had an extensive agricultural system in the Shire but were not industrialised. The landscape included small pockets of forest (again similar to the English countryside). Various supplies were produced in the Shire, including cereals, fruit, wood and pipe-weed.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Regions of the Shire\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The original parts of the Shire were subdivided into four Farthings (\\\\\\"fourth-ings\\\\\\" or \\\\\\"quarterings\\\\\\").[9] The Three-Farthing Stone marked the tripoint where the borders of the Eastfarthing, Westfarthing and Southfarthing of the Shire came together, by the East Road.[10] (Iceland was traditionally also divided in Farthings, or \\\\\\"fourth parts\\\\\\", as the Shire is.) It is claimed that the Three-Farthing Stone was inspired by the Four shire stone.[11]</p><p><br/></p><p>Buckland, across the Baranduin River to the east, and the Westmarch, between the Far Downs and the Tower Hills to the west, were not part of the original grant to the hobbits by King Argeleb II of Arthedain. These were formally given to the hobbits as the East and West Marches of the Shire by King Elessar after the War of the Ring, in S.R. 1462 (F.A. 41).[9][12] Buckland had been long settled by then: Gorhendad Oldbuck led hobbits from the East Farthing across the river in T.A. 2340,[12] and Buckland became \\\\\\"sort of a colony of the Shire\\\\\\".[13] There is no mention of settlement in the Westmarch until Elessar's gift; Sam Gamgee's daughter Elanor and her husband Fastred later settled there, and Fastred was created Warden of Westmarch.</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "title": "The Shire", "pk": 18, "content_type": 6, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 14, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "path": "0001000100030007"}	\N	18	1
56	f	2017-01-12 22:13:57.951+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "samwise-gamgee", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/samwise-gamgee/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Samwise</b>\\\\u00a0\\\\\\"<b>Sam</b>\\\\\\"\\\\u00a0<b>Gamgee</b>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English\\\\\\">/\\\\u02c8s\\\\u00e6m\\\\u02ccwa\\\\u026az\\\\u00a0\\\\u02c8\\\\u0261\\\\u00e6m\\\\u02ccd\\\\u0292i\\\\u02d0/</a>\\\\u00a0(later known as Samwise Gardner)<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee#cite_note-gardner-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_character\\\\\\">fictional character</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tolkien%27s_legendarium\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien's legendarium</a>. Samwise is one of the main characters of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>, in which he fills an\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archetype\\\\\\">archetypical</a>\\\\u00a0role as the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sidekick\\\\\\">sidekick</a>\\\\u00a0of the primary\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protagonist\\\\\\">protagonist</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>. Sam is a member of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Literature\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Samwise Gamgee is first introduced in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>. Sam is\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>' gardener, having inherited the position as Baggins' gardener from his father,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaffer_Gamgee\\\\\\">Hamfast \\\\\\"Gaffer\\\\\\" Gamgee</a>. At the time of the War of the Ring, Sam was living in Number 3,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#Bagshot_Row\\\\\\">Bagshot Row</a>\\\\u00a0with his father.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>As \\\\\\"punishment\\\\\\" for\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eavesdropping\\\\\\">eavesdropping</a>\\\\u00a0on\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>'s conversation with Frodo regarding the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>, Sam was made Frodo's first companion on his journey to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>. They were joined by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Peregrin Took</a>, Frodo's cousins, and journeyed together to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, where the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_Elrond\\\\\\">Council of Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0took place and Sam joined the Fellowship of the Ring.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>When the Fellowship was split up at the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falls_of_Rauros\\\\\\">Falls of Rauros</a>, Sam insisted on accompanying Frodo. Sam protected and cared for Frodo, who was growing weaker under the Ring's influence, as they moved through the dangerous lands toward\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>. Sam distrusted\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gollum\\\\\\">Gollum</a>, who became their guide into Mordor. His suspicions were proven right when Gollum betrayed them to the giant spider\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelob\\\\\\">Shelob</a>. After Shelob apparently killed Frodo, Sam drove her off. When a band of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0approached, Sam was forced to leave the apparently dead Frodo and take the Ring himself, and briefly became a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring-bearer\\\\\\">Ring-bearer</a>. He was momentarily tempted by its promise of power, but did not succumb to it, subsequently rescuing Frodo (who had only been paralysed) from the Orcs who held him captive. Sam also returned the Ring to Frodo, making him the only Ring-bearer to freely give up the Ring without intervention. The two then journeyed alone through Mordor and into the heart of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Doom\\\\\\">Mount Doom</a>, where Gollum attacked Frodo and reclaimed the Ring, only to inadvertently destroy both it and himself by falling into the mountain's lava.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/l1eLHoDxMNE\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After the hobbits' return home and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Bywater\\\\\\">Battle of Bywater</a>, Sam travelled the length and breadth of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0replanting trees that had been cut down during\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>'s brief reign. He used the gift of earth given to him by the Lady\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galadriel\\\\\\">Galadriel</a>, which caused the saplings he planted to grow at an accelerated rate. The small amount remaining he took to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-Farthing_Stone\\\\\\">Three-Farthing Stone</a>\\\\u00a0(roughly the centre of the Shire) and cast into the air, prompting the bountiful period of growth starting in the spring of the year 1420 (<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_Reckoning\\\\\\">Shire Reckoning</a>). The greatest wonder was a young\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mallorn\\\\\\">mallorn</a></i>\\\\u00a0tree sprouting in the Party Field: \\\\\\"the only\\\\u00a0<i>mallorn</i>\\\\u00a0west of the Mountains and east of the Sea\\\\\\" (grown from a nut included as part of Galadriel's gift).</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After the War of the Ring, Sam married\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Hobbits#Rose_Cotton\\\\\\">Rose \\\\\\"Rosie\\\\\\" Cotton</a>\\\\u00a0and moved to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bag_End\\\\\\">Bag End</a>\\\\u00a0with Frodo. Sam and Rosie had 13 children:\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elanor_the_Fair\\\\\\">Elanor the Fair</a>, Frodo, Rose, Merry, Pippin, Goldilocks, Hamfast, Daisy, Primrose, Bilbo, Ruby, Robin, and Tolman (Tom). Sam was elected\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mayor_of_the_Shire\\\\\\">Mayor of the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0for seven consecutive seven-year terms and came to be known as Samwise Gardner.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After Sam and Rose's first child was born, Frodo told Sam he would leave\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>, along with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins\\\\\\">Bilbo Baggins</a>, Gandalf and most of the remaining High\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elves</a>, for the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Undying_Lands\\\\\\">Undying Lands</a>. Before Frodo left, he gave the estate of Bag End to Sam, as well as the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Book_of_Westmarch\\\\\\">Red Book of Westmarch</a></i>\\\\u00a0for Sam to continue, hinting that Sam might also be allowed to travel into the West eventually.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After the death of his wife in the year 62 of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourth_Age\\\\\\">Fourth Age</a>\\\\u00a0(<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_Calendar\\\\\\">Shire Reckoning</a>\\\\u00a01482), Sam entrusted the Red Book to Elanor and left the Shire at the age of 102. He was not seen again in Middle-earth, but Elanor and her descendants preserved the tradition that he went to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_Havens\\\\\\">Grey Havens</a>\\\\u00a0and sailed into the West. As the last of the Ring-bearers, he was entitled to sail across the Sea and be reunited with Frodo in the Undying Lands.</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "host_place_relationship": [{"host_page": 36, "pk": 14, "place": 18}], "title": "Samwise Gamgee", "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_page": 36, "host_interests": 4, "pk": 13}], "pk": 36, "content_type": 12, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 25, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "host_experience_relationship": [{"host_page": 36, "sort_order": 0, "pk": 35, "experiences": 26}, {"host_page": 36, "sort_order": 1, "pk": 36, "experiences": 23}, {"host_page": 36, "sort_order": 2, "pk": 37, "experiences": 22}], "path": "000100010001000D"}	\N	36	1
