57	f	2017-01-12 22:18:36.654+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "gandalf", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/gandalf/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Gandalf</b>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English\\\\\\">/\\\\u02c8\\\\u0261\\\\u00e6nd\\\\u0251\\\\u02d0lf/</a><sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[2]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Character_(arts)\\\\\\">fictional character</a>\\\\u00a0and one of the protagonists in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s novels\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. He is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">wizard</a>, member of the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Istari</a></i>\\\\u00a0order, as well as leader of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>\\\\u00a0and the army of the West. In\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, he is initially known as\\\\u00a0<b>Gandalf the Grey</b>, but returns from death as\\\\u00a0<b>Gandalf the White</b>.</p><p></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"The Fellowship of the Ring\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Returning to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>, in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a03018, Gandalf confirmed his suspicions by throwing\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">the Ring</a>\\\\u00a0into\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo</a>'s hearth-fire and reading the writing that appeared on\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring#Appearance\\\\\\">the Ring's surface</a>. He told Frodo the full history of the Ring, and urged him to take the Ring to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>; for he would be in grave danger if he stayed in the Shire. Gandalf said he would attempt to return for Frodo's 50th birthday party, in order to accompany him on the road thereafter; and that meanwhile Frodo should arrange to leave quietly, as the servants of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>\\\\u00a0would be searching for him.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Outside the Shire, Gandalf encountered\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radagast_the_Brown\\\\\\">Radagast the Brown</a>, another of the Istari, who brought the news that the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl\\\\\\">Nazg\\\\u00fbl</a>\\\\u00a0had ridden forth and crossed the River\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anduin\\\\\\">Anduin</a>\\\\u2014and a request from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>\\\\u00a0that Gandalf come to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isengard\\\\\\">Isengard</a>. Gandalf left a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_objects#Gandalf.27s_letter\\\\\\">letter</a>\\\\u00a0to Frodo (urging his immediate departure) with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barliman_Butterbur\\\\\\">Barliman Butterbur</a>\\\\u00a0at the inn in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bree_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Bree</a>, and headed towards Isengard. There Saruman revealed his true colours, urging Gandalf to help him obtain the Ring for his own use. Gandalf refused, and Saruman imprisoned him at the top of the tower of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthanc\\\\\\">Orthanc</a>. Eventually Gandalf was rescued by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gwaihir\\\\\\">Gwaihir</a>\\\\u00a0the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eagle_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Eagle</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Gwaihir set Gandalf down in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>, where Gandalf appealed to King\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C3%A9oden\\\\\\">Th\\\\u00e9oden</a>\\\\u00a0for a horse. Th\\\\u00e9oden, under the malign influence of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr%C3%ADma_Wormtongue\\\\\\">Gr\\\\u00edma Wormtongue</a>, Saruman's spy, told Gandalf to take any horse he pleased, but to leave quickly. It was then that Gandalf met the great horse\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shadowfax_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Shadowfax</a>, one of the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mearas\\\\\\">mearas</a></i>, who would be his mount and companion for most of the rest of the war. Gandalf pursued the horse for two days<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf#cite_note-AppB-6\\\\\\">[6]</a>\\\\u00a0before Shadowfax permitted Gandalf to ride him. Gandalf then rode hard for the Shire, but did not reach it until Frodo had already set out. Knowing that Frodo and his companions would be heading for Rivendell, Gandalf began to make his own way there. He learned at Bree that the Hobbits had fallen in with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\\\\\">Aragorn</a>. He faced the Nazg\\\\u00fbl at\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weathertop\\\\\\">Weathertop</a>\\\\u00a0but escaped after an all-night battle, drawing four of them northward. Frodo, Aragorn and company faced the remaining five on Weathertop a few nights later. Gandalf reached Rivendell just before Frodo's arrival.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In Rivendell, Gandalf helped\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0drive off the Nazg\\\\u00fbl pursuing Frodo and played a great part in the following\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_Elrond\\\\\\">council</a>\\\\u00a0as the only person who knew the full history of the Ring. He also revealed that Saruman had betrayed them and was in league with Sauron. When it was decided that the Ring had to be destroyed, Gandalf volunteered to accompany Frodo\\\\u2014now the Ring-bearer\\\\u2014in his quest. He also persuaded Elrond to let Frodo's cousins\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Merry</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Pippin</a>\\\\u00a0join the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Taking charge of the Fellowship (comprising nine representatives of the free hostss of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>, \\\\\\"set against the Nine Riders\\\\\\"), Gandalf and Aragorn led the Hobbits and their companions south. After an unsuccessful attempt to cross Mount\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caradhras\\\\\\">Caradhras</a>\\\\u00a0in winter, they crossed\\\\u00a0<i>under</i>\\\\u00a0the mountains through the Mines of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moria_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Moria</a>, though only\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gimli_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Gimli</a>\\\\u00a0the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwarf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Dwarf</a>\\\\u00a0was enthusiastic about that route. In Moria, they discovered that the Dwarf colony established there earlier had been overrun by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Orcs</a>. The Fellowship fought with the Orcs and Trolls of Moria and escaped them.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>At the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bridge_of_Khazad-d%C3%BBm\\\\\\">Bridge of Khazad-d\\\\u00fbm</a>, they encountered \\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balrog#Durin.27s_Bane\\\\\\">Durin's Bane</a>,\\\\\\" a fearsome\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balrog\\\\\\">Balrog</a>\\\\u00a0from ancient times. Gandalf faced the Balrog to enable the others to escape. After a brief exchange of blows, Gandalf broke the bridge beneath the Balrog with his\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magic_(Middle-earth)#Magic_items\\\\\\">staff</a>. As the Balrog fell, it wrapped its whip around Gandalf's legs, dragging him over the edge. As his friends looked on in horror, Gandalf fell into the abyss, crying \\\\\\"Fly, you fools!\\\\\\" as he went.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After a long fall, Gandalf and the Balrog crashed into a deep subterranean lake far under Moria. Gandalf pursued the Balrog through the tunnels for eight days until they climbed to the peak of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minor_places_in_Middle-earth#Celebdil\\\\\\">Zirakzigil</a>. Here they fought for two days and nights. In the end, the Balrog was defeated and cast down onto the mountainside. Gandalf himself died shortly afterwards, and his body lay on the peak while his spirit travelled \\\\\\"out of thought and time\\\\\\".</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "host_place_relationship": [{"host_page": 37, "pk": 15, "place": 12}], "title": "Gandalf", "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_page": 37, "host_interests": 3, "pk": 14}], "pk": 37, "content_type": 12, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 26, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "host_experience_relationship": [{"host_page": 37, "sort_order": 0, "pk": 38, "experiences": 6}, {"host_page": 37, "sort_order": 1, "pk": 39, "experiences": 20}, {"host_page": 37, "sort_order": 2, "pk": 40, "experiences": 21}], "path": "000100010001000E"}	\N	37	1
53	f	2017-01-12 22:03:52.86+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "sauron", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/sauron/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Sauron</b>,\\\\u00a0pronounced\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA\\\\\\">[\\\\u02c8sa\\\\u028ar\\\\u0254n]</a>,<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0is the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Title_character\\\\\\">title character</a><sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-3\\\\\\">[note 1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0and main antagonist of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. In the same work, he is identified as the\\\\u00a0<b>Necromancer</b>, mentioned in Tolkien's earlier novel\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>. In Tolkien's\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Silmarillion\\\\\\">The Silmarillion</a></i>\\\\u00a0(published posthumously by Tolkien's son\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christopher_Tolkien\\\\\\">Christopher Tolkien</a>),<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-4\\\\\\">[3]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0he is also described as the chief lieutenant of the first\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dark_Lord_(fiction)\\\\\\">Dark Lord</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morgoth\\\\\\">Morgoth</a>. Tolkien noted that the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainur_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">\\\\\\"angelic\\\\\\" powers of his constructed myth</a>\\\\u00a0\\\\\\"were capable of many degrees of error and failing\\\\\\", but by far the worst was \\\\\\"the absolute\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satan\\\\\\">Satanic</a>\\\\u00a0rebellion and evil of Morgoth and his satellite Sauron\\\\\\".<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-5\\\\\\">[4]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Biography\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Before creation of the world\\", \\"size\\": \\"h3\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainulindal%C3%AB\\\\\\">Ainulindal\\\\u00eb</a></i>, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creation_myth\\\\\\">cosmological myth</a>\\\\u00a0prefixed to\\\\u00a0<i>The Silmarillion</i>, explains how the supreme being\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eru_Il%C3%BAvatar\\\\\\">Eru</a>\\\\u00a0initiated his creation by bringing into being innumerable spirits, \\\\\\"the offspring of his thought\\\\\\", who were with him before anything else had been made. The being later known as Sauron originated as an \\\\\\"immortal (angelic) spirit\\\\\\".<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters243-6\\\\\\">[5]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0In his origin, Sauron therefore perceived the Creator directly. As Tolkien noted: \\\\\\"Sauron could not, of course, be a 'sincere'\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atheist\\\\\\">atheist</a>. Though one of the minor spirits created before the world, he knew Eru, according to his measure.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-ME-ref.7CMR.7Cp._397-7\\\\\\">[6]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the terminology of Tolkien's\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_language\\\\\\">invented language</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quenya\\\\\\">Quenya</a>, these angelic spirits were called\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainur_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Ainur</a>. Those who entered the physical world were called\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vala_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Valar</a>, especially the most powerful ones. The (mostly) lesser beings who entered the world, of whom Sauron was one, were called\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maia_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Maiar</a>. In Tolkien's letters, the author noted that Sauron \\\\\\"was of course a '<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divinity\\\\\\">divine</a>' person (in the terms of this mythology; a lesser member of the race of Valar)\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters205-8\\\\\\">[7]</a>\\\\u00a0Tolkien noted that he was of a \\\\\\"far higher order\\\\\\" than the Maiar who later came to Middle-earth as the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Wizards</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters243fn-9\\\\\\">[8]</a>\\\\u00a0As created by Eru, the Ainur were all good and uncorrupt, as\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0stated in\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>: \\\\\\"Nothing is evil in the beginning. Even Sauron was not so.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-10\\\\\\">[9]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Rebellion originated with the Vala\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morgoth\\\\\\">Melkor</a>. According to a story meant as a parable of events beyond\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elvish</a>\\\\u00a0comprehension,<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-11\\\\\\">[10]</a>\\\\u00a0Eru let his spirit-children perform a great Music, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainulindal%C3%AB\\\\\\">Music of the Ainur</a>, developing a theme revealed by Eru himself. For a while the cosmic choir made wondrous music, but then Melkor tried to increase his own glory by weaving into his song thoughts and ideas that were not in accordance with the original theme. \\\\\\"Straightway discord arose around him, and many that sang nigh him grew despondent ... but some began to attune their music to his rather than to the thought which they had at first.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-12\\\\\\">[11]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The discord Melkor created would have dire consequences, as this singing was a kind of template for the world: \\\\\\"The evils of the world were not at first in the great Theme, but entered with the discords of Melkor.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-13\\\\\\">[12]</a>\\\\u00a0However, \\\\\\"Sauron was not a beginner of discord; and he probably knew more of the Music than did Melkor, whose mind had always been filled with his own plans and devices.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-14\\\\\\">[13]</a>\\\\u00a0Apparently Sauron was not even one of the spirits that immediately began to attune their music to that of Melkor, since it is noted elsewhere that his fall occurred later (<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#Sauron.27s_fall\\\\\\">see below</a>).</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The cosmic Music now represented the conflict between\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Good_and_evil\\\\\\">good and evil</a>. Finally, Eru abruptly brought the Song of Creation to an end. To show the spirits, faithful or otherwise, what they had done, Eru gave independent being to the now-marred Music. This resulted in the manifestation of the material World,\\\\u00a0<i>E\\\\u00e4</i>, where the drama of good and evil would play out and be resolved.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"First Age\\", \\"size\\": \\"h3\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the terminology of Tolkien's\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_language\\\\\\">invented language</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quenya\\\\\\">Quenya</a>, these angelic spirits were called\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainur_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Ainur</a>. Those who entered the physical world were called\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vala_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Valar</a>, especially the most powerful ones. The (mostly) lesser beings who entered the world, of whom Sauron was one, were called\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maia_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Maiar</a>. In Tolkien's letters, the author noted that Sauron \\\\\\"was of course a '<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divinity\\\\\\">divine</a>' person (in the terms of this mythology; a lesser member of the race of Valar)\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters205-8\\\\\\">[7]</a>\\\\u00a0Tolkien noted that he was of a \\\\\\"far higher order\\\\\\" than the Maiar who later came to Middle-earth as the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Wizards</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters243fn-9\\\\\\">[8]</a>\\\\u00a0As created by Eru, the Ainur were all good and uncorrupt, as\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0stated in\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>: \\\\\\"Nothing is evil in the beginning. Even Sauron was not so.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-10\\\\\\">[9]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Sauron's fall\\", \\"size\\": \\"h4\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Melkor opposed the other Valar, who remained faithful to Eru and tried to carry out the Creator's designs. Within the larger universe, they eventually focused on developing the world of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arda_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Arda</a>\\\\u00a0(Earth, or the entire solar system). Around this time, Sauron fell victim to Melkor's corrupting influence: \\\\\\"In the beginning of Arda, Melkor seduced him to his allegiance.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-18\\\\\\">[17]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>As for Sauron's motives, Tolkien noted that \\\\\\"it had been his virtue (and therefore also the cause of his fall ...) that he loved order and coordination, and disliked all confusion and wasteful friction\\\\\\". Thus \\\\\\"it was the apparent will and power of Melkor to effect his designs quickly and masterfully that had first attracted Sauron to him\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-19\\\\\\">[18]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>For a while, Sauron apparently kept up the pretence that he was a faithful servant of the Valar, all the while feeding Melkor information about their doings. Thus, when the Valar made\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almaren\\\\\\">Almaren</a>\\\\u00a0as their first physical abode in the world, \\\\\\"Melkor knew of all that was done; for even then he had secret friends and spies among the Maiar whom he had converted to his cause, and of these the chief, as after became known, was Sauron.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-ME-ref.7CMR.7Cp._52-15\\\\\\">[14]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Melkor soon destroyed Almaren, and the Valar established a new abode in the Uttermost West: the Blessed Realm of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valinor\\\\\\">Valinor</a>. They still did not perceive Sauron's treachery, for he too became \\\\\\"a being of Valinor\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters151-20\\\\\\">[19]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>At some point, Sauron left the Blessed Realm and went to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>, the central continent of Arda, where Melkor had established his stronghold. In one text, Tolkien wrote of Sauron that \\\\\\"in Valinor he had dwelt among the hosts of the gods, but there Morgoth had drawn him to evil and to his service\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-21\\\\\\">[20]</a>\\\\u00a0Sauron deserted his service to the Valar and openly joined their great enemy: \\\\\\"Because of his admiration of Strength he had become a follower of Morgoth and fell with him down into the depths of evil.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters243fn-9\\\\\\">[8]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"The Lieutenant of Melkor\\", \\"size\\": \\"h4\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After joining his new master in Middle-earth, Sauron proved to be a devoted and capable servant: \\\\\\"While Morgoth still stood, Sauron did not seek his own supremacy, but worked and schemed for another, desiring the triumph of Melkor, whom in the beginning he had adored. He thus was often able to achieve things, first conceived by Melkor, which his master did not or could not complete in the furious haste of his malice.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-ME-ref.7CMR.7Cp._420-22\\\\\\">[21]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0\\\\\\"In all the deeds of Melkor the Morgoth upon Arda, in his vast works and in the deceits of his cunning, Sauron had a part.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-23\\\\\\">[22]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In chapter three of\\\\u00a0<i>The Silmarillion</i>, Tolkien writes that by the time the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elves</a>\\\\u00a0awoke in the world, Sauron had become Melkor's lieutenant and was given command over the newly built stronghold of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angband\\\\\\">Angband</a>. To protect the Elves, the Valar made war on Melkor and captured him, but could not find Sauron.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Thus, \\\\\\"when Melkor was made captive, Sauron escaped and lay hid in Middle-earth; and it can in this way be understood how the breeding of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Orcs</a>\\\\u00a0(no doubt already begun) went on with increasing speed\\\\\\". In the Blessed Realm, Melkor feigned reform, but eventually escaped back to Middle-earth, holding the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silmaril\\\\\\">Silmarils</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F%C3%ABanor\\\\\\">F\\\\u00ebanor</a>. By then, Sauron had \\\\\\"secretly repaired Angband for the help of his Master when he returned; and there the dark places underground were already manned with hosts of the Orcs before Melkor came back at last, as Morgoth the Black Enemy\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-24\\\\\\">[23]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Shortly after the return of Morgoth, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noldor\\\\\\">Noldorin</a>\\\\u00a0Elves also left the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blessed_Realm_of_Valinor\\\\\\">Blessed Realm of Valinor</a>\\\\u00a0in the Uttermost West, against the counsel of the Valar, to wage war on Morgoth, who had stolen the Silmarils. In that war, Sauron served as Morgoth's chief lieutenant, surpassing all others in rank, such as\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gothmog\\\\\\">Gothmog</a>, the Lord of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balrog\\\\\\">Balrogs</a>. Known as\\\\u00a0<b>Gorthaur the Cruel</b>, Sauron was at that time a master of illusions and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shapeshifting\\\\\\">shapeshifting</a>;\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Werewolf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">werewolves</a>\\\\u00a0and vampires were his servants, chief among them\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Draugluin\\\\\\">Draugluin</a>, Father of Werewolves, and his vampire herald\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thuringwethil\\\\\\">Thuringwethil</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>When Morgoth left Angband to corrupt the newly discovered\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Men</a>, Sauron directed the war against the Elves. He conquered the Elvish island of Tol Sirion and its watchtower\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith_(First_Age)\\\\\\">Minas Tirith</a>, so that it became known as\\\\u00a0<i>Tol-in-Gaurhoth,</i>\\\\u00a0the Isle of Werewolves.</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "host_place_relationship": [{"host_page": 33, "pk": 11, "place": 8}], "title": "Sauron", "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_page": 33, "host_interests": 3, "pk": 10}], "pk": 33, "content_type": 12, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "depth": 4, "live": true,