p valley of the cleft\\\\\\". The name Rivendell is formed by two English elements: \\\\\\"riven\\\\\\" (split, cloven) and \\\\\\"dell\\\\\\" (valley), making the whole word purport \\\\\\"deeply cloven valley\\\\\\". Imladris was also rendered \\\\\\"<i>Karningul</i>\\\\\\" in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Westron\\\\\\">Westron</a>, the \\\\\\"Common Tongue\\\\\\" of Middle-Earth represented as English in the text of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings.</i>\\\\u00a0It is also referred to as\\\\u00a0<i>The Last Homely House,</i>\\\\u00a0alluding to the elves' old cities, in Beleriand and Aman, and the wilderness (Rhovanion) that lies east of the Misty Mountains.<br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Legacy\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\", \\"value\\": {\\"text\\": \\"Evil things do not come into this valley... We are sitting in a fortress. Outside it is getting dark.\\", \\"attribute_group\\": \\"Fellowship of the Ring\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Gandalf\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the period of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Counterculture\\\\\\">counterculture</a>\\\\u00a0in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_World\\\\\\">Western World</a>\\\\u00a0of the 1960s and 1970s, a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commune\\\\\\">commune</a>\\\\u00a0called\\\\u00a0<i>Maos Lyst</i>\\\\u00a0(<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mao_Zedong\\\\\\">Mao</a>'s Delight) was founded in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denmark\\\\\\">Denmark</a>\\\\u00a0in 1968, its inhabitants replacing their surnames with\\\\u00a0<i>Kl\\\\u00f8vedal</i>, Danish for Rivendell, inspired by Tolkien's Elven outpost.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell#cite_note-6\\\\\\">[6]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0Several of them later became well-known cultural personalities in the country.</p><p>The Canadian progressive rock band\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rush_(band)\\\\\\">Rush</a>\\\\u00a0memorializes Rivendell in the song \\\\\\"Rivendell\\\\\\" on their second studio album\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fly_by_Night_(album)\\\\\\">Fly By Night</a></i>. The song focuses on the tranquillity and seemingly endless time a weary traveller could find there.</p><p>The Austrian folk band Rivendell takes the material for their lyrics almost entirely from Tolkien's books.</p><p>A Californian manufacturer of bicycles,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell_Bicycle_Works\\\\\\">Rivendell Bicycle Works</a>, also uses the name, inspired by the book and a United States backpacking supply company founded in the 1970s called\\\\u00a0Rivendell Mountain Works. They take many of the names of their bicycle models from Tolkien.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell#cite_note-7\\\\\\">[7]</a></sup></p>\\"}]", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "slug": "rivendell", "pk": 19, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-16T22:08:32.876Z", "owner": 1, "live": true, "content_type": 6, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/rivendell/", "expired": false, "numchild": 0, "go_live_at": null, "locked": false, "title": "Rivendell", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:16:17.742Z"}	\N	19	1
52	f	2017-01-12 21:59:11.525+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "shelob", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/shelob/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Shelob</b>\\\\u00a0is a fictional\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spider_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">giant spider</a>\\\\u00a0from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legendarium\\\\\\">legendarium</a>. She appears at the end of the fourth book, second volume (<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\\\\\">The Two Towers</a></i>), of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. Her lair lies in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cirith_Ungol\\\\\\">Cirith Ungol</a>\\\\u00a0(\\\\\\"the pass of the spider\\\\\\") leading into\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gollum\\\\\\">Gollum</a>\\\\u00a0deliberately leads\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>\\\\u00a0there in hopes of recovering the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>\\\\u00a0when Shelob attacks Frodo. The plan is foiled when\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee\\\\\\">Samwise Gamgee</a>\\\\u00a0greatly injures Shelob with Frodo's Elvish dagger,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sting_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Sting</a>, and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phial_of_Galadriel\\\\\\">Phial of Galadriel</a>.</p><p></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Literature\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Shelob was an \\\\\\"evil thing in spider form...[the] last child of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ungoliant\\\\\\">Ungoliant</a>\\\\u00a0to trouble the unhappy world\\\\\\",<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelob#cite_note-TTT_book_4_ch_9-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0living high in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ephel_D%C3%BAath\\\\\\">Ephel D\\\\u00faath</a>\\\\u00a0mountains on the borders of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>. There are numerous references to her predating the events of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>\\\\u00a0by many ages. Although she resided in Mordor and was unrepentantly evil, she was independent of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>\\\\u00a0and his influence.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelob#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[2]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>This creature makes her first appearance in the chapter \\\\\\"The Stairs of Cirith Ungol\\\\\\", though she is formally introduced in the next chapter \\\\\\"Shelob's Lair\\\\\\" where the author says \\\\\\"But still she was there, who was there before Sauron, and before the first stone of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barad-d%C3%BBr\\\\\\">Barad-d\\\\u00fbr</a>; and she served none but herself, drinking the blood of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elves</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Men</a>, bloated and grown fat with endless brooding on her feasts, weaving webs of shadow; for all living things were her food, and her vomit darkness\\\\\\". Her descendants include the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spider_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Giant Spiders</a>\\\\u00a0defeated by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins\\\\\\">Bilbo Baggins</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Shelob's lair was\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Torech_Ungol\\\\\\">Torech Ungol</a>, below Cirith Ungol (\\\\\\"Pass of the Spider\\\\\\"), along the path that\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sam_Gamgee\\\\\\">Sam Gamgee</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>\\\\u00a0took into Mordor, where Shelob had encountered Gollum during his previous trip to Mordor, and he apparently worshipped her. The\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Orcs</a>\\\\u00a0of the Tower of Cirith Ungol called her \\\\\\"Shelob the Great\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"Her Ladyship\\\\\\", and referred to Gollum as \\\\\\"Her Sneak\\\\\\". Sauron himself was aware of her existence, but left her alone, as a useful guard on the pass, and occasionally fed prisoners to her. In the story, Gollum led the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit\\\\\\">Hobbits</a>\\\\u00a0into her lair to himself recover the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>\\\\u00a0after she consumed them. She cornered them; but Frodo used the Phial of Galadriel's light to drive her off, and used Sting to cut the webs blocking the tunnel. Gollum waylaid the pair and tried to strangle Sam, while Shelob paralysed Frodo; whereafter Sam fought off Gollum and then wielded Sting against Shelob. Seeking to crush Sam, she instead impaled herself upon\\\\u00a0<i>Sting</i>; and was nearly blinded by the Phial of Galadriel; whereupon she fled. Thinking Frodo dead, Sam took the Ring from his friend and left his body behind, but discovered by listening to a pair of Orcs that Frodo was alive but senseless, under a minor influence of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Venom\\\\\\">venom</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/pA0ffVBw584\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Name\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>As Tolkien admitted in a letter to his son, Shelob \\\\\\"is of course only 'she + lob',\\\\\\" -\\\\u00a0<i>lob</i>\\\\u00a0being an archaic English word for spider, influenced by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_English\\\\\\">Old English</a>\\\\u00a0<i>loppe</i>\\\\u00a0or \\\\\\"spider\\\\\\". The word is not related to \\\\\\"cob\\\\\\" nor \\\\\\"cobweb\\\\\\".\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_English\\\\\\">Old English</a>\\\\u00a0<i>attercoppe</i>\\\\u00a0(meaning \\\\\\"spider\\\\\\") is derived from\\\\u00a0<i>atter</i>\\\\u00a0meaning \\\\\\"poison\\\\\\" and\\\\u00a0<i>coppe</i>\\\\u00a0meaning \\\\\\"head\\\\\\"; Tolkien used \\\\\\"attercop\\\\\\" as well as \\\\\\"cob\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"lob\\\\\\" in\\\\u00a0<i>The Hobbit</i>, where Bilbo Baggins sings songs taunting the giant spiders in Mirkwood: \\\\\\"Attercop, Attercop, Old Tomnoddy\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"Lazy Lob and Crazy Cob\\\\\\".<sup>[<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\\\\\\">citation needed</a></i>]</sup></p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T21:55:58.885Z", "show_in_menus": false, "host_place_relationship": [{"host_page": 32, "pk": 10, "place": 8}], "title": "Shelob", "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_page": 32, "host_interests": 6, "pk": 9}], "pk": 32, "content_type": 12, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T21:55:58.826Z", "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 23, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "