46	f	2017-01-12 21:35:51.073+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "saruman", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/saruman/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Saruman the White</b>\\\\u00a0is a fictional character and a major antagonist in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s fantasy novel\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. He is leader of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Istari</a>, wizards sent to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>\\\\u00a0in human form by the godlike\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vala_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Valar</a>\\\\u00a0to challenge\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>, the main antagonist of the novel, but eventually he desires Sauron's power for himself and tries to take over Middle-earth by force. His schemes feature prominently in the second volume,\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\\\\\">The Two Towers</a></i>, and at the end of the third volume,\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\\\\\">The Return of the King</a></i>. His earlier history is given briefly in the posthumously published\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Silmarillion\\\\\\">The Silmarillion</a></i>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unfinished_Tales\\\\\\">Unfinished Tales</a></i>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Saruman is one of several characters in the book illustrating the corruption of power; his desire for knowledge and order leads to his fall, and he rejects the chance of redemption when it is offered. The name\\\\u00a0<i>Saruman</i>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA\\\\\\">[\\\\u02c8saruman]</a>\\\\u00a0means \\\\\\"man of experience\\\\\\" in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercian_(Anglo-Saxon)\\\\\\">Mercian dialect</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_English_language\\\\\\">Anglo-Saxon</a>;<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0he serves as an example of technology and modernity being overthrown by forces more in tune with nature. Saruman is represented by a white hand.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Characterisation\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Tolkien described Saruman at the time of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>\\\\u00a0as having a long face and a high forehead, \\\\\\"...he had deep darkling eyes ... His hair and beard were white, but strands of black still showed around his lips and ears.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Orthanc-24\\\\\\">[24]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0His hair is elsewhere described as having been black when he first arrived in Middle-earth. He is referred to as 'Saruman the White' and is said to have originally worn white robes, but on his first entry in\\\\u00a0<i>The Fellowship of the Ring</i>\\\\u00a0they instead appear to be \\\\\\"woven from all colours [, they] shimmered and changed hue so that the eye was bewildered\\\\\\" and he names himself 'Saruman of Many Colours'.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Saru1-25\\\\\\">[25]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/TQq4LjSF2rc\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The power of Saruman's voice is noted throughout the book. Jonathan Evans calls the characterization of Saruman in the chapter\\\\u00a0<i>The Voice of Saruman</i>\\\\u00a0a \\\\\\"tour de force\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Evans-20\\\\\\">[20]</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Sale\\\\\\">Roger Sale</a>\\\\u00a0says of the same chapter that \\\\\\"Tolkien valiantly tried to do something worth doing which he simply cannot bring off.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-26\\\\\\">[26]</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Shippey\\\\\\">Tom Shippey</a>\\\\u00a0writes that \\\\\\"Saruman talks like a politician ... No other character in Middle-earth has Saruman's trick of balancing phrases against each other so that incompatibles are resolved, and none comes out with words as empty as 'deploring', 'ultimate', worst of all, 'real'. What is 'real change'?\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-elcoun-27\\\\\\">[27]</a>Shippey contrasts this modern speech pattern with the archaic stoicism and directness that Tolkien employs for other characters such as the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwarf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Dwarven</a>\\\\u00a0King\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D%C3%A1in_II_Ironfoot\\\\\\">D\\\\u00e1in</a>, which Shippey believes represent Tolkien's view of heroism in the mould of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beowulf\\\\\\">Beowulf</a></i>.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-elcoun-27\\\\\\">[27]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After the defeat of his armies, having been caught in the betrayal of Sauron, Saruman is offered refuge by Gandalf, in return for his aid, but having chosen his path, is unable to turn from it.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Spacks2-28\\\\\\">[28]</a>\\\\u00a0Evans has compared the character of Saruman to that of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satan\\\\\\">Satan</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Milton\\\\\\">John Milton</a>'s\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paradise_Lost\\\\\\">Paradise Lost</a></i>\\\\u00a0in his use of rhetoric and in this final refusal of redemption, \\\\\\"conquered by pride and hatred\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman#cite_note-Evans-20\\\\\\">[20]</a></p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "host_place_relationship": [{"host_page": 27, "pk": 5, "place": 14}], "title": "Saruman", "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_page": 27, "host_interests": 3, "pk": 4}], "pk": 27, "content_type": 12, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 18, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "host_experience_relationship": [{"host_page": 27, "sort_order": 0, "pk": 10, "experiences": 6}, {"host_page": 27, "sort_order": 1, "pk": 11, "experiences": 24}], "path": "0001000100010004"}	\N	27	1
45	f	2017-01-12 21:19:17.059+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "boromir", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/boromir/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Boromir</b>\\\\u00a0is a character in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legendarium\\\\\\">legendarium</a>. He appears in the first two volumes of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>\\\\u00a0(<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\\\\\">The Two Towers</a></i>), and is mentioned in the last volume,\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\\\\\">The Return of the King</a></i>. He is the heir of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denethor\\\\\\">Denethor II</a>\\\\u00a0(the 26th\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stewards_of_Gondor\\\\\\">Ruling Steward</a>of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondor</a>) and the elder brother of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faramir\\\\\\">Faramir</a>. In the course of the story Boromir joins the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Boromir is portrayed as a noble character who believes passionately in the greatness of his kingdom, who would have defended its hosts to the last. Boromir's great stamina and physical strength, together with a forceful and commanding personality, made him a widely admired commander in Gondor's army: he was made Captain of the White Tower, and quickly became Captain-General, also bearing the title High Warden of the White Tower. He was also heir apparent to the Stewardship. Boromir led many successful forays against\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>'s forces, prior to his journey north to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, which brought him great esteem in the eyes of his father, Denethor.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Literature\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Boromir, as a character, is portrayed as having been born in the year 2978 of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">Third Age</a>\\\\u00a0to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denethor_II\\\\\\">Denethor II</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finduilas_of_Dol_Amroth\\\\\\">Finduilas</a>, daughter of Adrahil of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dol_Amroth\\\\\\">Dol Amroth</a>. His younger brother,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faramir\\\\\\">Faramir</a>, was born in the year\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a02983. The following year, Denethor became Steward of Gondor, succeeding his father,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ecthelion_II\\\\\\">Ecthelion II</a>. Boromir simultaneously became heir apparent, inheriting the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horn_of_Gondor\\\\\\">Horn of Gondor</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Boromir was named after the son of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denethor_I\\\\\\">Denethor I</a>, who was Steward around 500 years before the War of the Ring. The\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir_(Steward)\\\\\\">first Boromir</a>\\\\u00a0was known as a great captain who cleared\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ithilien\\\\\\">Ithilien</a>\\\\u00a0of orcs of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>\\\\u00a0and was feared even by the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witch-king\\\\\\">Witch-king</a>\\\\u00a0himself. Thus there were high expectations for Boromir the son of Denethor II.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\", \\"value\\": {\\"attribute_group\\": \\"\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Boromir\\", \\"text\\": \\"It is a strange fate that we should suffer so much fear and doubt over so small a thing. Such a little thing.\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>When Boromir's mother Finduilas died (<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a02988), he was aged only 10. Denethor became sombre, cold and detached from his family. As their father withdrew, the relationship between Faramir and Boromir grew closer and greater in love. Denethor always favoured Boromir over Faramir\\\\u2014Denethor loved Boromir \\\\\\"too much, perhaps; the more so because they were unlike\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir#cite_note-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u2014but this caused no rivalry between the two brothers. Boromir always protected and helped Faramir. Boromir was judged to be the more daring one, as well as the more fearless.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In response to prophetic dreams that came to Faramir and later to himself, Boromir claimed the quest of riding to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>\\\\u00a0from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith\\\\\\">Minas Tirith</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a03018. His journey lasted a hundred and eleven days, and he travelled through \\\\\\"roads forgotten\\\\\\" to reach Rivendell, though, as he said, \\\\\\"few knew where it lay\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[2]</a>\\\\u00a0Boromir lost his horse halfway along, while crossing the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greyflood\\\\\\">Greyflood</a>at the ruined city of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tharbad\\\\\\">Tharbad</a>\\\\u00a0where the bridge was broken. He had to travel the remaining way on foot<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir#cite_note-3\\\\\\">[3]</a>\\\\u00a0and barely arrived in time for the Council of Elrond. (Tolkien wrote of Boromir's journey that \\\\\\"the courage and hardihood required is not fully recognized in the narrative\\\\\\".)<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir#cite_note-4\\\\\\">[4]</a></p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": "2017-01-09T10:58:20.579Z", "show_in_menus": false, "host_place_relationship": [{"host_page": 13, "pk": 4, "place": 8}], "title": "Boromir", "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_page": 13, "host_interests": 1, "pk": 1}], "pk": 13, "content_type": 12, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-10T17:49:07Z", "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 6, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "host_experience_relationship": [{"host_page": 13, "sort_order": 0, "pk": null, "experiences": 21}, {"host_page": 13, "sort_order": 1, "pk": null, "experiences": 26}, {"host_page": 13, "sort_order": 2, "pk": null, "experiences": 23}], "path": "0001000100010003"}	\N	13	1
24	f	2017-01-12 19:51:42.977+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "helms-deep", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/helms-deep/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0J. R. R. Tolkien's\\\\u00a0Middle-earth\\\\u00a0high fantasy\\\\u00a0writings,\\\\u00a0<b>Helm's Deep</b>\\\\u00a0was a large valley in the north-western\\\\u00a0Ered Nimrais\\\\u00a0(White Mountains).</p><p>The valley was described as being blocked over its entire width by the natural series of hills called\\\\u00a0<b>Helm's Dike</b>\\\\u00a0and behind that lay the fortress of Aglarond or the\\\\u00a0<b>Hornburg</b>, at the entrance to the Glittering Caves.</p><p>In the Appendices of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, the history of the valley states that it was home to a small\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondorian</a>\\\\u00a0regiment, but after the place which was called\\\\u00a0Calenardhon\\\\u00a0became\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>, it became an encampment of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)#hosts\\\\\\">Rohirrim</a>, where the guards of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fords_of_Isen\\\\\\">Fords of Isen</a>\\\\u00a0lived.</p><p>It also states that during the war with the\\\\u00a0Dunlendings\\\\u00a0under\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wulf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Wulf</a>, the Rohirrim under King\\\\u00a0Helm Hammerhand\\\\u00a0and many of his hosts sought refuge in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keep\\\\\\">keep</a>, where they held out during the winter of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a02758\\\\u20132759.</p><p>The castle itself was described as having a long causeway which wound up to the great gate of the fortress itself. Inside the keep there were stables and an armoury, as well as a great hall in the rear which was dug out of the mountainside. There also was a great tower (the Hornburg) the top of which consisted of the great horn of\\\\u00a0Helm Hammerhand. The Deep, which was described as standing next to the fortress, was barred by the long Deeping Wall, which was described as consisting of solid rock except for a small culvert which allowed water from the Deeping Stream to enter; this rendered a fresh supply in sieges of great length. The Deeping Wall itself is described as standing 20 feet tall; and also being wide enough for four men to stand side by side. Access to the fortress from within the Deep was made possible by a long stair which led to the Hornburg's rear gate.</p><p>In\\\\u00a0<i>The Two Towers</i>, the fortress guarding Helm's Deep becomes the refuge of the main army of the Rohirrim, under King\\\\u00a0Th\\\\u00e9oden\\\\u00a0during the\\\\u00a0War of the Ring. Th\\\\u00e9oden said that \\\\\\"the Hornburg has never fallen to assault\\\\\\" giving an impression of invulnerability. This was tested during the\\\\u00a0Battle of the Hornburg, as a massive army of\\\\u00a0Uruk-hai\\\\u00a0sent by\\\\u00a0Saruman\\\\u00a0almost overwhelmed the defences of the Rohirrim. Saruman's\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0used an explosive blast of fire within the culvert which, when detonated, breached the long Deeping Wall. The origin of this explosion is unclear and Tolkien denotes it as \\\\\\"Saruman's devilry\\\\\\". The Rohirrim defenders held out long enough in the fortress until dawn, giving Gandalf time to gather and lead a counter-attack, while Th\\\\u00e9oden led a cavalry charge that drove the Orcs from the fortress.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"style\\": \\"full\\", \\"caption\\": \\"Crest of Gondor, keepers of the Helm\\", \\"image\\": 9}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Aglarond\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Aglarond and Angrenost (which later became Isengard) were the two fortresses built by Gondor to guard the approaches to the Fords of Isen. Like Angrenost to the north, it was initially well guarded, but as the population of Calenardhon (the later Rohan) dwindled it was not maintained and, losing importance, was left to a hereditary small guard who intermarried with Dunlendings.</p><p><br/></p><p>When Cirion, Steward of Gondor, gave Calenardhon to the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od, Aglarond was transferred into the care of the Rohirrim, who named it S\\\\u00fathburg (southern burg in their language). The Gondorian guard was merged with that of Angrenost to the north, which remained in the keep of Gondor. Guard duty of the Fords was initially shared between Gondor and Rohan, but later maintained only by the Rohirrim.</p><p><br/></p><p>During the reign of Helm Hammerhand, Rohan was attacked by Dunlendings from across the river Isen. Edoras was taken, and Helm and many of his hosts retreated to S\\\\u00fathburg. Because Helm always blew a great horn before riding out to fight the beleaguering Dunlendings, the keep was renamed Hornburg. During the War of the Ring, the Hornburg was the refuge of the Rohirrim as they defended Helm's Deep.</p><p><br/></p><p>After the war, Gimli the Dwarf, who fought in that battle, established a colony of Durin's folk there. Aglarond lay in front of a huge and very beautiful cave system, which proved irresistible to him. Gimli became known as 'the Lord of the Glittering Caves', although this new realm was presumably under the overlordship of Thorin Stonehelm, his kinsman and heir of the lordship of all Durin's Folk. The dwarves of Aglarond restored the Hornburg following the War of the Ring, and it became a fortress they shared with the Rohirrim.</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "title": "Helm's Deep", "pk": 15, "content_type": 6, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 10, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "path": "0001000100030004"}	\N	15	1
49	f	2017-01-12 21:48:59.985+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "treebeard", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/treebeard/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Treebeard</b>\\\\u00a0(<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\\\\\">Sindarin</a>:\\\\u00a0<i>Fangorn</i>) is a fictional character from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tolkien%27s_legendarium\\\\\\">fantasy writings</a>. The eldest of the species of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ent\\\\\\">Ents</a>, he is said to live in the ancient\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fangorn\\\\\\">Forest of Fangorn</a>\\\\u00a0and stands fourteen feet (4 m) in height. He is treelike in appearance, with leafy hair and a rigid structure.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0His home of Fangorn Forest lies next to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isengard\\\\\\">Isengard</a>, where\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman the White</a>\\\\u00a0resides. Treebeard's motto is \\\\\\"Do not be hasty.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\\\\\">The Two Towers</a></i>\\\\u00a0he meets with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Peregrin Took</a>, two\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit\\\\\\">Hobbits</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0known also as Merry and Pippin.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0Treebeard is known to have a strong hatred of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Orcs</a>, and, after Saruman's betrayal of the Ents, of Saruman as well.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\\\\\">[1]</a><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-AofAW2-2\\\\\\">[2]</a>\\\\u00a0During his initial encounter with the two hobbits, he is so agitated that he misidentifies them as orc spies. He then carries them to the white wizard.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Spirits were sent by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eru_Il%C3%BAvatar\\\\\\">Eru Il\\\\u00favatar</a>\\\\u00a0to inhabit the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree\\\\\\">trees</a>, which the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vala_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Vala</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yavanna\\\\\\">Yavanna</a>\\\\u00a0had created along with other plants or\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_plants\\\\\\">olvar</a></i>. The Vala longed for their protection since\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morgoth\\\\\\">Morgoth</a>\\\\u00a0or\\\\u00a0<i>Melkor</i>\\\\u00a0was destroying the trees and olvar, which could not defend themselves from him. The Ents were created by Il\\\\u00favatar at the behest of Yavanna as the\\\\u00a0<i>Shepherds of the Forest</i>\\\\u00a0or\\\\u00a0<i>Tree-herders</i>.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ent#Entwives\\\\\\">Entwives</a>\\\\u00a0were also created for the Ents, but, in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Age\\\\\\">Second Age</a>, were driven out by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup><sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-AofAW2-2\\\\\\">[2]</a></sup><sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-3\\\\\\">[3]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Treebeard is the oldest of three remaining original Ents.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\\\\\">[1]</a><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TBLOTR-4\\\\\\">[4]</a>\\\\u00a0He is said to have once roamed all of the forests in Middle-earth, which included the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misty_Mountains\\\\\\">Misty Mountains</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirkwood\\\\\\">Mirkwood</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>, and the Blue Mountains. After the loss of the Entwives by the end of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">Third Age</a>, he and the remaining Ents dwelt in the Forest of Fangorn. This led the remaining Ents into isolation and all information from the outside world was cut off.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0The arrival of Merry and Pippin shifted Treebeard's attention to take action against Saruman for hacking down his trees. He led the Ents to war against Saruman and his Orcs. Treebeard later realised that while Saruman had learned much from him, the Wizard had shared no useful information of his own.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\", \\"value\\": {\\"attribute_group\\": \\"\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"JRR Tolkien\\", \\"text\\": \\"A large Man-like figure, at least fourteen foot high, very sturdy, with a tall head, and hardly any neck. Whether it was clad in stuff like green and grey bark, or whether that was its hide, was difficult to say. Arms, at a short distance from the trunk, were not wrinkled, but covered with a brown smooth skin. The large feet had seven toes each. Grey beard, deep brown eyes, shot with a green light.\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Treebeard had been friends with Saruman. It is described in\\\\u00a0<i>The Two Towers</i>\\\\u00a0that Saruman visited Treebeard in Fangorn Forest and had talked with him on various subjects of concern. Saruman gathered information from Treebeard about the Forest of Fangorn; its intertwining paths were of particular concern to him.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After Merry and Pippin's meeting with Treebeard, Treebeard called an\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entmoot\\\\\\">Entmoot</a>, which lasted three days, to decide to call an attack on Isengard and Saruman.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\\\\\">[1]</a><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-AofAW2-2\\\\\\">[2]</a><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TBLOTR-4\\\\\\">[4]</a>\\\\u00a0Since\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leaflock\\\\\\">Leaflock</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skinbark\\\\\\">Skinbark</a>\\\\u00a0were the oldest of the Ents along with Treebeard, they refused to fight, however, Treebeard thought he was going to his doom during \\\\\\"the last march of the Ents.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\\\\\">[1]</a><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TBLOTR-4\\\\\\">[4]</a>\\\\u00a0Treebeard hoped that some of the younger Ents would come instead of just the two, and, during the night he spread the word. They later launched an assault on Isengard.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\\\\\">[1]</a><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-AofAW2-2\\\\\\">[2]</a><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TBLOTR-4\\\\\\">[4]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/BbV2Hr0qRdo\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After Treebeard ordered the Ents to march to Isengard, the Ents felled Saruman's walls and destroyed every object in and around Isengard; the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthanc\\\\\\">Tower of Orthanc</a>\\\\u00a0could not be breached, but Saruman was trapped within. Treebeard stopped the attack on the tower when he realised their efforts were in vain; the tower was too strong. The Ents were ordered to unleash the waters of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_rivers#I\\\\\\">River Isen</a>, which flooded Isengard.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-AofAW2-2\\\\\\">[2]</a>\\\\u00a0When Merry and Pippin departed Treebeard he requested them to watch for the Entwives.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard#cite_note-TUCK-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0At one point in the book, Tolkien gives hints on the whereabouts of the Entwives. It is speculated that they were spotted by Samwise Gamgee's cousin Hal in the North Farthing.\\\\u00a0</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "host_place_relationship": [{"host_page": 30, "pk": 8, "place": 17}], "title": "Treebeard", "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_page": 30, "host_interests": 5, "pk": 7}], "pk": 30, "content_type": 12, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 21, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "host_experience_relationship": [{"host_page": 30, "sort_order": 0, "pk": 18, "experiences": 20}, {"host_page": 30, "sort_order": 1, "pk": 19, "experiences": 10}, {"host_page": 30, "sort_order": 2, "pk": 20, "experiences": 26}], "path": "0001000100010007"}	\N	30	1
58	f	2017-01-12 22:23:37.58+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "bilbo", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/bilbo/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Bilbo Baggins</b>\\\\u00a0is the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Title_character\\\\\\">title character</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protagonist\\\\\\">protagonist</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s 1937 novel\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>, as well as a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supporting_character\\\\\\">supporting character</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. In Tolkien's narrative\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conceit\\\\\\">conceit</a>, in which all the writings of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>\\\\u00a0are translations from the fictitious volume of\\\\u00a0<i>The\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Book_of_Westmarch\\\\\\">Red Book of Westmarch</a></i>, Bilbo is the author of\\\\u00a0<i>The Hobbit</i>\\\\u00a0and translator of various \\\\\\"works from the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvish_language\\\\\\">elvish</a>\\\\\\" (as mentioned in the end of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\\\\\">The Return of the King</a></i>).</p><p></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"style\\": \\"half\\", \\"caption\\": \\"Bilbo Baggins illustration\\", \\"image\\": 28}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"The Hobbit\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<i>The Hobbit</i>, Bilbo Baggins, a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit\\\\\\">hobbit</a>\\\\u00a0in comfortable middle age at 50 years old, was hired despite his objections as a \\\\\\"burglar\\\\\\" by the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Istari\\\\\\">wizard</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_The_Hobbit_characters#Thorin.27s_company\\\\\\">13 Dwarves</a>\\\\u00a0led by their king\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thorin_Oakenshield\\\\\\">Thorin Oakenshield</a>\\\\u00a0on a quest to reclaim the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lonely_Mountain\\\\\\">Lonely Mountain</a>\\\\u00a0and its treasure from the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragon_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">dragon</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smaug\\\\\\">Smaug</a>. The adventure took Bilbo and the companions through the wilderness, to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">elf</a>\\\\u00a0haven of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, across the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misty_Mountains\\\\\\">Misty Mountains</a>\\\\u00a0and the black forest of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirkwood\\\\\\">Mirkwood</a>, to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esgaroth\\\\\\">Lake-town</a>\\\\u00a0in the middle of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_Lake_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Long Lake</a>, and eventually to the Mountain itself. Here, after the dragon was killed and the Mountain was reclaimed, soon after that the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Five_Armies\\\\\\">Battle of Five Armies</a>\\\\u00a0took place.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In his journey, Bilbo encountered other fantastic creatures, including\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troll_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">trolls</a>, elves,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_animals#Great_Spiders\\\\\\">giant spiders</a>, a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beorn\\\\\\">man who can change shape into a bear</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">goblins</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eagle_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">eagles</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warg\\\\\\">wolves</a>\\\\u00a0and a slimy, murderous creature named\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gollum\\\\\\">Gollum</a>. Underground, near Gollum's lair, Bilbo accidentally found a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">magic ring of invisibility</a>, which he used to escape from Gollum.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>By the end of the journey, Bilbo had become wiser and more confident, having saved the day in many precarious situations. Bilbo's journey has been compared to a pilgrimage of grace. The Hobbit can be characterized as a \\\\\\"Christian\\\\u00a0<i>bildungsroman</i>\\\\u00a0which equates progress to wisdom gained in the form of a rite of passage.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-Saint_Benedict_Press-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0He rescued the dwarves from giant spiders with the magic ring and a short\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_weapons_and_armour#Sting\\\\\\">Elven-sword</a>\\\\u00a0he acquired. He used the ring to sneak around in dangerous places, as well as his wits to smuggle the dwarves out of the elves' prisons. When tensions arose over ownership of the recovered treasure, he tried unsuccessfully to bring the opposing sides to compromise, using the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_objects#Arkenstone\\\\\\">Arkenstone</a>, a stolen heirloom jewel, as leverage. This strained his relationship with Thorin, but the two were reconciled at Thorin's deathbed. At the end of the story, Bilbo returned to his home in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0only to find that several of his relatives, believing him to be dead, were trying to claim his home and possessions. In addition to becoming wealthy from his share of the dwarves' treasure, he found that he, like\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adam\\\\\\">Adam</a>, had traded respectability for experience and wisdom. At the end, Gandalf proclaims Bilbo is no longer the Hobbit he was. This is certainly true as Bilbo has fully matured. Continuing the pilgrimage theme, a true pilgrimage does not end at the destination, but rather when the wanderer is absolved, blessed, and ready to return home.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-Saint_Benedict_Press-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"The Lord of the Rings\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>, the first volume of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, begins with Bilbo's \\\\\\"eleventy-first\\\\\\" (111th) birthday, 60 years after the beginning of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>. The main character of the novel is\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>, Bilbo's cousin,<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[nb 1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0who celebrates his 33rd birthday and legally comes of age on the same day.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a02989 (<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_Reckoning\\\\\\">S.R.</a>\\\\u00a01389), Bilbo, a lifelong bachelor, adopted Frodo, the orphaned son of his first cousin\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primula_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Primula Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and his second cousin\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drogo_Baggins\\\\\\">Drogo Baggins</a>, and made him his heir. Though Frodo was actually \\\\\\"his first\\\\u00a0<i>and</i>\\\\u00a0second\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cousin#Cousin_chart\\\\\\">cousin once removed</a>\\\\u00a0either way\\\\\\",<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-LotR_party-3\\\\\\">[2]</a>\\\\u00a0the two regarded each other as uncle and nephew.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>All this time Bilbo had kept his magic ring, with no idea of its significance, using it mostly to hide from his obnoxious cousins, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sackville-Baggins\\\\\\">Sackville-Bagginses</a>, when they came to visit.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>'s investigations revealed it to be the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>\\\\u00a0forged by the Dark Lord\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>. The Ring had prolonged Bilbo's life beyond the normal hobbit span, and at 111 he still looked 50. While the Ring did not initially corrupt him as it had its previous owners, it was beginning to affect him; over the years, it had begun to prey on his mind when out of his sight, and he lost sleep and felt \\\\\\"thin, sort of\\\\u00a0<i>stretched</i>\\\\u00a0\\\\u2026 like butter that has been scraped over too much bread\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-LotR_party-3\\\\\\">[2]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>On the night of his and Frodo's birthday, Bilbo threw himself a party and invited all of the Shire. He signed his home,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bag_End\\\\\\">Bag End</a>, and estate over to Frodo. He then gave a farewell address to his neighbors, at the end of which he put on the Ring and vanished from sight. As Bilbo prepared finally to leave the house, he reacted with panic and suspicion when Gandalf tried to persuade him to leave the Ring with Frodo. Bilbo refused to give up the Ring, referring to it as his \\\\\\"precious\\\\\\" \\\\u2013 just as Gollum had. Gandalf lost his temper with his old friend and talked some sense into him. Bilbo admitted he would have liked to be rid of the Ring, and he left it behind, becoming the first person to do so voluntarily. He left the Shire that night, and was never seen in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbiton\\\\\\">Hobbiton</a>\\\\u00a0again.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>His earlier adventure, his\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eccentric_(behavior)\\\\\\">eccentric</a>\\\\u00a0habits as a hobbit, and his sudden disappearance led to the enduring figure of \\\\\\"Mad Baggins\\\\\\" in hobbit folklore, who disappeared with a flash and a bang and returned with gold and jewels.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Freed of the Ring's power over his senses, Bilbo travelled first to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, and then on to visit the dwarves of the Lonely Mountain. After he returned to Rivendell he spent much of the next 17 years living a pleasant life of retirement: eating, sleeping, writing poetry, and working on his memoirs,\\\\u00a0<i>There and Back Again</i>, known as\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>. He became a scholar of Elven lore, leaving behind the\\\\u00a0<i>Translations from the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvish_languages_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elvish</a></i>, which forms the basis of what is known to us as\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Silmarillion\\\\\\">The Silmarillion</a></i>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>When Frodo and his friends\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee\\\\\\">Samwise Gamgee</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Peregrin Took</a>\\\\u00a0stopped in Rivendell on their quest to destroy the Ring, Bilbo was still alive but now visibly aged, the years having caught up with him after he surrendered the Ring. Upon seeing the Ring again, he suddenly tried to take it from Frodo; he returned to his senses when a terrified Frodo backed away, and he broke down in tears, apologizing for bringing the burden of the Ring onto Frodo.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After the quest to destroy the Ring was fulfilled in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\\\\\">The Return of the King</a></i>, Gandalf and the four Hobbits visited Rivendell on their way back to the Shire and found Bilbo still living there. He gave Frodo a set of manuscripts that later became\\\\u00a0<i>Translations from the Elvish</i>, and also gave Sam a small bag of gold that represented the last of his share from Smaug's vast hoard. Two years later Bilbo accompanied Gandalf,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galadriel\\\\\\">Galadriel</a>, and Frodo to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_Havens\\\\\\">Grey Havens</a>, there to take ship for\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tol_Eress%C3%ABa\\\\\\">Tol Eress\\\\u00eba</a>\\\\u00a0across the sea, on 29th 'September'\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a03021. He had already celebrated his 131st birthday by this time, surpassing the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Took\\\\\\">Old Took</a>\\\\u00a0by one year and becoming the oldest Hobbit ever in Middle-earth. (The natural lifespan of Hobbits is about 100 years.)<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-4\\\\\\">[3]</a></p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "host_place_relationship": [{"host_page": 38, "pk": 16, "place": 18}], "title": "Bilbo", "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_page": 38, "host_interests": 4, "pk": 15}], "pk": 38, "content_type": 12, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 27, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "host_experience_relationship": [{"host_page": 38, "sort_order": 0, "pk": 41, "experiences": 10}, {"host_page": 38, "sort_order": 1, "pk": 42, "experiences": 23}], "path": "000100010001000F"}	\N	38	1
55	f	2017-01-12 22:10:53.935+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "frodo", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/frodo/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Frodo Baggins</b>\\\\u00a0is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Character_(arts)\\\\\\">fictional character</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tolkien%27s_legendarium\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien's legendarium</a>, and the main protagonist of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. Frodo is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit\\\\\\">hobbit</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0who inherits the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>\\\\u00a0from his cousin\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins\\\\\\">Bilbo Baggins</a>\\\\u00a0and undertakes the quest to destroy it in the fires of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Doom\\\\\\">Mount Doom</a>. He is also mentioned in Tolkien's posthumously published works,\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Silmarillion\\\\\\">The Silmarillion</a></i>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unfinished_Tales\\\\\\">Unfinished Tales</a></i>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Concept and creation\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Frodo did not appear until the third draft of\\\\u00a0<i>A Long-Expected Party</i>\\\\u00a0(the first chapter of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>), when he was named Bingo (after a family of toy\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Koala\\\\\\">koala</a>\\\\u00a0owned by Tolkien's children), son of Bilbo Baggins and Primula Brandybuck.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins#cite_note-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0In the fourth draft, he was renamed Bingo Bolger-Baggins, son of Rollo Bolger and Primula Brandybuck.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[2]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0Tolkien did not change the name to Frodo until the third phase of writing, when much of the narrative, as far as the hobbits' arrival in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, had already taken shape.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins#cite_note-3\\\\\\">[3]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0Prior to this, the name \\\\\\"Frodo\\\\\\" had been used for the character who eventually became\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Peregrin Took</a>.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins#cite_note-4\\\\\\">[4]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"The Fellowship of the Ring\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><i>The Fellowship of the Ring</i>\\\\u00a0opens as Frodo came of age (at 33 years old) and Bilbo left\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0for good on his one hundred and eleventh birthday. Frodo inherited\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bag_End\\\\\\">Bag End</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">Bilbo's ring</a>, which were both introduced in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>, at this time, was not certain about the origin of the Ring, so he warned Frodo to avoid using it and to keep it secret. Frodo kept the Ring hidden for 17 years, resulting in it giving him the same longevity of Bilbo, until Gandalf returned to tell him that it was the One Ring of the Dark Lord\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>, who desired to use it to conquer\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Realizing that he was a danger to the Shire as long as he remained there with the Ring, Frodo decided to leave home and take the Ring to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, home of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>, a mighty\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elf</a>\\\\u00a0lord. He left the Shire with three companions: his gardener\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee\\\\\\">Samwise Gamgee</a>\\\\u00a0and his cousins\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Peregrin Took</a>. They escaped just in time, for Sauron's most powerful servants, the Nine\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl\\\\\\">Nazg\\\\u00fbl</a>, had entered the Shire as Black Riders, looking for Bilbo and the Ring. They followed Frodo's trail across the Shire and nearly intercepted him.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Frodo and his companions escaped the Black Riders by travelling through the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Forest\\\\\\">Old Forest</a>, but they were misled by the magic of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Man_Willow\\\\\\">Old Man Willow</a>\\\\u00a0until they were rescued by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Bombadil\\\\\\">Tom Bombadil</a>, who gave them shelter and guided them on their way. After leaving Bombadil, they were caught in fog on the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrow_Downs\\\\\\">Barrow Downs</a>\\\\u00a0by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrow-wight\\\\\\">Barrow-wights</a>\\\\u00a0and were entranced under a spell. Frodo broke loose from the spell, attacked the barrow-wight and summoned Tom Bombadil, who again rescued the hobbits and set them on their way.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>At the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prancing_Pony\\\\\\">Prancing Pony</a></i>, an inn in the village of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bree_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Bree</a>, Frodo received a delayed\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_objects#Gandalf.27s_letter\\\\\\">letter from Gandalf</a>, and met\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\\\\\">Aragorn</a>, also called Strider, a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranger_of_the_North\\\\\\">Ranger of the North</a>. Strider became the hobbits' guide while journeying through the wilderness towards Rivendell. The One Ring slipped onto Frodo's finger inadvertently in the\\\\u00a0<i>Prancing Pony'</i>s common room, turning Frodo invisible. This attracted the attention of Sauron's agents, who ransacked the hobbits' rooms in the night. The group, under Aragorn's guidance, quickly fled through the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minor_places_in_Middle-earth#Midgewater_Marshes\\\\\\">Midgewater Marshes</a>\\\\u00a0and again escaped the Nazg\\\\u00fbl.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>While encamped at\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amon_S%C3%BBl\\\\\\">Amon S\\\\u00fbl</a>, they were found and attacked by five Nazg\\\\u00fbl. The chief of the Nazg\\\\u00fbl, known as the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witch-king_of_Angmar\\\\\\">Witch-king of Angmar</a>, stabbed Frodo with a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morgul-blade\\\\\\">Morgul-blade</a>, before Aragorn routed all five of them with fire. A piece of this blade remained in Frodo's shoulder and, working its way towards his heart, threatened to turn him into a wraith under the control of the Witch-king. With the help of his companions and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glorfindel\\\\\\">Glorfindel</a>, Frodo was able to evade the remaining Ringwraiths and reach Rivendell. Although almost overcome by his wound, once there he was healed over time by Elrond; it was said and later seen that the wound would never completely heal, however, as it was as much spiritual as physical.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In Rivendell, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_Elrond\\\\\\">Council of Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0met and resolved to destroy the Ring by casting it into\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Doom\\\\\\">Mount Doom</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>, the realm of Sauron. Frodo, realizing that he was destined for this task, stepped forward to be the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring-bearer\\\\\\">Ring-bearer</a>. A\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of nine companions</a>\\\\u00a0was formed to guide and protect him: the hobbits, Gandalf, Aragorn, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwarf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">dwarf</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gimli_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Gimli</a>, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">elf</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legolas\\\\\\">Legolas</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirkwood\\\\\\">Mirkwood</a>, and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir\\\\\\">Boromir</a>, a man of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondor</a>. Together they set out from Rivendell. Frodo was armed with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sting_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Sting</a>, Bilbo's Elvish knife, and wore Bilbo's coat of Dwarven mail made of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mithril\\\\\\">mithril</a></i>. The company, seeking a way over the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misty_Mountains\\\\\\">Misty Mountains</a>, first tried the Pass of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caradhras\\\\\\">Caradhras</a>, but abandoned it in favour of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moria_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">mines of Moria</a>. In Moria Frodo was stabbed by an\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Orc</a>-spear, but his coat of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mithril\\\\\\">mithril</a></i>\\\\u00a0armour saved his life. They were led through the mines by Gandalf, until he fell battling a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balrog\\\\\\">Balrog</a>, and then by Aragorn to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lothl%C3%B3rien\\\\\\">Lothl\\\\u00f3rien</a>. There\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galadriel\\\\\\">Galadriel</a>, the Lady of the Woods, gave Frodo an\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_objects#Elven-cloaks\\\\\\">Elven cloak</a>\\\\u00a0and a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phial_of_Galadriel\\\\\\">phial</a>\\\\u00a0carrying the Light of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E%C3%A4rendil\\\\\\">E\\\\u00e4rendil</a>\\\\u00a0to aid him on his dangerous quest.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Having then travelled some miles down the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anduin\\\\\\">Anduin</a>\\\\u00a0by boat, the Fellowship reached\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parth_Galen\\\\\\">Parth Galen</a>. There, Boromir, having fallen to the lure of the Ring, tried to take it by force from Frodo. Frodo escaped by putting on the Ring and becoming invisible. This event broke the Fellowship; Boromir was later slain defending Merry and Pippin from invading Orcs, who captured the two hobbits. Aragorn, Gimli and Legolas gave him a hero's funeral before setting out after the two hobbits. Frodo chose to continue the quest alone, but Sam followed his master, joining him on the journey to Mordor.</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "host_place_relationship": [{"host_page": 35, "pk": 13, "place": 18}], "title": "Frodo", "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_page": 35, "host_interests": 4, "pk": 12}], "pk": 35, "content_type": 12, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 25, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "host_experience_relationship": [{"host_page": 35, "sort_order": 0, "pk": 31, "experiences": 20}, {"host_page": 35, "sort_order": 1, "pk": 32, "experiences": 10}, {"host_page": 35, "sort_order": 2, "pk": 33, "experiences": 25}, {"host_page": 35, "sort_order": 3, "pk": 34, "experiences": 26}], "path": "000100010001000C"}	\N	35	1
25	f	2017-01-12 19:52:54.693+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "helms-deep", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/helms-deep/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0J. R. R. Tolkien's\\\\u00a0Middle-earth\\\\u00a0high fantasy\\\\u00a0writings,\\\\u00a0<b>Helm's Deep</b>\\\\u00a0was a large valley in the north-western\\\\u00a0Ered Nimrais\\\\u00a0(White Mountains).</p><p>The valley was described as being blocked over its entire width by the natural series of hills called\\\\u00a0<b>Helm's Dike</b>\\\\u00a0and behind that lay the fortress of Aglarond or the\\\\u00a0<b>Hornburg</b>, at the entrance to the Glittering Caves.</p><p>In the Appendices of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, the history of the valley states that it was home to a small\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondorian</a>\\\\u00a0regiment, but after the place which was called\\\\u00a0Calenardhon\\\\u00a0became\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>, it became an encampment of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)#hosts\\\\\\">Rohirrim</a>, where the guards of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fords_of_Isen\\\\\\">Fords of Isen</a>\\\\u00a0lived.</p><p>It also states that during the war with the\\\\u00a0Dunlendings\\\\u00a0under\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wulf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Wulf</a>, the Rohirrim under King\\\\u00a0Helm Hammerhand\\\\u00a0and many of his hosts sought refuge in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keep\\\\\\">keep</a>, where they held out during the winter of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a02758\\\\u20132759.</p><p>The castle itself was described as having a long causeway which wound up to the great gate of the fortress itself. Inside the keep there were stables and an armoury, as well as a great hall in the rear which was dug out of the mountainside. There also was a great tower (the Hornburg) the top of which consisted of the great horn of\\\\u00a0Helm Hammerhand. The Deep, which was described as standing next to the fortress, was barred by the long Deeping Wall, which was described as consisting of solid rock except for a small culvert which allowed water from the Deeping Stream to enter; this rendered a fresh supply in sieges of great length. The Deeping Wall itself is described as standing 20 feet tall; and also being wide enough for four men to stand side by side. Access to the fortress from within the Deep was made possible by a long stair which led to the Hornburg's rear gate.</p><p>In\\\\u00a0<i>The Two Towers</i>, the fortress guarding Helm's Deep becomes the refuge of the main army of the Rohirrim, under King\\\\u00a0Th\\\\u00e9oden\\\\u00a0during the\\\\u00a0War of the Ring. Th\\\\u00e9oden said that \\\\\\"the Hornburg has never fallen to assault\\\\\\" giving an impression of invulnerability. This was tested during the\\\\u00a0Battle of the Hornburg, as a massive army of\\\\u00a0Uruk-hai\\\\u00a0sent by\\\\u00a0Saruman\\\\u00a0almost overwhelmed the defences of the Rohirrim. Saruman's\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0used an explosive blast of fire within the culvert which, when detonated, breached the long Deeping Wall. The origin of this explosion is unclear and Tolkien denotes it as \\\\\\"Saruman's devilry\\\\\\". The Rohirrim defenders held out long enough in the fortress until dawn, giving Gandalf time to gather and lead a counter-attack, while Th\\\\u00e9oden led a cavalry charge that drove the Orcs from the fortress.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"style\\": \\"full\\", \\"caption\\": \\"Crest of Gondor, the original builders of the Helm\\", \\"image\\": 9}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Aglarond\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Aglarond and Angrenost (which later became Isengard) were the two fortresses built by Gondor to guard the approaches to the Fords of Isen. Like Angrenost to the north, it was initially well guarded, but as the population of Calenardhon (the later Rohan) dwindled it was not maintained and, losing importance, was left to a hereditary small guard who intermarried with Dunlendings.</p><p><br/></p><p>When Cirion, Steward of Gondor, gave Calenardhon to the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od, Aglarond was transferred into the care of the Rohirrim, who named it S\\\\u00fathburg (southern burg in their language). The Gondorian guard was merged with that of Angrenost to the north, which remained in the keep of Gondor. Guard duty of the Fords was initially shared between Gondor and Rohan, but later maintained only by the Rohirrim.</p><p><br/></p><p>During the reign of Helm Hammerhand, Rohan was attacked by Dunlendings from across the river Isen. Edoras was taken, and Helm and many of his hosts retreated to S\\\\u00fathburg. Because Helm always blew a great horn before riding out to fight the beleaguering Dunlendings, the keep was renamed Hornburg. During the War of the Ring, the Hornburg was the refuge of the Rohirrim as they defended Helm's Deep.</p><p><br/></p><p>After the war, Gimli the Dwarf, who fought in that battle, established a colony of Durin's folk there. Aglarond lay in front of a huge and very beautiful cave system, which proved irresistible to him. Gimli became known as 'the Lord of the Glittering Caves', although this new realm was presumably under the overlordship of Thorin Stonehelm, his kinsman and heir of the lordship of all Durin's Folk. The dwarves of Aglarond restored the Hornburg following the War of the Ring, and it became a fortress they shared with the Rohirrim.</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T19:51:43.011Z", "show_in_menus": false, "title": "Helm's Deep", "pk": 15, "content_type": 6, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T19:51:42.977Z", "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 10, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "path": "0001000100030004"}	\N	15	1
47	f	2017-01-12 21:40:27.2+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "\\u00e9owyn", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/\\u00e9owyn/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>\\\\u00c9owyn is a fictional character in Tolkien's legendarium who appears in his most famous work, The Lord of the Rings. She is a noblewoman of Rohan who is described as a shieldmaiden.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Literature\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\\\\\">The Two Towers</a></i>, \\\\u00c9owyn, a daughter of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Kings_of_Rohan#House_of_Eorl\\\\\\">House of Eorl</a>\\\\u00a0and the goddaughter of King\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C3%A9oden\\\\\\">Th\\\\u00e9oden</a>\\\\u00a0of Rohan, is introduced in Meduseld, the king's hall at Edoras.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-hall-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0She was the daughter of Th\\\\u00e9odwyn (Th\\\\u00e9oden's sister) and \\\\u00c9omund and the sister of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89omer\\\\\\">\\\\u00c9omer</a>. When she was only seven years old, her father was killed fighting\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0and her mother died of grief. \\\\u00c9owyn and \\\\u00c9omer were raised in her uncle's household as if they were his own children.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Tolkien writes that she longed to win renown in battle\\\\u2014especially since she was royal\\\\u2014but being female, her duties were reckoned to be at Edoras.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-healing-2\\\\\\">[2]</a>\\\\u00a0When Th\\\\u00e9oden's mind was poisoned by his adviser\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr%C3%ADma_Wormtongue\\\\\\">Gr\\\\u00edma Wormtongue</a>, \\\\u00c9owyn was obliged to care for her uncle, and his deterioration pained her deeply. To make matters worse, she was constantly harassed by Gr\\\\u00edma, who lusted after her. However, when\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0arrived, he freed Th\\\\u00e9oden from Wormtongue's influence.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>\\\\u00c9owyn fell in love with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\\\\\">Aragorn</a>, but it soon became clear that he could not return her love although he did not mention his betrothal to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arwen\\\\\\">Arwen</a>, except by indirect allusion, and would not allow her to join him in going to war.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-grey-3\\\\\\">[3]</a>\\\\u00a0As Aragorn pointed out,<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-grey-3\\\\\\">[3]</a>\\\\u00a0her duty was with her hosts; she had to shoulder the responsibility of ruling Rohan in Th\\\\u00e9oden's stead when the war-host of Rohan went to war,<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-hall-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0a duty he deemed no less valiant.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-grey-3\\\\\\">[3]</a>\\\\u00a0Likening her situation to a \\\\\\"cage\\\\\\", \\\\u00c9owyn said she feared \\\\\\"[t]o stay behind bars, until use and old age accept them, and all chance of great deeds is gone beyond recall or desire.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-grey-3\\\\\\">[3]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\", \\"value\\": {\\"attribute_group\\": \\"\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Aragorn\\", \\"text\\": \\"But who knows what she spoke to the darkness, alone, in the bitter watches of the night, when all her life seemed shrinking, and the walls of her bower closing in about her, a hutch to trammel some wild thing in?\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"In\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\\\\\">The Return of the King</a><p><p></p><p>The Return of the King</p></p></i>, she disguised herself as a man and under the alias of\\\\u00a0<i>Dernhelm</i>\\\\u00a0(from Old English\\\\u00a0<i>dern</i>\\\\u00a0meaning \\\\\\"secret, concealed\\\\\\"), and she traveled with the Riders of Rohan to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_the_Pelennor_Fields\\\\\\">Battle of the Pelennor Fields</a>\\\\u00a0outside the White City of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith\\\\\\">Minas Tirith</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondor</a>, carrying with her\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>, who had also been ordered to remain behind, on her horse Windfola.\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>During the battle of the Pelennor Fields, she confronted the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witch-king_of_Angmar\\\\\\">Witch-king of Angmar</a>, Lord of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl\\\\\\">Nazg\\\\u00fbl</a>, after Th\\\\u00e9oden was injured. The Witch-king threatened to \\\\\\"bear [her] away to the houses of lamentation, beyond all darkness, where [her] flesh shall be devoured, and [her] shriveled mind be left naked to the Lidless Eye.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-pelennor-4\\\\\\">[4]</a>\\\\u00a0The Witch-king further boasted that \\\\\\"[n]o living man may hinder me,\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-pelennor-4\\\\\\">[4]</a>\\\\u00a0referring to the 1,000-year-old\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prophecy\\\\\\">prophecy</a>\\\\u00a0by the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elf</a>-lord\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glorfindel\\\\\\">Glorfindel</a>, foretelling that the Witch-king would not fall \\\\\\"by the hand of man\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-glorfindel-5\\\\\\">[5]</a>\\\\u00a0\\\\u00c9owyn then removed her helmet and declared.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>But no living man am I! You look upon a woman. \\\\u00c9owyn I am, \\\\u00c9omund\\\\u2019s daughter. You stand between me and my lord and kin. Begone, if you be not deathless! For living or dark undead, I will smite you, if you touch him.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-pelennor-4\\\\\\">[4]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Witch-king attacked \\\\u00c9owyn with his\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl#Steeds\\\\\\">steed</a>, but she slew it with her sword. He then shattered her shield and broke her shield-arm with his mace, but was distracted by Merry, who stabbed him behind the knee with a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrow-blade\\\\\\">barrow-blade</a>. \\\\u00c9owyn seized the opportunity to strike the Witch-king with a killing thrust \\\\\\"between crown and mantle\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-pelennor-4\\\\\\">[4]</a>\\\\u00a0Then, as her sword shattered, his withering form collapsed and he vanished with a final cry of anguish.</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "host_place_relationship": [{"host_page": 28, "pk": 6, "place": 15}], "title": "\\u00c9owyn", "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_page": 28, "host_interests": 1, "pk": 5}], "pk": 28, "content_type": 12, "go_live_at": null, "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "depth": 4, "live": true, "image": 19, "owner": 1, "numchild": 0, "locked": false, "host_experience_relationship": [{"host_page": 28, "sort_order": 0, "pk": 12, "experiences": 26}, {"host_page": 28, "sort_order": 1, "pk": 13, "experiences": 21}, {"host_page": 28, "sort_order": 2, "pk": 14, "experiences": 24}, {"host_page": 28, "sort_order": 3, "pk": 15, "experiences": 22}], "path": "0001000100010005"}	\N	28	1
54	f	2017-01-12 22:07:10.276+00	{"expire_at": null, "slug": "pergrin-took", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/pergrin-took/", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Peregrin Took</b>, more commonly known as\\\\u00a0<b>Pippin</b>, is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_character\\\\\\">fictional character</a>\\\\u00a0from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s fantasy novel\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. Pippin is introduced as a young\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit\\\\\\">Hobbit</a>, and plays a major role as one of the companions of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>, in his quest to destroy the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>. Pippin is a member of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>.</p><p></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Overview\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Peregrin was the only son and heir of Paladin Took II, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thain_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Thain</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>. His best friend\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>, more commonly known as Merry, was his cousin; another good friend was\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>'Peregrin' means 'traveller in strange countries'.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took#cite_note-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0Pippin indeed saw much more of Middle-earth than most Hobbits: he journeyed with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo\\\\\\">Frodo</a>\\\\u00a0and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>, and fought in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">War of the Ring</a>. Late in life he travelled again to the kingdoms of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondor</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Pippin's hair colour is mentioned as \\\\\\"almost golden\\\\\\" in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_History_of_Middle-earth\\\\\\">The History of Middle-earth</a></i>, vol. IX,\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron_Defeated\\\\\\">Sauron Defeated</a></i>, through the eyes of Pippin Gamgee.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took#cite_note-SD_-2\\\\\\">[2]</a>\\\\u00a0In the later drafts of this same section Tolkien omitted this statement, leaving the reader to envisage Pippin's appearance.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"The Great Years\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Pippin was the youngest of the four Hobbits who set out from the Shire and the only one who had not yet reached his 'coming of age' at age 33. He was therefore said to be still in his 'tweens' (twenties). He was 28 at the time, while Merry, the next youngest, was 36. At\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0almost denied Pippin the chance to accompany Frodo, intending to send Pippin and Merry as messengers back to the Shire.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>, however, supported his and Merry's claims of friendship and loyalty, and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_Elrond\\\\\\">Council of Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0ultimately chose them as the last two members of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/5cZ4ABUo6TU\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After remaining with the Fellowship until its breaking at\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amon_Hen\\\\\\">Amon Hen</a>, Pippin was captured along with Merry by an\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Orc</a>-band, which included some of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uruk-hai\\\\\\">Uruk-hai</a>. While held captive by the Orcs, he purposefully dropped his elven brooch (a gift from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lothl%C3%B3rien\\\\\\">L\\\\u00f3rien</a>) as a sign for\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\\\\\">Aragorn</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legolas\\\\\\">Legolas</a>, and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gimli_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Gimli</a>, who were in pursuit. During a skirmish among his captors, Pippin managed to cut his bonds using a sword held fast by a dead Uruk. In\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>, Pippin and Merry managed to escape when the Orcs were attacked by a company of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)#hosts\\\\\\">Rohirrim</a>, the local hosts. Upon their escape, he and Merry befriended\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard\\\\\\">Treebeard</a>, leader of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ent\\\\\\">Ents</a>. They roused the other Ents to fight against Saruman, and they attacked his stronghold of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isengard\\\\\\">Isengard</a>, partially crippling his power. Due to a special \\\\\\"Ent-draught\\\\\\" that Treebeard made him and Merry drink, Pippin and his cousin became the tallest Hobbits in history, at four and a half feet, surpassing Pippin's ancestor,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullroarer_Took#Bandobras\\\\\\">Bullroarer Took</a>, who was four feet and five inches tall.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Pippin picked up the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palant%C3%ADr\\\\\\">palant\\\\u00edr</a></i>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthanc\\\\\\">Orthanc</a>\\\\u00a0after\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr%C3%ADma_Wormtongue\\\\\\">Gr\\\\u00edma Wormtongue</a>\\\\u00a0threw it at them. Later, obsessed by the mysterious stone, Pippin took it out of Gandalf's hands while the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Istari\\\\\\">wizard</a>\\\\u00a0slept, putting a rock in its place. Looking into the stone, he had a terrifying encounter with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>\\\\u00a0himself. In fact, Pippin is the only character in the book who is shown to speak directly to Sauron. To keep Pippin safe from Sauron's forces, Gandalf brought him to the city of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith\\\\\\">Minas Tirith</a>, separating him from his friends.</p>\\"}]", "first_published_at": null, "show_in_menus": false, "host_place_relationship": [{"host_page": 34, "pk": 12, "place": 17}], "title": "Pergrin Took", "host_interest_relationship":