92	f	2017-01-23 07:52:06.016+00	{"pk": 15, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/helms-deep/", "go_live_at": null, "live": true, "content_type": 6, "numchild": 0, "expired": false, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0J. R. R. Tolkien's\\\\u00a0Middle-earth\\\\u00a0high fantasy\\\\u00a0writings,\\\\u00a0<b>Helm's Deep</b>\\\\u00a0was a large valley in the north-western\\\\u00a0Ered Nimrais\\\\u00a0(White Mountains).</p><p>The valley was described as being blocked over its entire width by the natural series of hills called\\\\u00a0<b>Helm's Dike</b>\\\\u00a0and behind that lay the fortress of Aglarond or the\\\\u00a0<b>Hornburg</b>, at the entrance to the Glittering Caves.</p><p>In the Appendices of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, the history of the valley states that it was home to a small\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondorian</a>\\\\u00a0regiment, but after the place which was called\\\\u00a0Calenardhon\\\\u00a0became\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>, it became an encampment of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)#hosts\\\\\\">Rohirrim</a>, where the guards of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fords_of_Isen\\\\\\">Fords of Isen</a>\\\\u00a0lived.</p><p>It also states that during the war with the\\\\u00a0Dunlendings\\\\u00a0under\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wulf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Wulf</a>, the Rohirrim under King\\\\u00a0Helm Hammerhand\\\\u00a0and many of his hosts sought refuge in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keep\\\\\\">keep</a>, where they held out during the winter of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a02758\\\\u20132759.</p><p>The castle itself was described as having a long causeway which wound up to the great gate of the fortress itself. Inside the keep there were stables and an armoury, as well as a great hall in the rear which was dug out of the mountainside. There also was a great tower (the Hornburg) the top of which consisted of the great horn of\\\\u00a0Helm Hammerhand. The Deep, which was described as standing next to the fortress, was barred by the long Deeping Wall, which was described as consisting of solid rock except for a small culvert which allowed water from the Deeping Stream to enter; this rendered a fresh supply in sieges of great length. The Deeping Wall itself is described as standing 20 feet tall; and also being wide enough for four men to stand side by side. Access to the fortress from within the Deep was made possible by a long stair which led to the Hornburg's rear gate.</p><p>In\\\\u00a0<i>The Two Towers</i>, the fortress guarding Helm's Deep becomes the refuge of the main army of the Rohirrim, under King\\\\u00a0Th\\\\u00e9oden\\\\u00a0during the\\\\u00a0War of the Ring. Th\\\\u00e9oden said that \\\\\\"the Hornburg has never fallen to assault\\\\\\" giving an impression of invulnerability. This was tested during the\\\\u00a0Battle of the Hornburg, as a massive army of\\\\u00a0Uruk-hai\\\\u00a0sent by\\\\u00a0Saruman\\\\u00a0almost overwhelmed the defences of the Rohirrim. Saruman's\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0used an explosive blast of fire within the culvert which, when detonated, breached the long Deeping Wall. The origin of this explosion is unclear and Tolkien denotes it as \\\\\\"Saruman's devilry\\\\\\". The Rohirrim defenders held out long enough in the fortress until dawn, giving Gandalf time to gather and lead a counter-attack, while Th\\\\u00e9oden led a cavalry charge that drove the Orcs from the fortress.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"caption\\": \\"Crest of Gondor, the original builders of the Helm\\", \\"style\\": \\"half\\", \\"image\\": 9}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Aglarond\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Aglarond and Angrenost (which later became Isengard) were the two fortresses built by Gondor to guard the approaches to the Fords of Isen. Like Angrenost to the north, it was initially well guarded, but as the population of Calenardhon (the later Rohan) dwindled it was not maintained and, losing importance, was left to a hereditary small guard who intermarried with Dunlendings.</p><p><br/></p><p>When Cirion, Steward of Gondor, gave Calenardhon to the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od, Aglarond was transferred into the care of the Rohirrim, who named it S\\\\u00fathburg (southern burg in their language). The Gondorian guard was merged with that of Angrenost to the north, which remained in the keep of Gondor. Guard duty of the Fords was initially shared between Gondor and Rohan, but later maintained only by the Rohirrim.</p><p><br/></p><p>During the reign of Helm Hammerhand, Rohan was attacked by Dunlendings from across the river Isen. Edoras was taken, and Helm and many of his hosts retreated to S\\\\u00fathburg. Because Helm always blew a great horn before riding out to fight the beleaguering Dunlendings, the keep was renamed Hornburg. During the War of the Ring, the Hornburg was the refuge of the Rohirrim as they defended Helm's Deep.</p><p><br/></p><p>After the war, Gimli the Dwarf, who fought in that battle, established a colony of Durin's folk there. Aglarond lay in front of a huge and very beautiful cave system, which proved irresistible to him. Gimli became known as 'the Lord of the Glittering Caves', although this new realm was presumably under the overlordship of Thorin Stonehelm, his kinsman and heir of the lordship of all Durin's Folk. The dwarves of Aglarond restored the Hornburg following the War of the Ring, and it became a fortress they shared with the Rohirrim.</p>\\"}]", "path": "0001000100030004", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T19:52:54.693Z", 