91	f	2017-01-23 07:51:36.509+00	{"pk": 17, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/fangorn/", "go_live_at": null, "live": true, "content_type": 6, "numchild": 0, "expired": false, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Fangorn (Sindarin: [Fangaorne]; \\\\\\"Beardtree\\\\\\") in J.R.R. Tolkien's Legendarium, was a forest located in the fictional world of Middle-earth and was the home of the tree shepherds, the Ents. It was named after the oldest Ent, Treebeard or Treebeard after it. Tolkien did, however, state that there was confusion about the two.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Forest of Fangorn provided an important role in The Lord of the Rings novel as did Mirkwood and Lothl\\\\u00f3rien in the Third Age, a time when Sauron challenged Middle-earth to battle and domination. The forest provided the means by where adventure expanded with the breaking up of the Fellowship. Merry Brandybuck and Peregrin Took were the first to discover the Ents were alive but were dwindling in numbers due to the loss of the Entwives. They were lost because of the events of the Last Alliance of Elves and Men. The forest was again severely damaged during the War of the Ring by the forces of Saruman who lived close by in the fortress of Isengard.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Etymology\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>\\\\\\"Fangorn\\\\\\" was the original name for the Ent Treebeard, who was the eldest of his species and who looked after vast areas of his home and the surrounding land which was named Fangorn Forest. Additionally, Fangorn translated in the fictional language of Sindarin from \\\\\\"fanga\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"beard\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"orne\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"tree\\\\\\". Sindarin was a language Tolkien created and described the Elves of Middle-Earth to possess; who \\\\\\"awoke\\\\\\" the Ents and taught them language. In other parts of Middle-earth Fangorn Forest was called the \\\\\\"Entwood\\\\\\" by the Rohirrim.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\", \\"value\\": {\\"attribute_name\\": \\"Treebeard\\", \\"text\\": \\"Some of us are still true Ents, and lively enough in our fashion, but many are growing sleepy, going tree-ish, as you might say. Most of the trees are just trees, of course; but many are half awake. Some are quite wide awake, and a few are, well, ah, well getting Entish. That is going on all the time.\\", \\"attribute_group\\": \\"\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Fangorn Forest apparently had several names as told by Treebeard who referred to the forest by various Quenya names in Lord of the Rings, some of which were Ambar\\\\u00f3na, Tauremornal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb, Tauremorna and Aldal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb. \\\\\\"Ambar\\\\u00f3na\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"uprising, sunrise, orient\\\\\\" from \\\\\\"amba\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"upwards\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"r\\\\u00f3na\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"east\\\\\\". \\\\\\"Aldal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"tree twilight\\\\\\" from \\\\\\"alda\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"tree\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"l\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"dusk, twilight\\\\\\".[1] \\\\\\"Tauremorna\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"gloomy forest\\\\\\" from \\\\\\"taur\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"forest\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"morna\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"gloomy, somber\\\\\\".[1] \\\\\\"Tauremornal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"gloomy twilight forest\\\\\\".</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Geography\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Forest of Fangorn was located at the south-eastern end of the Misty Mountains near the Gap of Rohan. The mountains formed the western border of Fangorn. At the end of the mountain range stood the stronghold of Isengard near the southwestern corner of the forest and this was where Saruman lived.[citation needed] To the east and south of Fangorn was the land of Rohan, and Lothl\\\\u00f3rien lay to the north and slightly east. Fangorn Forest stretched for many miles and held many paths.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Tolkien stated that two significant rivers ran through the forest. To the north the Limlight flowed from the woods and then formed the northern border of Rohan. The river then merged into the larger Anduin. In the south, the Entwash spread deep into the forest arriving from Methedras, a mountainous region located near the Misty Mountains. The river then flowed from Fangorn and was directed through Rohan to the Anduin River. The valley of Derndingle was located to the south-west. There was a path where the Entwash passed into a region called Wellinghall and this was where the Entwash passed the home of Treebeard, the shepherd of the forest.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Fangorn Forest was said to be humid, and trunks and branches grew thick where very little light penetrated the forest. Similarly, Fangorn was said to be a dangerous and evil place like Mirkwood (where huge spiders roamed the forest and other evil creatures lay), but this was not the case following the events of The Lord of the Rings. The forest was home to many different kinds of trees. Huorns also lived in the forest, similar to Ents but more discreet. Most lived deep in the Forest of Fangorn. The Ents and Huorns drank from the river Entwash, and from it the Ents brewed their legendary drink, the Ent-draughts.</p>\\"}]", "path": "0001000100030006", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T20:05:17.843Z", "image": 13, "title": "Fangorn", "show_in_menus": false, "locked": false, "expire_at": null, "seo_title": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:05:17.882Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "depth": 4, "owner": 1, "slug": "fangorn", "search_description": ""}	\N	17	1
73	f	2017-01-22 10:41:10.278+00	{"host_place_relationship": [{"pk": 16, "place": 18, "host_page": 38}], "path": "000100010001000F", "pk": 38, "seo_title": "", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T22:23:37.580Z", "show_in_menus": false, "expired": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/bilbo/", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T22:23:37.638Z", "numchild": 0, "depth": 4, "image": 27, "expire_at": null, "host_experience_relationship": [{"pk": 41, "experiences": 10, "host_page": 38, "sort_order": 0}, {"pk": 42, "experiences": 23, "host_page": 38, "sort_order": 1}], "search_description": "", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Bilbo Baggins</b>\\\\u00a0is the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Title_character\\\\\\">title character</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protagonist\\\\\\">protagonist</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s 1937 novel\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>, as well as a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supporting_character\\\\\\">supporting character</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. In Tolkien's narrative\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conceit\\\\\\">conceit</a>, in which all the writings of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>\\\\u00a0are translations from the fictitious volume of\\\\u00a0<i>The\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Book_of_Westmarch\\\\\\">Red Book of Westmarch</a></i>, Bilbo is the author of\\\\u00a0<i>The Hobbit</i>\\\\u00a0and translator of various \\\\\\"works from the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvish_language\\\\\\">elvish</a>\\\\\\" (as mentioned in the end of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\\\\\">The Return of the King</a></i>).</p><p></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"image\\": 28, \\"style\\": \\"half\\", \\"caption\\": \\"Bilbo Baggins illustration\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"The Hobbit\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<i>The Hobbit</i>, Bilbo Baggins, a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit\\\\\\">hobbit</a>\\\\u00a0in comfortable middle age at 50 years old, was hired despite his objections as a \\\\\\"burglar\\\\\\" by the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Istari\\\\\\">wizard</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_The_Hobbit_characters#Thorin.27s_company\\\\\\">13 Dwarves</a>\\\\u00a0led by their king\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thorin_Oakenshield\\\\\\">Thorin Oakenshield</a>\\\\u00a0on a quest to reclaim the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lonely_Mountain\\\\\\">Lonely Mountain</a>\\\\u00a0and its treasure from the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragon_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">dragon</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smaug\\\\\\">Smaug</a>. The adventure took Bilbo and the companions through the wilderness, to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">elf</a>\\\\u00a0haven of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, across the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misty_Mountains\\\\\\">Misty Mountains</a>\\\\u00a0and the black forest of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirkwood\\\\\\">Mirkwood</a>, to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esgaroth\\\\\\">Lake-town</a>\\\\u00a0in the middle of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_Lake_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Long Lake</a>, and eventually to the Mountain itself. Here, after the dragon was killed and the Mountain was reclaimed, soon after that the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Five_Armies\\\\\\">Battle of Five Armies</a>\\\\u00a0took place.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In his journey, Bilbo encountered other fantastic creatures, including\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troll_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">trolls</a>, elves,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_animals#Great_Spiders\\\\\\">giant spiders</a>, a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beorn\\\\\\">man who can change shape into a bear</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">goblins</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eagle_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">eagles</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warg\\\\\\">wolves</a>\\\\u00a0and a slimy, murderous creature named\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gollum\\\\\\">Gollum</a>. Underground, near Gollum's lair, Bilbo accidentally found a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">magic ring of invisibility</a>, which he used to escape from Gollum.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>By the end of the journey, Bilbo had become wiser and more confident, having saved the day in many precarious situations. Bilbo's journey has been compared to a pilgrimage of grace. The Hobbit can be characterized as a \\\\\\"Christian\\\\u00a0<i>bildungsroman</i>\\\\u00a0which equates progress to wisdom gained in the form of a rite of passage.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-Saint_Benedict_Press-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0He rescued the dwarves from giant spiders with the magic ring and a short\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_weapons_and_armour#Sting\\\\\\">Elven-sword</a>\\\\u00a0he acquired. He used the ring to sneak around in dangerous places, as well as his wits to smuggle the dwarves out of the elves' prisons. When tensions arose over ownership of the recovered treasure, he tried unsuccessfully to bring the opposing sides to compromise, using the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_objects#Arkenstone\\\\\\">Arkenstone</a>, a stolen heirloom jewel, as leverage. This strained his relationship with Thorin, but the two were reconciled at Thorin's deathbed. At the end of the story, Bilbo returned to his home in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0only to find that several of his relatives, believing him to be dead, were trying to claim his home and possessions. In addition to becoming wealthy from his share of the dwarves' treasure, he found that he, like\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adam\\\\\\">Adam</a>, had traded respectability for experience and wisdom. At the end, Gandalf proclaims Bilbo is no longer the Hobbit he was. This is certainly true as Bilbo has fully matured. Continuing the pilgrimage theme, a true pilgrimage does not end at the destination, but rather when the wanderer is absolved, blessed, and ready to return home.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-Saint_Benedict_Press-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"The Lord of the Rings\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>, the first volume of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, begins with Bilbo's \\\\\\"eleventy-first\\\\\\" (111th) birthday, 60 years after the beginning of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>. The main character of the novel is\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>, Bilbo's cousin,<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[nb 1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0who celebrates his 33rd birthday and legally comes of age on the same day.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a02989 (<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_Reckoning\\\\\\">S.R.</a>\\\\u00a01389), Bilbo, a lifelong bachelor, adopted Frodo, the orphaned son of his first cousin\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primula_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Primula Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and his second cousin\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drogo_Baggins\\\\\\">Drogo Baggins</a>, and made him his heir. Though Frodo was actually \\\\\\"his first\\\\u00a0<i>and</i>\\\\u00a0second\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cousin#Cousin_chart\\\\\\">cousin once removed</a>\\\\u00a0either way\\\\\\",<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-LotR_party-3\\\\\\">[2]</a>\\\\u00a0the two regarded each other as uncle and nephew.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>All this time Bilbo had kept his magic ring, with no idea of its significance, using it mostly to hide from his obnoxious cousins, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sackville-Baggins\\\\\\">Sackville-Bagginses</a>, when they came to visit.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>'s investigations revealed it to be the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>\\\\u00a0forged by the Dark Lord\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>. The Ring had prolonged Bilbo's life beyond the normal hobbit span, and at 111 he still looked 50. While the Ring did not initially corrupt him as it had its previous owners, it was beginning to affect him; over the years, it had begun to prey on his mind when out of his sight, and he lost sleep and felt \\\\\\"thin, sort of\\\\u00a0<i>stretched</i>\\\\u00a0\\\\u2026 like butter that has been scraped over too much bread\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-LotR_party-3\\\\\\">[2]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>On the night of his and Frodo's birthday, Bilbo threw himself a party and invited all of the Shire. He signed his home,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bag_End\\\\\\">Bag End</a>, and estate over to Frodo. He then gave a farewell address to his neighbors, at the end of which he put on the Ring and vanished from sight. As Bilbo prepared finally to leave the house, he reacted with panic and suspicion when Gandalf tried to persuade him to leave the Ring with Frodo. Bilbo refused to give up the Ring, referring to it as his \\\\\\"precious\\\\\\" \\\\u2013 just as Gollum had. Gandalf lost his temper with his old friend and talked some sense into him. Bilbo admitted he would have liked to be rid of the Ring, and he left it behind, becoming the first person to do so voluntarily. He left the Shire that night, and was never seen in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbiton\\\\\\">Hobbiton</a>\\\\u00a0again.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>His earlier adventure, his\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eccentric_(behavior)\\\\\\">eccentric</a>\\\\u00a0habits as a hobbit, and his sudden disappearance led to the enduring figure of \\\\\\"Mad Baggins\\\\\\" in hobbit folklore, who disappeared with a flash and a bang and returned with gold and jewels.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Freed of the Ring's power over his senses, Bilbo travelled first to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, and then on to visit the dwarves of the Lonely Mountain. After he returned to Rivendell he spent much of the next 17 years living a pleasant life of retirement: eating, sleeping, writing poetry, and working on his memoirs,\\\\u00a0<i>There and Back Again</i>, known as\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>. He became a scholar of Elven lore, leaving behind the\\\\u00a0<i>Translations from the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvish_languages_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elvish</a></i>, which forms the basis of what is known to us as\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Silmarillion\\\\\\">The Silmarillion</a></i>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>When Frodo and his friends\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee\\\\\\">Samwise Gamgee</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Peregrin Took</a>\\\\u00a0stopped in Rivendell on their quest to destroy the Ring, Bilbo was still alive but now visibly aged, the years having caught up with him after he surrendered the Ring. Upon seeing the Ring again, he suddenly tried to take it from Frodo; he returned to his senses when a terrified Frodo backed away, and he broke down in tears, apologizing for bringing the burden of the Ring onto Frodo.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After the quest to destroy the Ring was fulfilled in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\\\\\">The Return of the King</a></i>, Gandalf and the four Hobbits visited Rivendell on their way back to the Shire and found Bilbo still living there. He gave Frodo a set of manuscripts that later became\\\\u00a0<i>Translations from the Elvish</i>, and also gave Sam a small bag of gold that represented the last of his share from Smaug's vast hoard. Two years later Bilbo accompanied Gandalf,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galadriel\\\\\\">Galadriel</a>, and Frodo to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_Havens\\\\\\">Grey Havens</a>, there to take ship for\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tol_Eress%C3%ABa\\\\\\">Tol Eress\\\\u00eba</a>\\\\u00a0across the sea, on 29th 'September'\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a03021. He had already celebrated his 131st birthday by this time, surpassing the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Took\\\\\\">Old Took</a>\\\\u00a0by one year and becoming the oldest Hobbit ever in Middle-earth. (The natural lifespan of Hobbits is about 100 years.)<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins#cite_note-4\\\\\\">[3]</a></p>\\"}]", "owner": 1, "go_live_at": null, "host_interest_relationship": [{"pk": 15, "host_page": 38, "host_interests": 4}], "content_type": 12, "slug": "bilbo", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "locked": false, "title": "Bilbo", "live": true}	\N	38	1
74	f	2017-01-22 10:44:54.381+00	{"host_place_relationship": [{"pk": 15, "place": 12, "host_page": 37}], "path": "000100010001000E", "pk": 37, "seo_title": "", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T22:18:36.654Z", "show_in_menus": false, "expired": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/gandalf/", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T22:18:36.780Z", "numchild": 0, "depth": 4, "image": 26, "expire_at": null, "host_experience_relationship": [{"pk": 38, "experiences": 6, "host_page": 37, "sort_order": 0}, {"pk": 39, "experiences": 20, "host_page": 37, "sort_order": 1}, {"pk": 40, "experiences": 21, "host_page": 37, "sort_order": 2}, {"pk": null, "experiences": 10, "host_page": 37, "sort_order": 3}], "search_description": "", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Showing a simple version of Streamfield</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Gandalf</b>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English\\\\\\">/\\\\u02c8\\\\u0261\\\\u00e6nd\\\\u0251\\\\u02d0lf/</a><sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[2]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Character_(arts)\\\\\\">fictional character</a>\\\\u00a0and one of the protagonists in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s novels\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. He is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">wizard</a>, member of the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Istari</a></i>\\\\u00a0order, as well as leader of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>\\\\u00a0and the army of the West. In\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, he is initially known as\\\\u00a0<b>Gandalf the Grey</b>, but returns from death as\\\\u00a0<b>Gandalf the White</b>.</p><p></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"The Fellowship of the Ring\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Returning to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>, in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a03018, Gandalf confirmed his suspicions by throwing\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">the Ring</a>\\\\u00a0into\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo</a>'s hearth-fire and reading the writing that appeared on\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring#Appearance\\\\\\">the Ring's surface</a>. He told Frodo the full history of the Ring, and urged him to take the Ring to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>; for he would be in grave danger if he stayed in the Shire. Gandalf said he would attempt to return for Frodo's 50th birthday party, in order to accompany him on the road thereafter; and that meanwhile Frodo should arrange to leave quietly, as the servants of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>\\\\u00a0would be searching for him.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Outside the Shire, Gandalf encountered\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radagast_the_Brown\\\\\\">Radagast the Brown</a>, another of the Istari, who brought the news that the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl\\\\\\">Nazg\\\\u00fbl</a>\\\\u00a0had ridden forth and crossed the River\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anduin\\\\\\">Anduin</a>\\\\u2014and a request from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>\\\\u00a0that Gandalf come to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isengard\\\\\\">Isengard</a>. Gandalf left a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_objects#Gandalf.27s_letter\\\\\\">letter</a>\\\\u00a0to Frodo (urging his immediate departure) with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barliman_Butterbur\\\\\\">Barliman Butterbur</a>\\\\u00a0at the inn in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bree_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Bree</a>, and headed towards Isengard. There Saruman revealed his true colours, urging Gandalf to help him obtain the Ring for his own use. Gandalf refused, and Saruman imprisoned him at the top of the tower of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthanc\\\\\\">Orthanc</a>. Eventually Gandalf was rescued by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gwaihir\\\\\\">Gwaihir</a>\\\\u00a0the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eagle_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Eagle</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Gwaihir set Gandalf down in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>, where Gandalf appealed to King\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C3%A9oden\\\\\\">Th\\\\u00e9oden</a>\\\\u00a0for a horse. Th\\\\u00e9oden, under the malign influence of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr%C3%ADma_Wormtongue\\\\\\">Gr\\\\u00edma Wormtongue</a>, Saruman's spy, told Gandalf to take any horse he pleased, but to leave quickly. It was then that Gandalf met the great horse\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shadowfax_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Shadowfax</a>, one of the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mearas\\\\\\">mearas</a></i>, who would be his mount and companion for most of the rest of the war. Gandalf pursued the horse for two days<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf#cite_note-AppB-6\\\\\\">[6]</a>\\\\u00a0before Shadowfax permitted Gandalf to ride him. Gandalf then rode hard for the Shire, but did not reach it until Frodo had already set out. Knowing that Frodo and his companions would be heading for Rivendell, Gandalf began to make his own way there. He learned at Bree that the Hobbits had fallen in with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\\\\\">Aragorn</a>. He faced the Nazg\\\\u00fbl at\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weathertop\\\\\\">Weathertop</a>\\\\u00a0but escaped after an all-night battle, drawing four of them northward. Frodo, Aragorn and company faced the remaining five on Weathertop a few nights later. Gandalf reached Rivendell just before Frodo's arrival.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In Rivendell, Gandalf helped\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0drive off the Nazg\\\\u00fbl pursuing Frodo and played a great part in the following\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_Elrond\\\\\\">council</a>\\\\u00a0as the only person who knew the full history of the Ring. He also revealed that Saruman had betrayed them and was in league with Sauron. When it was decided that the Ring had to be destroyed, Gandalf volunteered to accompany Frodo\\\\u2014now the Ring-bearer\\\\u2014in his quest. He also persuaded Elrond to let Frodo's cousins\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Merry</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Pippin</a>\\\\u00a0join the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Taking charge of the Fellowship (comprising nine representatives of the free hostss of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>, \\\\\\"set against the Nine Riders\\\\\\"), Gandalf and Aragorn led the Hobbits and their companions south. After an unsuccessful attempt to cross Mount\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caradhras\\\\\\">Caradhras</a>\\\\u00a0in winter, they crossed\\\\u00a0<i>under</i>\\\\u00a0the mountains through the Mines of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moria_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Moria</a>, though only\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gimli_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Gimli</a>\\\\u00a0the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwarf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Dwarf</a>\\\\u00a0was enthusiastic about that route. In Moria, they discovered that the Dwarf colony established there earlier had been overrun by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Orcs</a>. The Fellowship fought with the Orcs and Trolls of Moria and escaped them.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>At the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bridge_of_Khazad-d%C3%BBm\\\\\\">Bridge of Khazad-d\\\\u00fbm</a>, they encountered \\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balrog#Durin.27s_Bane\\\\\\">Durin's Bane</a>,\\\\\\" a fearsome\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balrog\\\\\\">Balrog</a>\\\\u00a0from ancient times. Gandalf faced the Balrog to enable the others to escape. After a brief exchange of blows, Gandalf broke the bridge beneath the Balrog with his\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magic_(Middle-earth)#Magic_items\\\\\\">staff</a>. As the Balrog fell, it wrapped its whip around Gandalf's legs, dragging him over the edge. As his friends looked on in horror, Gandalf fell into the abyss, crying \\\\\\"Fly, you fools!\\\\\\" as he went.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After a long fall, Gandalf and the Balrog crashed into a deep subterranean lake far under Moria. Gandalf pursued the Balrog through the tunnels for eight days until they climbed to the peak of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minor_places_in_Middle-earth#Celebdil\\\\\\">Zirakzigil</a>. Here they fought for two days and nights. In the end, the Balrog was defeated and cast down onto the mountainside. Gandalf himself died shortly afterwards, and his body lay on the peak while his spirit travelled \\\\\\"out of thought and time\\\\\\".</p>\\"}]", "owner": 1, "go_live_at": null, "host_interest_relationship": [{"pk": null, "host_page": 37, "host_interests": 1}], "content_type": 12, "slug": "gandalf", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "locked": false, "title": "Gandalf", "live": true}	\N	37	1
75	f	2017-01-22 10:49:22.897+00	{"host_place_relationship": [{"pk": 15, "place": 12, "host_page": 37}], "path": "000100010001000E", "pk": 37, "seo_title": "", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-22T10:44:54.381Z", "show_in_menus": false, "expired": false, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/gandalf/", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T22:18:36.780Z", "numchild": 0, "depth": 4, "image": 26, "expire_at": null, "host_experience_relationship": [{"pk": 38, "experiences": 6, "host_page": 37, "sort_order": 0}, {"pk": 39, "experiences": 20, "host_page": 37, "sort_order": 1}, {"pk": 40, "experiences": 21, "host_page": 37, "sort_order": 2}, {"pk": 43, "experiences": 10, "host_page": 37, "sort_order": 3}], "search_description": "", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Gandalf</b>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English\\\\\\">/\\\\u02c8\\\\u0261\\\\u00e6nd\\\\u0251\\\\u02d0lf/</a><sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[2]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Character_(arts)\\\\\\">fictional character</a>\\\\u00a0and one of the protagonists in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s novels\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. He is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">wizard</a>, member of the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Istari</a></i>\\\\u00a0order, as well as leader of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>\\\\u00a0and the army of the West. In\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, he is initially known as\\\\u00a0<b>Gandalf the Grey</b>, but returns from death as\\\\u00a0<b>Gandalf the White</b>.</p><p></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"The Fellowship of the Ring\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Returning to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>, in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a03018, Gandalf confirmed his suspicions by throwing\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">the Ring</a>\\\\u00a0into\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo</a>'s hearth-fire and reading the writing that appeared on\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring#Appearance\\\\\\">the Ring's surface</a>. He told Frodo the full history of the Ring, and urged him to take the Ring to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>; for he would be in grave danger if he stayed in the Shire. Gandalf said he would attempt to return for Frodo's 50th birthday party, in order to accompany him on the road thereafter; and that meanwhile Frodo should arrange to leave quietly, as the servants of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>\\\\u00a0would be searching for him.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Outside the Shire, Gandalf encountered\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radagast_the_Brown\\\\\\">Radagast the Brown</a>, another of the Istari, who brought the news that the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl\\\\\\">Nazg\\\\u00fbl</a>\\\\u00a0had ridden forth and crossed the River\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anduin\\\\\\">Anduin</a>\\\\u2014and a request from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>\\\\u00a0that Gandalf come to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isengard\\\\\\">Isengard</a>. Gandalf left a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_objects#Gandalf.27s_letter\\\\\\">letter</a>\\\\u00a0to Frodo (urging his immediate departure) with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barliman_Butterbur\\\\\\">Barliman Butterbur</a>\\\\u00a0at the inn in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bree_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Bree</a>, and headed towards Isengard. There Saruman revealed his true colours, urging Gandalf to help him obtain the Ring for his own use. Gandalf refused, and Saruman imprisoned him at the top of the tower of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthanc\\\\\\">Orthanc</a>. Eventually Gandalf was rescued by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gwaihir\\\\\\">Gwaihir</a>\\\\u00a0the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eagle_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Eagle</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Gwaihir set Gandalf down in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>, where Gandalf appealed to King\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C3%A9oden\\\\\\">Th\\\\u00e9oden</a>\\\\u00a0for a horse. Th\\\\u00e9oden, under the malign influence of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr%C3%ADma_Wormtongue\\\\\\">Gr\\\\u00edma Wormtongue</a>, Saruman's spy, told Gandalf to take any horse he pleased, but to leave quickly. It was then that Gandalf met the great horse\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shadowfax_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Shadowfax</a>, one of the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mearas\\\\\\">mearas</a></i>, who would be his mount and companion for most of the rest of the war. Gandalf pursued the horse for two days<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf#cite_note-AppB-6\\\\\\">[6]</a>\\\\u00a0before Shadowfax permitted Gandalf to ride him. Gandalf then rode hard for the Shire, but did not reach it until Frodo had already set out. Knowing that Frodo and his companions would be heading for Rivendell, Gandalf began to make his own way there. He learned at Bree that the Hobbits had fallen in with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\\\\\">Aragorn</a>. He faced the Nazg\\\\u00fbl at\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weathertop\\\\\\">Weathertop</a>\\\\u00a0but escaped after an all-night battle, drawing four of them northward. Frodo, Aragorn and company faced the remaining five on Weathertop a few nights later. Gandalf reached Rivendell just before Frodo's arrival.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In Rivendell, Gandalf helped\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0drive off the Nazg\\\\u00fbl pursuing Frodo and played a great part in the following\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_Elrond\\\\\\">council</a>\\\\u00a0as the only person who knew the full history of the Ring. He also revealed that Saruman had betrayed them and was in league with Sauron. When it was decided that the Ring had to be destroyed, Gandalf volunteered to accompany Frodo\\\\u2014now the Ring-bearer\\\\u2014in his quest. He also persuaded Elrond to let Frodo's cousins\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Merry</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Pippin</a>\\\\u00a0join the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Taking charge of the Fellowship (comprising nine representatives of the free hostss of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>, \\\\\\"set against the Nine Riders\\\\\\"), Gandalf and Aragorn led the Hobbits and their companions south. After an unsuccessful attempt to cross Mount\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caradhras\\\\\\">Caradhras</a>\\\\u00a0in winter, they crossed\\\\u00a0<i>under</i>\\\\u00a0the mountains through the Mines of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moria_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Moria</a>, though only\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gimli_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Gimli</a>\\\\u00a0the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwarf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Dwarf</a>\\\\u00a0was enthusiastic about that route. In Moria, they discovered that the Dwarf colony established there earlier had been overrun by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Orcs</a>. The Fellowship fought with the Orcs and Trolls of Moria and escaped them.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>At the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bridge_of_Khazad-d%C3%BBm\\\\\\">Bridge of Khazad-d\\\\u00fbm</a>, they encountered \\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balrog#Durin.27s_Bane\\\\\\">Durin's Bane</a>,\\\\\\" a fearsome\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balrog\\\\\\">Balrog</a>\\\\u00a0from ancient times. Gandalf faced the Balrog to enable the others to escape. After a brief exchange of blows, Gandalf broke the bridge beneath the Balrog with his\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magic_(Middle-earth)#Magic_items\\\\\\">staff</a>. As the Balrog fell, it wrapped its whip around Gandalf's legs, dragging him over the edge. As his friends looked on in horror, Gandalf fell into the abyss, crying \\\\\\"Fly, you fools!\\\\\\" as he went.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After a long fall, Gandalf and the Balrog crashed into a deep subterranean lake far under Moria. Gandalf pursued the Balrog through the tunnels for eight days until they climbed to the peak of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minor_places_in_Middle-earth#Celebdil\\\\\\">Zirakzigil</a>. Here they fought for two days and nights. In the end, the Balrog was defeated and cast down onto the mountainside. Gandalf himself died shortly afterwards, and his body lay on the peak while his spirit travelled \\\\\\"out of thought and time\\\\\\".</p>\\"}]", "owner": 1, "go_live_at": null, "host_interest_relationship": [{"pk": 16, "host_page": 37, "host_interests": 1}], "content_type": 12, "slug": "gandalf", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "locked": false, "title": "Gandalf", "live": true}	\N	37	1
89	f	2017-01-23 07:46:18.099+00	{"host_place_relationship": [{"place": 8, "host_page": 33, "pk": 11}], "pk": 33, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/sauron/", "go_live_at": null, "live": true, "content_type": 12, "numchild": 0, "expired": false, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Sauron</b>,\\\\u00a0pronounced\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA\\\\\\">[\\\\u02c8sa\\\\u028ar\\\\u0254n]</a>,<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0is the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Title_character\\\\\\">title character</a><sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-3\\\\\\">[note 1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0and main antagonist of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. In the same work, he is identified as the\\\\u00a0<b>Necromancer</b>, mentioned in Tolkien's earlier novel\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hobbit\\\\\\">The Hobbit</a></i>. In Tolkien's\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Silmarillion\\\\\\">The Silmarillion</a></i>\\\\u00a0(published posthumously by Tolkien's son\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christopher_Tolkien\\\\\\">Christopher Tolkien</a>),<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-4\\\\\\">[3]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0he is also described as the chief lieutenant of the first\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dark_Lord_(fiction)\\\\\\">Dark Lord</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morgoth\\\\\\">Morgoth</a>. Tolkien noted that the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainur_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">\\\\\\"angelic\\\\\\" powers of his constructed myth</a>\\\\u00a0\\\\\\"were capable of many degrees of error and failing\\\\\\", but by far the worst was \\\\\\"the absolute\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satan\\\\\\">Satanic</a>\\\\u00a0rebellion and evil of Morgoth and his satellite Sauron\\\\\\".<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-5\\\\\\">[4]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Biography\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Before creation of the world\\", \\"size\\": \\"h3\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainulindal%C3%AB\\\\\\">Ainulindal\\\\u00eb</a></i>, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creation_myth\\\\\\">cosmological myth</a>\\\\u00a0prefixed to\\\\u00a0<i>The Silmarillion</i>, explains how the supreme being\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eru_Il%C3%BAvatar\\\\\\">Eru</a>\\\\u00a0initiated his creation by bringing into being innumerable spirits, \\\\\\"the offspring of his thought\\\\\\", who were with him before anything else had been made. The being later known as Sauron originated as an \\\\\\"immortal (angelic) spirit\\\\\\".<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters243-6\\\\\\">[5]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0In his origin, Sauron therefore perceived the Creator directly. As Tolkien noted: \\\\\\"Sauron could not, of course, be a 'sincere'\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atheist\\\\\\">atheist</a>. Though one of the minor spirits created before the world, he knew Eru, according to his measure.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-ME-ref.7CMR.7Cp._397-7\\\\\\">[6]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the terminology of Tolkien's\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_language\\\\\\">invented language</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quenya\\\\\\">Quenya</a>, these angelic spirits were called\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainur_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Ainur</a>. Those who entered the physical world were called\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vala_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Valar</a>, especially the most powerful ones. The (mostly) lesser beings who entered the world, of whom Sauron was one, were called\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maia_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Maiar</a>. In Tolkien's letters, the author noted that Sauron \\\\\\"was of course a '<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divinity\\\\\\">divine</a>' person (in the terms of this mythology; a lesser member of the race of Valar)\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters205-8\\\\\\">[7]</a>\\\\u00a0Tolkien noted that he was of a \\\\\\"far higher order\\\\\\" than the Maiar who later came to Middle-earth as the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Wizards</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters243fn-9\\\\\\">[8]</a>\\\\u00a0As created by Eru, the Ainur were all good and uncorrupt, as\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0stated in\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>: \\\\\\"Nothing is evil in the beginning. Even Sauron was not so.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-10\\\\\\">[9]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Rebellion originated with the Vala\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morgoth\\\\\\">Melkor</a>. According to a story meant as a parable of events beyond\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elvish</a>\\\\u00a0comprehension,<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-11\\\\\\">[10]</a>\\\\u00a0Eru let his spirit-children perform a great Music, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainulindal%C3%AB\\\\\\">Music of the Ainur</a>, developing a theme revealed by Eru himself. For a while the cosmic choir made wondrous music, but then Melkor tried to increase his own glory by weaving into his song thoughts and ideas that were not in accordance with the original theme. \\\\\\"Straightway discord arose around him, and many that sang nigh him grew despondent ... but some began to attune their music to his rather than to the thought which they had at first.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-12\\\\\\">[11]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The discord Melkor created would have dire consequences, as this singing was a kind of template for the world: \\\\\\"The evils of the world were not at first in the great Theme, but entered with the discords of Melkor.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-13\\\\\\">[12]</a>\\\\u00a0However, \\\\\\"Sauron was not a beginner of discord; and he probably knew more of the Music than did Melkor, whose mind had always been filled with his own plans and devices.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-14\\\\\\">[13]</a>\\\\u00a0Apparently Sauron was not even one of the spirits that immediately began to attune their music to that of Melkor, since it is noted elsewhere that his fall occurred later (<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#Sauron.27s_fall\\\\\\">see below</a>).</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The cosmic Music now represented the conflict between\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Good_and_evil\\\\\\">good and evil</a>. Finally, Eru abruptly brought the Song of Creation to an end. To show the spirits, faithful or otherwise, what they had done, Eru gave independent being to the now-marred Music. This resulted in the manifestation of the material World,\\\\u00a0<i>E\\\\u00e4</i>, where the drama of good and evil would play out and be resolved.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"First Age\\", \\"size\\": \\"h3\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the terminology of Tolkien's\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_language\\\\\\">invented language</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quenya\\\\\\">Quenya</a>, these angelic spirits were called\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ainur_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Ainur</a>. Those who entered the physical world were called\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vala_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Valar</a>, especially the most powerful ones. The (mostly) lesser beings who entered the world, of whom Sauron was one, were called\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maia_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Maiar</a>. In Tolkien's letters, the author noted that Sauron \\\\\\"was of course a '<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divinity\\\\\\">divine</a>' person (in the terms of this mythology; a lesser member of the race of Valar)\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters205-8\\\\\\">[7]</a>\\\\u00a0Tolkien noted that he was of a \\\\\\"far higher order\\\\\\" than the Maiar who later came to Middle-earth as the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wizard_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Wizards</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters243fn-9\\\\\\">[8]</a>\\\\u00a0As created by Eru, the Ainur were all good and uncorrupt, as\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0stated in\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>: \\\\\\"Nothing is evil in the beginning. Even Sauron was not so.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-10\\\\\\">[9]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Sauron's fall\\", \\"size\\": \\"h4\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Melkor opposed the other Valar, who remained faithful to Eru and tried to carry out the Creator's designs. Within the larger universe, they eventually focused on developing the world of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arda_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Arda</a>\\\\u00a0(Earth, or the entire solar system). Around this time, Sauron fell victim to Melkor's corrupting influence: \\\\\\"In the beginning of Arda, Melkor seduced him to his allegiance.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-18\\\\\\">[17]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>As for Sauron's motives, Tolkien noted that \\\\\\"it had been his virtue (and therefore also the cause of his fall ...) that he loved order and coordination, and disliked all confusion and wasteful friction\\\\\\". Thus \\\\\\"it was the apparent will and power of Melkor to effect his designs quickly and masterfully that had first attracted Sauron to him\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-19\\\\\\">[18]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>For a while, Sauron apparently kept up the pretence that he was a faithful servant of the Valar, all the while feeding Melkor information about their doings. Thus, when the Valar made\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almaren\\\\\\">Almaren</a>\\\\u00a0as their first physical abode in the world, \\\\\\"Melkor knew of all that was done; for even then he had secret friends and spies among the Maiar whom he had converted to his cause, and of these the chief, as after became known, was Sauron.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-ME-ref.7CMR.7Cp._52-15\\\\\\">[14]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Melkor soon destroyed Almaren, and the Valar established a new abode in the Uttermost West: the Blessed Realm of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valinor\\\\\\">Valinor</a>. They still did not perceive Sauron's treachery, for he too became \\\\\\"a being of Valinor\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters151-20\\\\\\">[19]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>At some point, Sauron left the Blessed Realm and went to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>, the central continent of Arda, where Melkor had established his stronghold. In one text, Tolkien wrote of Sauron that \\\\\\"in Valinor he had dwelt among the hosts of the gods, but there Morgoth had drawn him to evil and to his service\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-21\\\\\\">[20]</a>\\\\u00a0Sauron deserted his service to the Valar and openly joined their great enemy: \\\\\\"Because of his admiration of Strength he had become a follower of Morgoth and fell with him down into the depths of evil.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-letters243fn-9\\\\\\">[8]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"The Lieutenant of Melkor\\", \\"size\\": \\"h4\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After joining his new master in Middle-earth, Sauron proved to be a devoted and capable servant: \\\\\\"While Morgoth still stood, Sauron did not seek his own supremacy, but worked and schemed for another, desiring the triumph of Melkor, whom in the beginning he had adored. He thus was often able to achieve things, first conceived by Melkor, which his master did not or could not complete in the furious haste of his malice.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-ME-ref.7CMR.7Cp._420-22\\\\\\">[21]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0\\\\\\"In all the deeds of Melkor the Morgoth upon Arda, in his vast works and in the deceits of his cunning, Sauron had a part.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-23\\\\\\">[22]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In chapter three of\\\\u00a0<i>The Silmarillion</i>, Tolkien writes that by the time the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elves</a>\\\\u00a0awoke in the world, Sauron had become Melkor's lieutenant and was given command over the newly built stronghold of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angband\\\\\\">Angband</a>. To protect the Elves, the Valar made war on Melkor and captured him, but could not find Sauron.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Thus, \\\\\\"when Melkor was made captive, Sauron escaped and lay hid in Middle-earth; and it can in this way be understood how the breeding of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Orcs</a>\\\\u00a0(no doubt already begun) went on with increasing speed\\\\\\". In the Blessed Realm, Melkor feigned reform, but eventually escaped back to Middle-earth, holding the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silmaril\\\\\\">Silmarils</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F%C3%ABanor\\\\\\">F\\\\u00ebanor</a>. By then, Sauron had \\\\\\"secretly repaired Angband for the help of his Master when he returned; and there the dark places underground were already manned with hosts of the Orcs before Melkor came back at last, as Morgoth the Black Enemy\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron#cite_note-24\\\\\\">[23]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Shortly after the return of Morgoth, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noldor\\\\\\">Noldorin</a>\\\\u00a0Elves also left the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blessed_Realm_of_Valinor\\\\\\">Blessed Realm of Valinor</a>\\\\u00a0in the Uttermost West, against the counsel of the Valar, to wage war on Morgoth, who had stolen the Silmarils. In that war, Sauron served as Morgoth's chief lieutenant, surpassing all others in rank, such as\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gothmog\\\\\\">Gothmog</a>, the Lord of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balrog\\\\\\">Balrogs</a>. Known as\\\\u00a0<b>Gorthaur the Cruel</b>, Sauron was at that time a master of illusions and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shapeshifting\\\\\\">shapeshifting</a>;\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Werewolf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">werewolves</a>\\\\u00a0and vampires were his servants, chief among them\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Draugluin\\\\\\">Draugluin</a>, Father of Werewolves, and his vampire herald\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thuringwethil\\\\\\">Thuringwethil</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>When Morgoth left Angband to corrupt the newly discovered\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Men</a>, Sauron directed the war against the Elves. He conquered the Elvish island of Tol Sirion and its watchtower\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith_(First_Age)\\\\\\">Minas Tirith</a>, so that it became known as\\\\u00a0<i>Tol-in-Gaurhoth,</i>\\\\u00a0the Isle of Werewolves.</p>\\"}]", "path": "000100010001000A", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T22:03:52.860Z", "image": 16, "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_interests": 3, "host_page": 33, "pk": 10}], "title": "Sauron", "show_in_menus": false, "locked": false, "expire_at": null, "seo_title": "", "first_published_at":