86	f	2017-01-23 07:43:39.036+00	{"host_place_relationship": [{"place": 15, "host_page": 28, "pk": 6}], "pk": 28, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/\\u00e9owyn/", "go_live_at": null, "live": true, "content_type": 12, "numchild": 0, "expired": false, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>\\\\u00c9owyn is a fictional character in Tolkien's legendarium who appears in his most famous work, The Lord of the Rings. She is a noblewoman of Rohan who is described as a shieldmaiden.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Literature\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Two_Towers\\\\\\">The Two Towers</a></i>, \\\\u00c9owyn, a daughter of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Kings_of_Rohan#House_of_Eorl\\\\\\">House of Eorl</a>\\\\u00a0and the goddaughter of King\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C3%A9oden\\\\\\">Th\\\\u00e9oden</a>\\\\u00a0of Rohan, is introduced in Meduseld, the king's hall at Edoras.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-hall-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0She was the daughter of Th\\\\u00e9odwyn (Th\\\\u00e9oden's sister) and \\\\u00c9omund and the sister of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89omer\\\\\\">\\\\u00c9omer</a>. When she was only seven years old, her father was killed fighting\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0and her mother died of grief. \\\\u00c9owyn and \\\\u00c9omer were raised in her uncle's household as if they were his own children.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Tolkien writes that she longed to win renown in battle\\\\u2014especially since she was royal\\\\u2014but being female, her duties were reckoned to be at Edoras.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-healing-2\\\\\\">[2]</a>\\\\u00a0When Th\\\\u00e9oden's mind was poisoned by his adviser\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr%C3%ADma_Wormtongue\\\\\\">Gr\\\\u00edma Wormtongue</a>, \\\\u00c9owyn was obliged to care for her uncle, and his deterioration pained her deeply. To make matters worse, she was constantly harassed by Gr\\\\u00edma, who lusted after her. However, when\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0arrived, he freed Th\\\\u00e9oden from Wormtongue's influence.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>\\\\u00c9owyn fell in love with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\\\\\">Aragorn</a>, but it soon became clear that he could not return her love although he did not mention his betrothal to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arwen\\\\\\">Arwen</a>, except by indirect allusion, and would not allow her to join him in going to war.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-grey-3\\\\\\">[3]</a>\\\\u00a0As Aragorn pointed out,<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-grey-3\\\\\\">[3]</a>\\\\u00a0her duty was with her hosts; she had to shoulder the responsibility of ruling Rohan in Th\\\\u00e9oden's stead when the war-host of Rohan went to war,<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-hall-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0a duty he deemed no less valiant.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-grey-3\\\\\\">[3]</a>\\\\u00a0Likening her situation to a \\\\\\"cage\\\\\\", \\\\u00c9owyn said she feared \\\\\\"[t]o stay behind bars, until use and old age accept them, and all chance of great deeds is gone beyond recall or desire.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-grey-3\\\\\\">[3]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\", \\"value\\": {\\"attribute_name\\": \\"Aragorn\\", \\"text\\": \\"But who knows what she spoke to the darkness, alone, in the bitter watches of the night, when all her life seemed shrinking, and the walls of her bower closing in about her, a hutch to trammel some wild thing in?\\", \\"attribute_group\\": \\"\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\\\\\">The Return of the King</a>\\\\u00a0</i>she disguised herself as a man and under the alias of\\\\u00a0<i>Dernhelm</i>\\\\u00a0(from Old English\\\\u00a0<i>dern</i>\\\\u00a0meaning \\\\\\"secret, concealed\\\\\\"), and she traveled with the Riders of Rohan to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_the_Pelennor_Fields\\\\\\">Battle of the Pelennor Fields</a>\\\\u00a0outside the White City of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith\\\\\\">Minas Tirith</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondor</a>, carrying with her\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>, who had also been ordered to remain behind, on her horse Windfola.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>During the battle of the Pelennor Fields, she confronted the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witch-king_of_Angmar\\\\\\">Witch-king of Angmar</a>, Lord of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl\\\\\\">Nazg\\\\u00fbl</a>, after Th\\\\u00e9oden was injured. The Witch-king threatened to \\\\\\"bear [her] away to the houses of lamentation, beyond all darkness, where [her] flesh shall be devoured, and [her] shriveled mind be left naked to the Lidless Eye.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-pelennor-4\\\\\\">[4]</a>\\\\u00a0The Witch-king further boasted that \\\\\\"[n]o living man may hinder me,\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-pelennor-4\\\\\\">[4]</a>\\\\u00a0referring to the 1,000-year-old\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prophecy\\\\\\">prophecy</a>\\\\u00a0by the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elf</a>-lord\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glorfindel\\\\\\">Glorfindel</a>, foretelling that the Witch-king would not fall \\\\\\"by the hand of man\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-glorfindel-5\\\\\\">[5]</a>\\\\u00a0\\\\u00c9owyn then removed her helmet and declared.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>But no living man am I! You look upon a woman. \\\\u00c9owyn I am, \\\\u00c9omund\\\\u2019s daughter. You stand between me and my lord and kin. Begone, if you be not deathless! For living or dark undead, I will smite you, if you touch him.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-pelennor-4\\\\\\">[4]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Witch-king attacked \\\\u00c9owyn with his\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl#Steeds\\\\\\">steed</a>, but she slew it with her sword. He then shattered her shield and broke her shield-arm with his mace, but was distracted by Merry, who stabbed him behind the knee with a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrow-blade\\\\\\">barrow-blade</a>. \\\\u00c9owyn seized the opportunity to strike the Witch-king with a killing thrust \\\\\\"between crown and mantle\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-pelennor-4\\\\\\">[4]</a>\\\\u00a0Then, as her sword shattered, his withering form collapsed and he vanished with a final cry of anguish.</p>\\"}]", "path": "0001000100010005", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T21:40:27.200Z", "image": 19, "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_interests": 1, "host_page": 28, "pk": 5}], "title": "\\u00c9owyn", "show_in_menus": false, "locked": false, "expire_at": null, "seo_title": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T21:40:27.266Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "depth": 4, "host_experience_relationship": [{"experiences": 26, "host_page": 28, "pk": 12, "sort_order": 0}, {"experiences": 21, "host_page": 28, "pk": 13, "sort_order": 1}, {"experiences": 24, "host_page": 28, "pk": 14, "sort_order": 2}, {"experiences": 22, "host_page": 28, "pk": 15, "sort_order": 3}], "owner": 1, "slug": "\\u00e9owyn", "search_description": ""}	\N	28	1
77	f	2017-01-23 07:17:54.527+00	{"host_place_relationship": [{"place": 18, "host_page": 36, "pk": 14}], "pk": 36, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/samwise-gamgee/", "go_live_at": null, "live": true, "content_type": 12, "numchild": 0, "expired": false, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Samwise</b>\\\\u00a0\\\\\\"<b>Sam</b>\\\\\\"\\\\u00a0<b>Gamgee</b>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English\\\\\\">/\\\\u02c8s\\\\u00e6m\\\\u02ccwa\\\\u026az\\\\u00a0\\\\u02c8\\\\u0261\\\\u00e6m\\\\u02ccd\\\\u0292i\\\\u02d0/</a>\\\\u00a0(later known as Samwise Gardner)<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee#cite_note-gardner-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_character\\\\\\">fictional character</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tolkien%27s_legendarium\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien's legendarium</a>. Samwise is one of the main characters of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>, in which he fills an\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archetype\\\\\\">archetypical</a>\\\\u00a0role as the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sidekick\\\\\\">sidekick</a>\\\\u00a0of the primary\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protagonist\\\\\\">protagonist</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>. Sam is a member of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Literature\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Samwise Gamgee is first introduced in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>. Sam is\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>' gardener, having inherited the position as Baggins' gardener from his father,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaffer_Gamgee\\\\\\">Hamfast \\\\\\"Gaffer\\\\\\" Gamgee</a>. At the time of the War of the Ring, Sam was living in Number 3,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#Bagshot_Row\\\\\\">Bagshot Row</a>\\\\u00a0with his father.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>As \\\\\\"punishment\\\\\\" for\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eavesdropping\\\\\\">eavesdropping</a>\\\\u00a0on\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>'s conversation with Frodo regarding the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>, Sam was made Frodo's first companion on his journey to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>. They were joined by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Peregrin Took</a>, Frodo's cousins, and journeyed together to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, where the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_Elrond\\\\\\">Council of Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0took place and Sam joined the Fellowship of the Ring.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>When the Fellowship was split up at the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falls_of_Rauros\\\\\\">Falls of Rauros</a>, Sam insisted on accompanying Frodo. Sam protected and cared for Frodo, who was growing weaker under the Ring's influence, as they moved through the dangerous lands toward\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>. Sam distrusted\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gollum\\\\\\">Gollum</a>, who became their guide into Mordor. His suspicions were proven right when Gollum betrayed them to the giant spider\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelob\\\\\\">Shelob</a>. After Shelob apparently killed Frodo, Sam drove her off. When a band of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0approached, Sam was forced to leave the apparently dead Frodo and take the Ring himself, and briefly became a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring-bearer\\\\\\">Ring-bearer</a>. He was momentarily tempted by its promise of power, but did not succumb to it, subsequently rescuing Frodo (who had only been paralysed) from the Orcs who held him captive. Sam also returned the Ring to Frodo, making him the only Ring-bearer to freely give up the Ring without intervention. The two then journeyed alone through Mordor and into the heart of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Doom\\\\\\">Mount Doom</a>, where Gollum attacked Frodo and reclaimed the Ring, only to inadvertently destroy both it and himself by falling into the mountain's lava.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/l1eLHoDxMNE\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After the hobbits' return home and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Bywater\\\\\\">Battle of Bywater</a>, Sam travelled the length and breadth of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0replanting trees that had been cut down during\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>'s brief reign. He used the gift of earth given to him by the Lady\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galadriel\\\\\\">Galadriel</a>, which caused the saplings he planted to grow at an accelerated rate. The small amount remaining he took to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-Farthing_Stone\\\\\\">Three-Farthing Stone</a>\\\\u00a0(roughly the centre of the Shire) and cast into the air, prompting the bountiful period of growth starting in the spring of the year 1420 (<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_Reckoning\\\\\\">Shire Reckoning</a>). The greatest wonder was a young\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mallorn\\\\\\">mallorn</a></i>\\\\u00a0tree sprouting in the Party Field: \\\\\\"the only\\\\u00a0<i>mallorn</i>\\\\u00a0west of the Mountains and east of the Sea\\\\\\" (grown from a nut included as part of Galadriel's gift).</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After the War of the Ring, Sam married\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Hobbits#Rose_Cotton\\\\\\">Rose \\\\\\"Rosie\\\\\\" Cotton</a>\\\\u00a0and moved to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bag_End\\\\\\">Bag End</a>\\\\u00a0with Frodo. Sam and Rosie had 13 children:\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elanor_the_Fair\\\\\\">Elanor the Fair</a>, Frodo, Rose, Merry, Pippin, Goldilocks, Hamfast, Daisy, Primrose, Bilbo, Ruby, Robin, and Tolman (Tom). Sam was elected\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mayor_of_the_Shire\\\\\\">Mayor of the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0for seven consecutive seven-year terms and came to be known as Samwise Gardner.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After Sam and Rose's first child was born, Frodo told Sam he would leave\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>, along with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins\\\\\\">Bilbo Baggins</a>, Gandalf and most of the remaining High\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elves</a>, for the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Undying_Lands\\\\\\">Undying Lands</a>. Before Frodo left, he gave the estate of Bag End to Sam, as well as the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Book_of_Westmarch\\\\\\">Red Book of Westmarch</a></i>\\\\u00a0for Sam to continue, hinting that Sam might also be allowed to travel into the West eventually.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After the death of his wife in the year 62 of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourth_Age\\\\\\">Fourth Age</a>\\\\u00a0(<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_Calendar\\\\\\">Shire Reckoning</a>\\\\u00a01482), Sam entrusted the Red Book to Elanor and left the Shire at the age of 102. He was not seen again in Middle-earth, but Elanor and her descendants preserved the tradition that he went to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_Havens\\\\\\">Grey Havens</a>\\\\u00a0and sailed into the West. As the last of the Ring-bearers, he was entitled to sail across the Sea and be reunited with Frodo in the Undying Lands.</p>\\"}]", "path": "000100010001000D", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T22:13:57.951Z", "image": 25, "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_interests": 4, "host_page": 36, "pk": 13}], "title": "Sam", "show_in_menus": false, "locked": false, "expire_at": null, "seo_title": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T22:13:58.009Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "depth": 4, "host_experience_relationship": [{"experiences": 26, "host_page": 36, "pk": 35, "sort_order": 0}, {"experiences": 23, "host_page": 36, "pk": 36, "sort_order": 1}, {"experiences": 22, "host_page": 36, "pk": 37, "sort_order": 2}], "owner": 1, "slug": "samwise-gamgee", "search_description": ""}	\N	36	1
80	f	2017-01-23 07:20:06.748+00	{"host_place_relationship": [{"place": 18, "host_page": 36, "pk": 14}], "pk": 36, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/samwise-gamgee/", "go_live_at": null, "live": true, "content_type": 12, "numchild": 0, "expired": false, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Samwise</b>\\\\u00a0\\\\\\"<b>Sam</b>\\\\\\"\\\\u00a0<b>Gamgee</b>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English\\\\\\">/\\\\u02c8s\\\\u00e6m\\\\u02ccwa\\\\u026az\\\\u00a0\\\\u02c8\\\\u0261\\\\u00e6m\\\\u02ccd\\\\u0292i\\\\u02d0/</a>\\\\u00a0(later known as Samwise Gardner)<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee#cite_note-gardner-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_character\\\\\\">fictional character</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tolkien%27s_legendarium\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien's legendarium</a>. Samwise is one of the main characters of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>, in which he fills an\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archetype\\\\\\">archetypical</a>\\\\u00a0role as the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sidekick\\\\\\">sidekick</a>\\\\u00a0of the primary\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protagonist\\\\\\">protagonist</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>. Sam is a member of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Literature\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Samwise Gamgee is first introduced in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>. Sam is\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>' gardener, having inherited the position as Baggins' gardener from his father,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaffer_Gamgee\\\\\\">Hamfast \\\\\\"Gaffer\\\\\\" Gamgee</a>. At the time of the War of the Ring, Sam was living in Number 3,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#Bagshot_Row\\\\\\">Bagshot Row</a>\\\\u00a0with his father.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>As \\\\\\"punishment\\\\\\" for\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eavesdropping\\\\\\">eavesdropping</a>\\\\u00a0on\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>'s conversation with Frodo regarding the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>, Sam was made Frodo's first companion on his journey to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>. They were joined by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Peregrin Took</a>, Frodo's cousins, and journeyed together to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, where the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_Elrond\\\\\\">Council of Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0took place and Sam joined the Fellowship of the Ring.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>When the Fellowship was split up at the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falls_of_Rauros\\\\\\">Falls of Rauros</a>, Sam insisted on accompanying Frodo. Sam protected and cared for Frodo, who was growing weaker under the Ring's influence, as they moved through the dangerous lands toward\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>. Sam distrusted\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gollum\\\\\\">Gollum</a>, who became their guide into Mordor. His suspicions were proven right when Gollum betrayed them to the giant spider\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelob\\\\\\">Shelob</a>. After Shelob apparently killed Frodo, Sam drove her off. When a band of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0approached, Sam was forced to leave the apparently dead Frodo and take the Ring himself, and briefly became a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring-bearer\\\\\\">Ring-bearer</a>. He was momentarily tempted by its promise of power, but did not succumb to it, subsequently rescuing Frodo (who had only been paralysed) from the Orcs who held him captive. Sam also returned the Ring to Frodo, making him the only Ring-bearer to freely give up the Ring without intervention. The two then journeyed alone through Mordor and into the heart of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Doom\\\\\\">Mount Doom</a>, where Gollum attacked Frodo and reclaimed the Ring, only to inadvertently destroy both it and himself by falling into the mountain's lava.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/l1eLHoDxMNE\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After the hobbits' return home and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Bywater\\\\\\">Battle of Bywater</a>, Sam travelled the length and breadth of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0replanting trees that had been cut down during\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>'s brief reign. He used the gift of earth given to him by the Lady\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galadriel\\\\\\">Galadriel</a>, which caused the saplings he planted to grow at an accelerated rate. The small amount remaining he took to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-Farthing_Stone\\\\\\">Three-Farthing Stone</a>\\\\u00a0(roughly the centre of the Shire) and cast into the air, prompting the bountiful period of growth starting in the spring of the year 1420 (<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_Reckoning\\\\\\">Shire Reckoning</a>). The greatest wonder was a young\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mallorn\\\\\\">mallorn</a></i>\\\\u00a0tree sprouting in the Party Field: \\\\\\"the only\\\\u00a0<i>mallorn</i>\\\\u00a0west of the Mountains and east of the Sea\\\\\\" (grown from a nut included as part of Galadriel's gift).</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After the War of the Ring, Sam married\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Hobbits#Rose_Cotton\\\\\\">Rose \\\\\\"Rosie\\\\\\" Cotton</a>\\\\u00a0and moved to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bag_End\\\\\\">Bag End</a>\\\\u00a0with Frodo. Sam and Rosie had 13 children:\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elanor_the_Fair\\\\\\">Elanor the Fair</a>, Frodo, Rose, Merry, Pippin, Goldilocks, Hamfast, Daisy, Primrose, Bilbo, Ruby, Robin, and Tolman (Tom). Sam was elected\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mayor_of_the_Shire\\\\\\">Mayor of the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0for seven consecutive seven-year terms and came to be known as Samwise Gardner.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After Sam and Rose's first child was born, Frodo told Sam he would leave\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>, along with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins\\\\\\">Bilbo Baggins</a>, Gandalf and most of the remaining High\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elves</a>, for the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Undying_Lands\\\\\\">Undying Lands</a>. Before Frodo left, he gave the estate of Bag End to Sam, as well as the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Book_of_Westmarch\\\\\\">Red Book of Westmarch</a></i>\\\\u00a0for Sam to continue, hinting that Sam might also be allowed to travel into the West eventually.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>After the death of his wife in the year 62 of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourth_Age\\\\\\">Fourth Age</a>\\\\u00a0(<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_Calendar\\\\\\">Shire Reckoning</a>\\\\u00a01482), Sam entrusted the Red Book to Elanor and left the Shire at the age of 102. He was not seen again in Middle-earth, but Elanor and her descendants preserved the tradition that he went to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_Havens\\\\\\">Grey Havens</a>\\\\u00a0and sailed into the West. As the last of the Ring-bearers, he was entitled to sail across the Sea and be reunited with Frodo in the Undying Lands.</p>\\"}]", "path": "000100010001000D", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-23T07:17:54.527Z", "image": 33, "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_interests": 4, "host_page": 36, "pk": 13}], "title": "Sam", "show_in_menus": false, "locked": false, "expire_at": null, "seo_title": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T22:13:58.009Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "depth": 4, "host_experience_relationship": [{"experiences": 26, "host_page": 36, "pk": 35, "sort_order": 0}, {"experiences": 23, "host_page": 36, "pk": 36, "sort_order": 1}, {"experiences": 22, "host_page": 36, "pk": 37, "sort_order": 2}], "owner": 1, "slug": "samwise-gamgee", "search_description": ""}	\N	36	1
78	f	2017-01-23 07:18:06.38+00	{"host_place_relationship": [{"place": 17, "host_page": 31, "pk": 9}], "pk": 31, "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/meriadoc-brandybuck/", "go_live_at": null, "live": true, "content_type": 12, "numchild": 0, "expired": false, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Meriadoc Brandybuck</b>, usually referred to as\\\\u00a0<b>Merry</b>, is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_character\\\\\\">fictional character</a>\\\\u00a0from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legendarium\\\\\\">legendarium</a>, featured throughout his most famous work,\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>A lover of boats and maps, Merry is described as one of the closest friends of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>, the main protagonist. Merry is a member of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Family and relations\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Frodo and Merry are\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cousin#First_cousins\\\\\\">first cousins once removed</a>. Their common ancestors are\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Hobbits#G\\\\\\">Gorbadoc Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Hobbits#M\\\\\\">Mirabella Took Brandybuck</a>.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck#cite_note-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Merry was born\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a02982 (or, in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth_calendar#Shire_calendar\\\\\\">Shire-reckoning</a>, in 1382), in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Buckland</a>.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[2]</a>\\\\u00a0He is the only child of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Hobbits#S\\\\\\">Saradoc Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0(T.A. 2940-<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourth_Age\\\\\\">F.A.</a>\\\\u00a011), who was a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brandybuck_Clan#Masters_of_Buckland\\\\\\">Master of Buckland</a>, and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Hobbits#E\\\\\\">Esmeralda Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0(n\\\\u00e9e Took) (T.A. 2936-\\\\u00a0?), the younger sister of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Hobbits#P\\\\\\">Paladin Took II</a>\\\\u00a0(T.A. 2933\\\\u20133034), making him first cousin to Paladin's son\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Peregrin Took</a>. (See\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, Appendix C.)</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Merry later married\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Hobbits#E\\\\\\">Estella (Bolger) Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0(T.A. 2985\\\\u2013?), the younger sister of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fredegar_Bolger\\\\\\">Fredegar Bolger</a>, who helped Frodo, Sam, Merry and Pippin on the first leg of their quest journey. Meriadoc and Estella had at least one son.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck#cite_note-M-E_Encyc-3\\\\\\">[3]</a></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Literature\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, Merry is often considered, and was described by Tolkien as, the most perceptive and intelligent of the hobbits. Even before\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins\\\\\\">Bilbo Baggins</a>\\\\u00a0left\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>, he knew of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>\\\\u00a0and its power of invisibility. He guarded\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bag_End\\\\\\">Bag End</a>\\\\u00a0after Bilbo's party, protecting Frodo from the various and often unwanted guests. He is knowledgeable and has an innocent, teasing sense of humour. In one incident,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lobelia_Sackville-Baggins\\\\\\">Lobelia Sackville-Baggins</a>\\\\u00a0accused Frodo of being a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brandybuck_clan\\\\\\">Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and no true\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_hobbit_families#B\\\\\\">Baggins</a>. Merry assured Frodo, \\\\\\"It was a compliment; and so, of course, not true\\\\\\".</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Merry was also a force behind \\\\\\"the Conspiracy\\\\\\" of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee\\\\\\">Sam</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Pippin</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fredegar_Bolger\\\\\\">Fredegar Bolger</a>\\\\u00a0and himself to help Frodo. Thus, at the beginning of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>, Merry was well-prepared and organized \\\\u2014 he assembled their packs and brought ponies. His shortcut through the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Forest\\\\\\">Old Forest</a>\\\\u00a0distanced them from the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl\\\\\\">Nazg\\\\u00fbl</a>\\\\u00a0for a time, though they had to be rescued from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Man_Willow\\\\\\">Old Man Willow</a>\\\\u00a0by the enigmatic\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Bombadil\\\\\\">Tom Bombadil</a>. In the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrow-downs_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Barrow-downs</a>, he acquired his sword, which was actually a dagger forged in the kingdom of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arnor\\\\\\">Arnor</a>.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>At\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bree_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Bree</a>, Merry was actually not present in the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prancing_Pony\\\\\\">Prancing Pony</a></i>\\\\u00a0when Frodo put on the Ring; instead, he was outside taking a walk, and was nearly overcome by a Nazg\\\\u00fbl. At\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, he was seen studying maps and plotting their path. He was admitted to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship</a>\\\\u00a0only a little less reluctantly than Pippin; they were the two youngest members, and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0had planned on sending them back to the Shire.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/kTnQeasvbZo\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>At the entrance to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moria_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Moria</a>, he asked\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0the meaning of the door inscription \\\\\\"Speak, friend, and enter\\\\\\". When Gandalf discovered the true interpretation, he said, \\\\\\"Merry, of all hosts, was on the right track\\\\\\".</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>At\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amon_Hen\\\\\\">Amon Hen</a>, he was captured, along with Pippin, by a band of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uruk-hai\\\\\\">Uruk-hai</a>, although he gave a good account of himself and was valiantly defended by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boromir\\\\\\">Boromir</a>. Escaping with Pippin into\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fangorn\\\\\\">Fangorn</a>forest, Merry was rescued by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard\\\\\\">Treebeard</a>. Along with Pippin, he drank significant amounts of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ent-draught\\\\\\">Ent-draught</a>\\\\u00a0and grew taller, despite being a fully grown adult Hobbit. Accompanying Treebeard to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entmoot\\\\\\">Entmoot</a>\\\\u00a0and later to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isengard\\\\\\">Isengard</a>, he and Pippin took up residence in an Isengard gate-house. It was here that he first encountered\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C3%A9oden\\\\\\">King Th\\\\u00e9oden</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>, and was reunited with four of the remaining members of the Fellowship.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Merry was separated from Pippin after his friend beheld\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>\\\\u00a0in the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palant%C3%ADr\\\\\\">palant\\\\u00edr</a></i>\\\\u00a0and was then hastily taken to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondor</a>\\\\u00a0with Gandalf on\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shadowfax_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Shadowfax</a>. Merry swore fealty to Th\\\\u00e9oden and became esquire to the king. Against Th\\\\u00e9oden's orders, he rode to Gondor with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn\\\\\\">\\\\u00c9owyn</a>, who was disguised as a common soldier. In the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_the_Pelennor_Fields\\\\\\">Battle of the Pelennor Fields</a>, while the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witch-king_of_Angmar\\\\\\">Witch-king of Angmar</a>\\\\u00a0was preoccupied with \\\\u00c9owyn, Merry stabbed him in the sinew behind his knee with a sword that was made by the D\\\\u00fanedain of Arnor for combat against the Nazg\\\\u00fbl. The Black Captain stumbled from Merry's stroke, and \\\\u00c9owyn seized the moment to strike the Captain's head, destroying him. This fulfilled the prophecy, as he was not killed \\\\\\"by the hand of man,\\\\\\" but rather by a hobbit and a woman. Merry heard Th\\\\u00e9oden's last words, but went unnoticed by the honour escort of Riders; Pippin found him wandering in the city.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\\\\\">Aragorn</a>\\\\u00a0healed him and he recovered fully, more quickly than \\\\u00c9owyn.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>For his bravery in battle, Merry was knighted by King\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89omer\\\\\\">\\\\u00c9omer</a>\\\\u00a0as a Knight of the Mark. During the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scouring_of_the_Shire\\\\\\">scouring of the Shire</a>, he led the hobbits in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Bywater\\\\\\">Battle of Bywater</a>, and personally killed the leader of the opposing forces.</p>\\"}]", "path": "0001000100010008", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T21:54:06.997Z", "image": 22, "host_interest_relationship": [{"host_interests": 4, "host_page": 31, "pk": 8}], "title": "Merry", "show_in_menus": false, "locked": false, "expire_at": null, "seo_title": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T21:54:07.074Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "depth": 4, "host_experience_relationship": [{"experiences": 21, "host_page": 31, "pk": 21, "sort_order": 0}, {"experiences": 25, "host_page": 31, "pk": 22, "sort_order": 1}, {"experiences": 23, "host_page": 31, "pk": 23, "sort_order": 2}, {"experiences": 20, "host_page": 31, "pk": 24, "sort_order": 3}], "owner": 1, "slug": "meriadoc-brandybuck", "search_description": ""}	\N	31	1
90	f	2017-01-23 07:50:25.055+00	{"pk": 18, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/shire/", "go_live_at": null, "live": true, "content_type": 6, "numchild": 0, "expired": false, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Shire is a region of J. R. R. Tolkien's fictional Middle-earth, described in The Lord of the Rings and other works. The Shire refers to an area settled exclusively by Hobbits and largely removed from the goings-on in the rest of Middle-earth. It is located in the northwest of the continent, in the large region of Eriador and the Kingdom of Arnor. In the languages invented by Tolkien, its name in Westron was S\\\\u00fbza \\\\\\"Shire\\\\\\"[1] or S\\\\u00fbzat \\\\\\"The Shire\\\\\\",[2] while its name in Sindarin was i Drann.[3]</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Geography\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>According to Tolkien, the Shire measured 40 leagues (193 km, 120 miles[4]) from the Far Downs in the west to the Brandywine Bridge in the east, and 50 leagues (241 km, 150 miles) from the northern moors to the marshes in the south.[5] This is confirmed in an essay by Tolkien on translating The Lord of the Rings,[6] where he describes the Shire as having an area of 18,000 square miles (47,000 km2).[7]</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/Ti5OaadrS9I\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The original territory of the Shire was bounded on the east by the Baranduin River, on the north by uplands rising to the old centre of Arnor, on the west by the White Downs, and on the south by marshland south of the River Shirebourn. After the original settlement, hobbits also expanded to the east into Buckland between the Baranduin and the Old Forest, and (much later) to the west into the Westmarch between the White Downs and the Tower Hills.[8]</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Shire was originally divided into four Farthings. The outlying lands of Buckland and the Westmarch were formally added after the War of the Ring.[5] Within the Farthings there are some smaller unofficial clan homelands: the Tooks nearly all live in or near Tuckborough in Tookland, for instance. A Hobbit surname often indicates where the family came from: Samwise Gamgee's last name derives from Gamwich, where the family originated. Buckland was named for the Oldbucks (later called the Brandybucks).</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Shire is described as a small but beautiful, idyllic and fruitful land, beloved by its inhabitants. The Hobbits had an extensive agricultural system in the Shire but were not industrialised. The landscape included small pockets of forest (again similar to the English countryside). Various supplies were produced in the Shire, including cereals, fruit, wood and pipe-weed.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Regions of the Shire\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The original parts of the Shire were subdivided into four Farthings (\\\\\\"fourth-ings\\\\\\" or \\\\\\"quarterings\\\\\\").[9] The Three-Farthing Stone marked the tripoint where the borders of the Eastfarthing, Westfarthing and Southfarthing of the Shire came together, by the East Road.[10] (Iceland was traditionally also divided in Farthings, or \\\\\\"fourth parts\\\\\\", as the Shire is.) It is claimed that the Three-Farthing Stone was inspired by the Four shire stone.[11]</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Buckland, across the Baranduin River to the east, and the Westmarch, between the Far Downs and the Tower Hills to the west, were not part of the original grant to the hobbits by King Argeleb II of Arthedain. These were formally given to the hobbits as the East and West Marches of the Shire by King Elessar after the War of the Ring, in S.R. 1462 (F.A. 41).[9][12] Buckland had been long settled by then: Gorhendad Oldbuck led hobbits from the East Farthing across the river in T.A. 2340,[12] and Buckland became \\\\\\"sort of a colony of the Shire\\\\\\".[13] There is no mention of settlement in the Westmarch until Elessar's gift; Sam Gamgee's daughter Elanor and her husband Fastred later settled there, and Fastred was created Warden of Westmarch.</p>\\"}]", "path": "0001000100030007", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T20:11:19.675Z", "image": 14, "title": "The Shire", "show_in_menus": false, "locked": false, "expire_at": null, "seo_title": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:11:19.705Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "depth": 4, "owner": 1, "slug": "shire", "search_description": ""}	\N	18	1
82	f	2017-01-23 07:24:45.4+00	{"pk": 16, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/edoras/", "go_live_at": null, "live": true, "content_type": 6, "numchild": 0, "expired": false, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The capital of Rohan is the hill fort of Edoras which is located on a hill in a valley of the White Mountains. Meduseld, the Golden Hall of the King of Rohan, is located there. \\\\\\"Edoras\\\\\\" is Old English for \\\\\\"enclosures\\\\\\",[4] which Tolkien held to be a translation of an unknown Rohirric name of the same meaning. The city of Edoras was built by Rohan's second King, Brego son of Eorl the Young. Before Edoras was completed, Rohan's capital was at Aldburg in the Folde. Meduseld is described as having a golden thatch. Edoras is built at the end of the valley of Harrowdale, which lies under the great mountain Starkhorn. The river Snowbourn flows past the city on its way east towards the Entwash. The city is protected only by a high wall of timber, and a one-way road allows access to the city. Just before the gates, two rows of mounds line the road, which are the graves of the former Kings of Rohan. \\\\\\"Meduseld\\\\\\", a modernised form of the Old English Maeduselde,[5] is similarly meant to be a translation of an unknown Rohirric name meaning \\\\\\"mead hall\\\\\\". Meduseld is a large hall with roof that appears golden from far off. The walls are richly decorated with tapestries depicting the history and legends of the Rohirrim, and it serves as a house for the King and his kin, a meeting hall for the King and his advisors, and a gathering hall.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"caption\\": \\"The Uffington White Horse, whence the banner and shield of the House of Eorl \\\\u2013 a \\\\\\"white horse upon green\\\\\\" \\\\u2013 is derived.\\", \\"style\\": \\"half\\", \\"image\\": 11}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Edoras is Rohan's only real city. It is at Meduseld that Aragorn, Gimli, Legolas, and Gandalf meet with King Th\\\\u00e9oden in the account of the early stages of the War of the Ring.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Another settlement is Aldburg, capital of the Eastfold and original settlement of Eorl the Young. A third settlement is Snowbourne, named after the river of the same name which runs nearby. It is similar in appearance to the hill-fort of Edoras. Dunharrow is a refuge in the White Mountains. Helm's Deep is a valley in the White Mountains in which the Hornburg, a major fortress of Rohan, is located.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Internal history\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the thirteenth century of the Third Age (T.A.), the Kings of Gondor made close alliances with the Northmen of Rhovanion, a hosts said in The Lord of the Rings to be akin to the Three Houses of Men (later the D\\\\u00fanedain) from the First Age.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the twenty-first century, a remnant tribe of such Northmen calling itself the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od moved from the valleys of Anduin to the north west of Mirkwood, clearing out what remained of the recently defeated witch kingdom of Angmar, east of the Misty Mountains. While there, some dispute arose between them and the Dwarves over the treasure-hoard of Scatha the dragon.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Later, in 2509, Cirion the Steward of Gondor sent summons to the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od for aid in throwing off a combined invasion of Men from the north east of Middle-earth, and Orcs from Mordor.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Eorl the Young, king of the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od, answered the summons, and arrived unexpected at a decisive battle at the Field of Celebrant, routing the orc army, and then destroying it as it fled.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>As a reward, Eorl was given the plains of Calenardhon, and he moved his kingdom there. This land had earlier been part of Gondor proper, but had been devastated by the plague of 1636, and the survivors to a large extent slain in the invasion mentioned above.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\", \\"value\\": {\\"attribute_name\\": \\"Aragorn\\", \\"text\\": \\"Where now the horse and the rider? Where is the horn that was blowing?\\\\r\\\\nWhere is the helm and the hauberk, and the bright hair flowing?\\\\r\\\\nWhere is the hand on the harp-string, and the red fire glowing?\\\\r\\\\nWhere is the spring and the harvest and the tall corn growing?\\", \\"attribute_group\\": \\"Reciting a forgotten poem on Eorl the Young\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<br/><p>The first line of kings lasted for 249 years, until the ninth king Helm Hammerhand died. His sons had been killed earlier, and his nephew Fr\\\\u00e9al\\\\u00e1f Hildeson began the second line of kings, which lasted until the end of the Third Age.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In 2758, Rohan was invaded by Dunlendings under Wulf, son of Freca, of mixed Dunland and Rohan blood. The King, Helm Hammerhand, took refuge in the Hornburg until aid from Gondor and Dunharrow (a refuge of the Rohirrim) arrived a year later and defeated the invaders.<br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/SLxeNktacYs\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>It was soon after this that Saruman arrived and took over Isengard, and was welcomed as a strong ally, since it would take Rohan close to 200 years to recover its strength after the invasion.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In 3014, Saruman began using his influence to weaken the King, Th\\\\u00e9oden, as part of a campaign to invade or take over the kingdom. In 3019, he launched a great invasion of Rohan, with victory in the two first battles (at the Fords of Isen; Th\\\\u00e9oden's son, Th\\\\u00e9odred was killed during these attacks) and defeat at the Battle of the Hornburg, where the Huorns came to the aid of the Rohirrim.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>On the heels of this victory, Th\\\\u00e9oden rode with an army to Minas Tirith and helped break its siege in the Battle of the Pelennor Fields, where he was slain. \\\\u00c9omer, the nephew of King Th\\\\u00e9oden, then took up the reign, beginning the third line. Also in this battle, \\\\u00c9owyn, niece of King Th\\\\u00e9oden and sister of \\\\u00c9omer, slew the Lord of the Nazg\\\\u00fbl. \\\\u00c9omer rode with the armies of Gondor to the Black Gate of Mordor and took part in the Battle of the Morannon against the forces of Sauron, who were defeated when the Ruling Ring was destroyed.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The rule of the Stewards of Gondor was then over. King \\\\u00c9omer and the new king of Gondor, Elessar, renewed their oath of alliance, and reaffirmed Cirion's grant of Calenardhon to the Rohirrim. At this time, \\\\u00c9owyn married Faramir, Prince of Ithilien and Steward of Gondor, thus joining the lines of Gondor and Rohan.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the Fourth Age, Rohan remained in peaceful coexistence with the Reunited Kingdom. A Dwarven community developed in the caves of Helm's Deep, which became prosperous from its mining of precious materials.<br/></p>\\"}]", "path": "0001000100030005", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T20:00:16.513Z", "image": 12, "title": "Edoras", "show_in_menus": false, "locked": false, "expire_at": null, "seo_title": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:00:16.547Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "depth": 4, "owner": 1, "slug": "edoras", "search_description": ""}	\N	16	1
