97	f	2017-01-23 07:54:32.017+00	{"pk": 8, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/mordor/", "go_live_at": null, "live": true, "content_type": 6, "numchild": 0, "expired": false, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_world\\\\\\">fictional world</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>,\\\\u00a0<b>Mordor</b>\\\\u00a0(pronounced\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA\\\\\\">[\\\\u02c8m\\\\u0254rd\\\\u0254r]</a>; from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\\\\\">Sindarin</a>\\\\u00a0<i>Black Land</i>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quenya\\\\\\">Quenya</a>\\\\u00a0<i>Land of Shadow</i>) was the region occupied and controlled by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>, in the southeast of northwestern Middle-earth to the East of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anduin\\\\\\">Anduin</a>, the great river.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orodruin\\\\\\">Orodruin</a>, a volcano in Mordor, was the goal of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>\\\\u00a0(and later\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee\\\\\\">Sam Gamgee</a>) in the quest to destroy the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>.</p><p>Mordor has three enormous mountain ranges surrounding it, from the north, from the west and from the south. The mountains both protected the land from an unexpected invasion by any of the hosts living in those directions and kept those living in Mordor from escaping. Tolkien was reported to have identified Mordor with the volcano of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stromboli\\\\\\">Stromboli</a>\\\\u00a0off Sicily, in terms of geographic equivalency with the real world.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"caption\\": \\"Barad-d\\\\u00fbr looking over Mount Doom\\", \\"style\\": \\"contain\\", \\"image\\": 16}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Geography\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Three sides of Mordor were bounded by mountain ranges, arranged in a rough rectangle: the Ered Lithui (translated as 'Ash Mountains') on the north, and the Ephel D\\\\u00faath (literally, \\\\\\"Fence of Shadow\\\\\\") on the west and the south. In the northwest the pass of Cirith Gorgor led into the enclosed plain of Ud\\\\u00fbn. Sauron built the Black Gate of Mordor (the Morannon) across the pass, joining the Towers of the Teeth, two earlier guard towers built by Gondor to keep a watch on this entrance. The passage through the inner side of Ud\\\\u00fbn into the interior of Mordor was guarded by another gate, the Isenmouthe. Outside the Morannon lay the Dagorlad or Battle Plain.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the interior within this mountainous border lay Sauron's main fortress Barad-d\\\\u00fbr, the arid plateau of Gorgoroth, and Mount Doom. To the east lay the plain of Lithlad. A narrow pass led through the Ephel D\\\\u00faath, guarded by Minas Morgul (earlier Minas Ithil). A higher, more difficult pass, Cirith Ungol, just to the north, was guarded by a tower originally built by Gondor. This pass, \\\\\\"the pass of the spider\\\\\\", was also blockaded by Torech Ungol, the lair of the giant spider Shelob. The fortress Durthang lay in the northern Ephel D\\\\u00faath above Ud\\\\u00fbn.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/jk9wwlzuwJE\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>N\\\\u00farn, the southern part of Mordor, was less arid and more fertile. Streams here fed the salt Sea of N\\\\u00farnen. Sauron's slaves farmed this region to support his armies.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Inside the Ephel D\\\\u00faath ran a lower parallel ridge, the Morgai, separated from the Ephel D\\\\u00faath by a narrow valley that Frodo and Sam followed northward after escaping from Cirith Ungol. Water trickled into this vale from the Ephel D\\\\u00faath, and the text describes it as a \\\\\\"dying land not yet dead\\\\\\". The vegetation included \\\\\\"low scrubby trees\\\\\\", \\\\\\"coarse grey grass-tussocks\\\\\\", \\\\\\"withered mosses\\\\\\", \\\\\\"great writhing, tangled brambles\\\\\\", and thickets of briars with long, stabbing thorns. The fauna included maggots, midges, and flies marked with \\\\\\"a red eye-shaped blotch\\\\\\".</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Adjacent to Mordor were, to the west, the narrow land of Ithilien (a province of Gondor); to the northwest the Dead Marshes; to the northeast Rh\\\\u00fbn; to the southeast Khand; and to the south Harad.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In The Atlas of Middle-earth, Karen Wynn Fonstad assumed that the lands of Mordor, Khand, and Rh\\\\u00fbn lay where the inland Sea of Helcar had been, and that the Sea of Rh\\\\u00fbn and Sea of N\\\\u00farnen were its remnants. This assumption stemmed from a First Age world-map drawn by Tolkien in the Ambarkanta, where the Inland Sea of Helcar occupied a large area of Middle-earth between the Ered Luin and Orocarni, with the western end being close to the head of the Great Gulf (later the Mouths of Anduin).[2] The atlas was however published before The hostss of Middle-earth, in which the Sea of Rh\\\\u00fbn and Mordor exist already in the First Age.</p>\\"}]", "path": "0001000100030001", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T20:23:50.810Z", "image": 5, "title": "Mordor", "show_in_menus": false, "locked": false, "expire_at": null, "seo_title": "", "first_published_at": "2016-10-24T15:19:13.969Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "depth": 4, "owner": 1, "slug": "mordor", "search_description": ""}	\N	8	1
