153	f	2017-05-07 02:30:00.572+00	{"numchild": 0, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "expired": false, "go_live_at": null, "first_published_at": "2017-01-09T10:57:05.960Z", "pk": 12, "expire_at": null, "path": "0001000100030002", "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/minas-tirith/", "image": 41, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Minas Tirith</b>\\\\u00a0(<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English\\\\\\">/\\\\u02c8m\\\\u026an\\\\u0259s\\\\u00a0\\\\u02c8t\\\\u026ar\\\\u026a\\\\u03b8/</a>;\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\\\\\">Sindarin</a>:\\\\u00a0/\\\\u02c8minas \\\\u02c8tiri\\\\u03b8/), originally named\\\\u00a0<b>Minas Anor</b>, is a fictional city and castle in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>\\\\u00a0writings. It became the heavily fortified\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_city\\\\\\">capital</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondor</a>\\\\u00a0in the second half of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">Third Age</a>. It was originally built to guard the former capital,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Osgiliath\\\\\\">Osgiliath</a>, from attack from the west, but became the capital when Osgiliath fell into ruin following the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_wars_and_battles#Kin-strife\\\\\\">Kin-strife</a>\\\\u00a0and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor#Decline\\\\\\">Great Plague</a>. It is often referred to as the\\\\u00a0<b>White City</b>\\\\u00a0(though that name is not in the book) and the\\\\u00a0<b>City of the Kings</b>. The\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)#hosts\\\\\\">Rohirrim</a>sometimes translated this into\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohirric\\\\\\">their own language</a>\\\\u00a0as \\\\\\"the\\\\u00a0<b>Mundburg</b>\\\\\\". In the climax of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>\\\\u00a0the city comes under a very large and determined attack by the allied forces of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>.<br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"size\\": \\"h2\\", \\"header_text\\": \\"Description\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The name\\\\u00a0<i>Minas Tirith</i>\\\\u00a0means \\\\\\"The Tower of Guard\\\\\\" or \\\\\\"The Tower of Watch\\\\\\" in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elvish</a>\\\\u00a0language\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\\\\\">Sindarin</a>.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith#cite_note-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0It was originally named\\\\u00a0<i>Minas Anor</i>, \\\\\\"The Tower of the Setting Sun\\\\\\", in connection with\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Morgul\\\\\\">Minas Ithil</a></i>, \\\\\\"The Tower of the Rising Moon\\\\\\". Minas Ithil was later conquered by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>\\\\u00a0and was renamed\\\\u00a0<i>Minas Morgul</i>, \\\\\\"The Tower of Black Sorcery\\\\\\".</p><p>The city of Minas Tirith covered an entire hill, the Hill of Guard, and was built on seven levels, culminating in the Citadel at the summit. Each level was about 100\\\\u00a0ft (30\\\\u00a0m) higher than the one below it, and each surrounded by a white wall, with the exception of the wall of the First Circle (the lowest level), which was black. The outer face of this outer wall, the lowest, was made of black stone, the same material used in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthanc\\\\\\">Orthanc</a>; it was vulnerable only to earthquakes capable of rending the ground where it stood.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[2]</a></sup></p><p>Each wall held a gate, and each gate faced a different direction from the one in the next lower wall. The city's main street snaked up the hill and through each of the gates.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"caption\\": \\"White Tree of Gondor in Minas Tirith\\", \\"image\\": 17, \\"style\\": \\"full\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"size\\": \\"h2\\", \\"header_text\\": \\"Great Gate\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Great Gate was the main gate on the first level of the City of Minas Tirith. It was in the City Wall \\\\u2014 or Othram \\\\u2014 facing eastward across the Pelennor Fields toward the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anduin\\\\\\">Anduin</a>.</p><p>In front of the Great Gate there was a large paved area called the Gateway. The main roads to Minas Tirith met here: the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#North-way\\\\\\">North-way</a>\\\\u00a0that became the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#Great_West_Road\\\\\\">Great West Road</a>\\\\u00a0to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>; the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#South_Road\\\\\\">South Road</a>\\\\u00a0to the southern provinces of Gondor; and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#Causeway_.28Osgiliath.29\\\\\\">road to Osgiliath</a>.</p><p>The Great Gate was very strong, constructed of iron and steel and guarded by stone towers and bastions. The iron doors of the Gate rolled back to open. Passwords were required to enter the Great Gate and each of the six other gates of Minas Tirith. The Great Gate was breached during the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">War of the Ring</a>.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>'s forces under the command of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witch-king_of_Angmar\\\\\\">Witch-king of Angmar</a>\\\\u00a0besieged the City on 13th 'March'. Before dawn on 15th 'March', the battering ram\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grond_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Grond</a>\\\\u00a0smashed into the Great Gate three times while the Witch-king spoke words of power. \\\\\\"As if stricken by some blasting spell it burst asunder: there was a flash of searing lightning, and the doors tumbled in riven fragments to the ground.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith#cite_note-3\\\\\\">[3]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0The Witch-king rode through the Gate where\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0awaited him, but then the Rohirrim arrived and the Witch-king went to fight them in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_the_Pelennor_Fields\\\\\\">Battle of the Pelennor Fields</a>\\\\u00a0where he was slain.</p><p>A temporary barricade was erected in place of the Great Gate. After the War, on 1st 'May',\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\\\\\">Aragorn</a>\\\\u00a0received the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crown_of_Gondor\\\\\\">Crown of Gondor</a>\\\\u00a0in front of the gate and then entered the City.</p><p>The Great Gate was rebuilt of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mithril\\\\\\">mithril</a></i>\\\\u00a0(the hardest of all metals in Tolkien's writing) and steel by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gimli_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Gimli</a>\\\\u00a0and Dwarves of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erebor\\\\\\">Erebor</a>\\\\u00a0from the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lonely_Mountain\\\\\\">Lonely Mountain</a>\\\\u00a0who had settled in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glittering_Caves\\\\\\">Glittering Caves</a>.</p>\\"}]", "locked": false, "depth": 4, "content_type": 6, "show_in_menus": false, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-05-06T04:32:14.373Z", "slug": "minas-tirith", "title": "Inle", "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "owner": 1, "live": true}	\N	12	1
