173	f	2017-05-17 03:54:31.986+00	{"live": true, "title": "Kauai", "go_live_at": null, "image": 35, "duration": "00:00:00", "slug": "resilience", "locked": false, "path": "0001000100020003", "expire_at": null, "expired": false, "depth": 4, "owner": 1, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Get picked up at your location on Kauai for a private 4 hour sightseeing tour of Waimea Canyon, Spouting Horn, and perhaps a couple of other beautiful places that are available on the Garden Isle.</p>\\"}]", "show_in_menus": false, "seo_title": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:40:13.912Z", "numchild": 0, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-05-11T03:42:00.263Z", "url_path": "/homepage/experience-index/resilience/", "pk": 20, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "content_type": 14, "place": 18, "host": 31, "search_description": ""}	\N	20	1
297	f	2018-01-26 04:32:43.68719+00	{"path": "0001000100030001", "go_live_at": null, "content_type": 6, "depth": 4, "show_in_menus": false, "image": 47, "numchild": 0, "first_published_at": "2016-10-24T15:19:13.969Z", "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "live": true, "slug": "mandalay", "expired": false, "title": "Mandalay", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Mandalay is the second largest city in Burma (after Yangon), and a former capital of Myanmar. The city is the economic and religious hub of upper Myanmar and is centred around the Royal Palace.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"style\\": \\"contain\\", \\"image\\": 73, \\"caption\\": \\"Palace of Mandalay\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>It has wide lanes filled with bicycles and motorcycles and is known for its cultural diversity. Half of Burma's monks reside in Mandalay and the surrounding areas.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Mandalay, the very name evokes the splendours of the Burma of old. But, most people will be surprised to learn that Mandalay is not an old city, not even a medieval one, but rather a new city that was created by King Mingdon Min of Burma in 1857 as the new capital of the kingdom of Ava. Only two Burmese kings ruled from there, King Mingdon and King Thibaw, before the British conquest of Upper Burma in 1885. It was a city of splendour between 1858 and 1885 but most of the magnificence is gone, destroyed by the fire that consumed wooden structures and by intensive bombing by the Axis powers during the Second World War. The city, neatly planned with its lettered roads and numbered streets, is a British creation. The once magnificent Royal Palace and the great Atumashi (incomparable) pagoda, King Mingdon Min's finest creations, are modern reconstructions. Today, Mandalay lies at the end of the Lashio Road and it is, by Burmese standards, relatively prosperous as a centre for trade with China and as a centre for the growing trade with India. Despite the capital having been moved to Naypyidaw, Mandalay remains by far the main commercial centre of Upper Myanmar.<br/></p>\\"}]", "expire_at": null, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-06-13T03:16:44.070Z", "owner": 1, "pk": 8, "url_path": "/homepage/places/mandalay/", "locked": false}	\N	8	1
147	f	2017-05-06 04:18:55.577+00	{"has_unpublished_changes": false, "show_in_menus": false, "title": "Mawlamyine", "depth": 4, "owner": 1, "live": true, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/fangorn/", "path": "0001000100030006", "slug": "fangorn", "search_description": "", "expired": false, "expire_at": null, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-23T07:51:36.509Z", "body": "[{\\"value\\": \\"<p>Fangorn (Sindarin: [Fangaorne]; \\\\\\"Beardtree\\\\\\") in J.R.R. Tolkien's Legendarium, was a forest located in the fictional world of Middle-earth and was the home of the tree shepherds, the Ents. It was named after the oldest Ent, Treebeard or Treebeard after it. Tolkien did, however, state that there was confusion about the two.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>The Forest of Fangorn provided an important role in The Lord of the Rings novel as did Mirkwood and Lothl\\\\u00f3rien in the Third Age, a time when Sauron challenged Middle-earth to battle and domination. The forest provided the means by where adventure expanded with the breaking up of the Fellowship. Merry Brandybuck and Peregrin Took were the first to discover the Ents were alive but were dwindling in numbers due to the loss of the Entwives. They were lost because of the events of the Last Alliance of Elves and Men. The forest was again severely damaged during the War of the Ring by the forces of Saruman who lived close by in the fortress of Isengard.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Etymology\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>\\\\\\"Fangorn\\\\\\" was the original name for the Ent Treebeard, who was the eldest of his species and who looked after vast areas of his home and the surrounding land which was named Fangorn Forest. Additionally, Fangorn translated in the fictional language of Sindarin from \\\\\\"fanga\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"beard\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"orne\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"tree\\\\\\". Sindarin was a language Tolkien created and described the Elves of Middle-Earth to possess; who \\\\\\"awoke\\\\\\" the Ents and taught them language. In other parts of Middle-earth Fangorn Forest was called the \\\\\\"Entwood\\\\\\" by the Rohirrim.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"attribute_group\\": \\"\\", \\"text\\": \\"Some of us are still true Ents, and lively enough in our fashion, but many are growing sleepy, going tree-ish, as you might say. Most of the trees are just trees, of course; but many are half awake. Some are quite wide awake, and a few are, well, ah, well getting Entish. That is going on all the time.\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Treebeard\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Fangorn Forest apparently had several names as told by Treebeard who referred to the forest by various Quenya names in Lord of the Rings, some of which were Ambar\\\\u00f3na, Tauremornal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb, Tauremorna and Aldal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb. \\\\\\"Ambar\\\\u00f3na\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"uprising, sunrise, orient\\\\\\" from \\\\\\"amba\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"upwards\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"r\\\\u00f3na\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"east\\\\\\". \\\\\\"Aldal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"tree twilight\\\\\\" from \\\\\\"alda\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"tree\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"l\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"dusk, twilight\\\\\\".[1] \\\\\\"Tauremorna\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"gloomy forest\\\\\\" from \\\\\\"taur\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"forest\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"morna\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"gloomy, somber\\\\\\".[1] \\\\\\"Tauremornal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"gloomy twilight forest\\\\\\".</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Geography\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>The Forest of Fangorn was located at the south-eastern end of the Misty Mountains near the Gap of Rohan. The mountains formed the western border of Fangorn. At the end of the mountain range stood the stronghold of Isengard near the southwestern corner of the forest and this was where Saruman lived.[citation needed] To the east and south of Fangorn was the land of Rohan, and Lothl\\\\u00f3rien lay to the north and slightly east. Fangorn Forest stretched for many miles and held many paths.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Tolkien stated that two significant rivers ran through the forest. To the north the Limlight flowed from the woods and then formed the northern border of Rohan. The river then merged into the larger Anduin. In the south, the Entwash spread deep into the forest arriving from Methedras, a mountainous region located near the Misty Mountains. The river then flowed from Fangorn and was directed through Rohan to the Anduin River. The valley of Derndingle was located to the south-west. There was a path where the Entwash passed into a region called Wellinghall and this was where the Entwash passed the home of Treebeard, the shepherd of the forest.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Fangorn Forest was said to be humid, and trunks and branches grew thick where very little light penetrated the forest. Similarly, Fangorn was said to be a dangerous and evil place like Mirkwood (where huge spiders roamed the forest and other evil creatures lay), but this was not the case following the events of The Lord of the Rings. The forest was home to many different kinds of trees. Huorns also lived in the forest, similar to Ents but more discreet. Most lived deep in the Forest of Fangorn. The Ents and Huorns drank from the river Entwash, and from it the Ents brewed their legendary drink, the Ent-draughts.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}]", "locked": false, "seo_title": "", "image": 13, "numchild": 0, "pk": 17, "content_type": 6, "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:05:17.882Z", "go_live_at": null}	\N	17	1
298	f	2018-01-26 04:33:12.082017+00	{"path": "0001000100030001", "go_live_at": null, "content_type": 6, "depth": 4, "show_in_menus": false, "image": 47, "numchild": 0, "first_published_at": "2016-10-24T15:19:13.969Z", "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "live": true, "slug": "mandalay", "expired": false, "title": "Mandalay", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Mandalay is the second largest city in Burma (after Yangon), and a former capital of Myanmar. The city is the economic and religious hub of upper Myanmar and is centred around the Royal Palace.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"style\\": \\"half\\", \\"image\\": 73, \\"caption\\": \\"Palace of Mandalay\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>It has wide lanes filled with bicycles and motorcycles and is known for its cultural diversity. Half of Burma's monks reside in Mandalay and the surrounding areas.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Mandalay, the very name evokes the splendours of the Burma of old. But, most people will be surprised to learn that Mandalay is not an old city, not even a medieval one, but rather a new city that was created by King Mingdon Min of Burma in 1857 as the new capital of the kingdom of Ava. Only two Burmese kings ruled from there, King Mingdon and King Thibaw, before the British conquest of Upper Burma in 1885. It was a city of splendour between 1858 and 1885 but most of the magnificence is gone, destroyed by the fire that consumed wooden structures and by intensive bombing by the Axis powers during the Second World War. The city, neatly planned with its lettered roads and numbered streets, is a British creation. The once magnificent Royal Palace and the great Atumashi (incomparable) pagoda, King Mingdon Min's finest creations, are modern reconstructions. Today, Mandalay lies at the end of the Lashio Road and it is, by Burmese standards, relatively prosperous as a centre for trade with China and as a centre for the growing trade with India. Despite the capital having been moved to Naypyidaw, Mandalay remains by far the main commercial centre of Upper Myanmar.<br/></p>\\"}]", "expire_at": null, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "latest_revision_created_at": "2018-01-26T04:32:43.687Z", "owner": 1, "pk": 8, "url_path": "/homepage/places/mandalay/", "locked": false}	\N	8	1
145	f	2017-05-06 04:17:09.239+00	{"has_unpublished_changes": false, "show_in_menus": false, "title": "Taunggyi", "depth": 4, "owner": 1, "live": true, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/helms-deep/", "path": "0001000100030004", "slug": "helms-deep", "search_description": "", "expired": false, "expire_at": null, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-23T07:52:06.016Z", "body": "[{\\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0J. R. R. Tolkien's\\\\u00a0Middle-earth\\\\u00a0high fantasy\\\\u00a0writings,\\\\u00a0<b>Helm's Deep</b>\\\\u00a0was a large valley in the north-western\\\\u00a0Ered Nimrais\\\\u00a0(White Mountains).</p><p>The valley was described as being blocked over its entire width by the natural series of hills called\\\\u00a0<b>Helm's Dike</b>\\\\u00a0and behind that lay the fortress of Aglarond or the\\\\u00a0<b>Hornburg</b>, at the entrance to the Glittering Caves.</p><p>In the Appendices of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, the history of the valley states that it was home to a small\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondorian</a>\\\\u00a0regiment, but after the place which was called\\\\u00a0Calenardhon\\\\u00a0became\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>, it became an encampment of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)#hosts\\\\\\">Rohirrim</a>, where the guards of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fords_of_Isen\\\\\\">Fords of Isen</a>\\\\u00a0lived.</p><p>It also states that during the war with the\\\\u00a0Dunlendings\\\\u00a0under\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wulf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Wulf</a>, the Rohirrim under King\\\\u00a0Helm Hammerhand\\\\u00a0and many of his hosts sought refuge in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keep\\\\\\">keep</a>, where they held out during the winter of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a02758\\\\u20132759.</p><p>The castle itself was described as having a long causeway which wound up to the great gate of the fortress itself. Inside the keep there were stables and an armoury, as well as a great hall in the rear which was dug out of the mountainside. There also was a great tower (the Hornburg) the top of which consisted of the great horn of\\\\u00a0Helm Hammerhand. The Deep, which was described as standing next to the fortress, was barred by the long Deeping Wall, which was described as consisting of solid rock except for a small culvert which allowed water from the Deeping Stream to enter; this rendered a fresh supply in sieges of great length. The Deeping Wall itself is described as standing 20 feet tall; and also being wide enough for four men to stand side by side. Access to the fortress from within the Deep was made possible by a long stair which led to the Hornburg's rear gate.</p><p>In\\\\u00a0<i>The Two Towers</i>, the fortress guarding Helm's Deep becomes the refuge of the main army of the Rohirrim, under King\\\\u00a0Th\\\\u00e9oden\\\\u00a0during the\\\\u00a0War of the Ring. Th\\\\u00e9oden said that \\\\\\"the Hornburg has never fallen to assault\\\\\\" giving an impression of invulnerability. This was tested during the\\\\u00a0Battle of the Hornburg, as a massive army of\\\\u00a0Uruk-hai\\\\u00a0sent by\\\\u00a0Saruman\\\\u00a0almost overwhelmed the defences of the Rohirrim. Saruman's\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0used an explosive blast of fire within the culvert which, when detonated, breached the long Deeping Wall. The origin of this explosion is unclear and Tolkien denotes it as \\\\\\"Saruman's devilry\\\\\\". The Rohirrim defenders held out long enough in the fortress until dawn, giving Gandalf time to gather and lead a counter-attack, while Th\\\\u00e9oden led a cavalry charge that drove the Orcs from the fortress.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"image\\": 9, \\"caption\\": \\"Crest of Gondor, the original builders of the Helm\\", \\"style\\": \\"half\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"image\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Aglarond\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Aglarond and Angrenost (which later became Isengard) were the two fortresses built by Gondor to guard the approaches to the Fords of Isen. Like Angrenost to the north, it was initially well guarded, but as the population of Calenardhon (the later Rohan) dwindled it was not maintained and, losing importance, was left to a hereditary small guard who intermarried with Dunlendings.</p><p><br/></p><p>When Cirion, Steward of Gondor, gave Calenardhon to the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od, Aglarond was transferred into the care of the Rohirrim, who named it S\\\\u00fathburg (southern burg in their language). The Gondorian guard was merged with that of Angrenost to the north, which remained in the keep of Gondor. Guard duty of the Fords was initially shared between Gondor and Rohan, but later maintained only by the Rohirrim.</p><p><br/></p><p>During the reign of Helm Hammerhand, Rohan was attacked by Dunlendings from across the river Isen. Edoras was taken, and Helm and many of his hosts retreated to S\\\\u00fathburg. Because Helm always blew a great horn before riding out to fight the beleaguering Dunlendings, the keep was renamed Hornburg. During the War of the Ring, the Hornburg was the refuge of the Rohirrim as they defended Helm's Deep.</p><p><br/></p><p>After the war, Gimli the Dwarf, who fought in that battle, established a colony of Durin's folk there. Aglarond lay in front of a huge and very beautiful cave system, which proved irresistible to him. Gimli became known as 'the Lord of the Glittering Caves', although this new realm was presumably under the overlordship of Thorin Stonehelm, his kinsman and heir of the lordship of all Durin's Folk. The dwarves of Aglarond restored the Hornburg following the War of the Ring, and it became a fortress they shared with the Rohirrim.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}]", "locked": false, "seo_title": "", "image": 10, "numchild": 0, "pk": 15, "content_type": 6, "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T19:51:43.011Z", "go_live_at": null}	\N	15	1
149	f	2017-05-06 04:21:00.19+00	{"has_unpublished_changes": false, "show_in_menus": false, "title": "Myitkyina", "depth": 4, "owner": 1, "live": true, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/minas-tirith/", "path": "0001000100030002", "slug": "minas-tirith", "search_description": "", "expired": false, "expire_at": null, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-12T20:27:03.937Z", "body": "[{\\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Minas Tirith</b>\\\\u00a0(<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English\\\\\\">/\\\\u02c8m\\\\u026an\\\\u0259s\\\\u00a0\\\\u02c8t\\\\u026ar\\\\u026a\\\\u03b8/</a>;\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\\\\\">Sindarin</a>:\\\\u00a0/\\\\u02c8minas \\\\u02c8tiri\\\\u03b8/), originally named\\\\u00a0<b>Minas Anor</b>, is a fictional city and castle in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>\\\\u00a0writings. It became the heavily fortified\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_city\\\\\\">capital</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondor</a>\\\\u00a0in the second half of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">Third Age</a>. It was originally built to guard the former capital,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Osgiliath\\\\\\">Osgiliath</a>, from attack from the west, but became the capital when Osgiliath fell into ruin following the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_wars_and_battles#Kin-strife\\\\\\">Kin-strife</a>\\\\u00a0and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor#Decline\\\\\\">Great Plague</a>. It is often referred to as the\\\\u00a0<b>White City</b>\\\\u00a0(though that name is not in the book) and the\\\\u00a0<b>City of the Kings</b>. The\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)#hosts\\\\\\">Rohirrim</a>sometimes translated this into\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohirric\\\\\\">their own language</a>\\\\u00a0as \\\\\\"the\\\\u00a0<b>Mundburg</b>\\\\\\". In the climax of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>\\\\u00a0the city comes under a very large and determined attack by the allied forces of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>.<br/></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Description\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>The name\\\\u00a0<i>Minas Tirith</i>\\\\u00a0means \\\\\\"The Tower of Guard\\\\\\" or \\\\\\"The Tower of Watch\\\\\\" in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elvish</a>\\\\u00a0language\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\\\\\">Sindarin</a>.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith#cite_note-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0It was originally named\\\\u00a0<i>Minas Anor</i>, \\\\\\"The Tower of the Setting Sun\\\\\\", in connection with\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Morgul\\\\\\">Minas Ithil</a></i>, \\\\\\"The Tower of the Rising Moon\\\\\\". Minas Ithil was later conquered by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>\\\\u00a0and was renamed\\\\u00a0<i>Minas Morgul</i>, \\\\\\"The Tower of Black Sorcery\\\\\\".</p><p>The city of Minas Tirith covered an entire hill, the Hill of Guard, and was built on seven levels, culminating in the Citadel at the summit. Each level was about 100\\\\u00a0ft (30\\\\u00a0m) higher than the one below it, and each surrounded by a white wall, with the exception of the wall of the First Circle (the lowest level), which was black. The outer face of this outer wall, the lowest, was made of black stone, the same material used in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthanc\\\\\\">Orthanc</a>; it was vulnerable only to earthquakes capable of rending the ground where it stood.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith#cite_note-2\\\\\\">[2]</a></sup></p><p>Each wall held a gate, and each gate faced a different direction from the one in the next lower wall. The city's main street snaked up the hill and through each of the gates.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"image\\": 17, \\"caption\\": \\"White Tree of Gondor in Minas Tirith\\", \\"style\\": \\"full\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"image\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Great Gate\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>The Great Gate was the main gate on the first level of the City of Minas Tirith. It was in the City Wall \\\\u2014 or Othram \\\\u2014 facing eastward across the Pelennor Fields toward the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anduin\\\\\\">Anduin</a>.</p><p>In front of the Great Gate there was a large paved area called the Gateway. The main roads to Minas Tirith met here: the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#North-way\\\\\\">North-way</a>\\\\u00a0that became the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#Great_West_Road\\\\\\">Great West Road</a>\\\\u00a0to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>; the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#South_Road\\\\\\">South Road</a>\\\\u00a0to the southern provinces of Gondor; and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#Causeway_.28Osgiliath.29\\\\\\">road to Osgiliath</a>.</p><p>The Great Gate was very strong, constructed of iron and steel and guarded by stone towers and bastions. The iron doors of the Gate rolled back to open. Passwords were required to enter the Great Gate and each of the six other gates of Minas Tirith. The Great Gate was breached during the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">War of the Ring</a>.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>'s forces under the command of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witch-king_of_Angmar\\\\\\">Witch-king of Angmar</a>\\\\u00a0besieged the City on 13th 'March'. Before dawn on 15th 'March', the battering ram\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grond_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Grond</a>\\\\u00a0smashed into the Great Gate three times while the Witch-king spoke words of power. \\\\\\"As if stricken by some blasting spell it burst asunder: there was a flash of searing lightning, and the doors tumbled in riven fragments to the ground.\\\\\\"<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith#cite_note-3\\\\\\">[3]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0The Witch-king rode through the Gate where\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0awaited him, but then the Rohirrim arrived and the Witch-king went to fight them in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_the_Pelennor_Fields\\\\\\">Battle of the Pelennor Fields</a>\\\\u00a0where he was slain.</p><p>A temporary barricade was erected in place of the Great Gate. After the War, on 1st 'May',\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\\\\\">Aragorn</a>\\\\u00a0received the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crown_of_Gondor\\\\\\">Crown of Gondor</a>\\\\u00a0in front of the gate and then entered the City.</p><p>The Great Gate was rebuilt of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mithril\\\\\\">mithril</a></i>\\\\u00a0(the hardest of all metals in Tolkien's writing) and steel by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gimli_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Gimli</a>\\\\u00a0and Dwarves of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erebor\\\\\\">Erebor</a>\\\\u00a0from the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lonely_Mountain\\\\\\">Lonely Mountain</a>\\\\u00a0who had settled in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glittering_Caves\\\\\\">Glittering Caves</a>.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}]", "locked": false, "seo_title": "", "image": 4, "numchild": 0, "pk": 12, "content_type": 6, "first_published_at": "2017-01-09T10:57:05.960Z", "go_live_at": null}	\N	12	1
148	f	2017-05-06 04:20:06.801+00	{"has_unpublished_changes": false, "show_in_menus": false, "title": "Ngwesaung", "depth": 4, "owner": 1, "live": true, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/edoras/", "path": "0001000100030005", "slug": "edoras", "search_description": "", "expired": false, "expire_at": null, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-23T07:41:42.028Z", "body": "[{\\"value\\": {\\"image\\": 11, \\"caption\\": \\"The Uffington White Horse, whence the banner and shield of the House of Eorl \\\\u2013 a \\\\\\"white horse upon green\\\\\\" \\\\u2013 is derived.\\", \\"style\\": \\"half\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"image\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>The capital of Rohan is the hill fort of Edoras which is located on a hill in a valley of the White Mountains. Meduseld, the Golden Hall of the King of Rohan, is located there. \\\\\\"Edoras\\\\\\" is Old English for \\\\\\"enclosures\\\\\\",[4] which Tolkien held to be a translation of an unknown Rohirric name of the same meaning. The city of Edoras was built by Rohan's second King, Brego son of Eorl the Young. Before Edoras was completed, Rohan's capital was at Aldburg in the Folde. Meduseld is described as having a golden thatch. Edoras is built at the end of the valley of Harrowdale, which lies under the great mountain Starkhorn. The river Snowbourn flows past the city on its way east towards the Entwash. The city is protected only by a high wall of timber, and a one-way road allows access to the city. Just before the gates, two rows of mounds line the road, which are the graves of the former Kings of Rohan. \\\\\\"Meduseld\\\\\\", a modernised form of the Old English Maeduselde,[5] is similarly meant to be a translation of an unknown Rohirric name meaning \\\\\\"mead hall\\\\\\". Meduseld is a large hall with roof that appears golden from far off. The walls are richly decorated with tapestries depicting the history and legends of the Rohirrim, and it serves as a house for the King and his kin, a meeting hall for the King and his advisors, and a gathering hall.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Edoras is Rohan's only real city. It is at Meduseld that Aragorn, Gimli, Legolas, and Gandalf meet with King Th\\\\u00e9oden in the account of the early stages of the War of the Ring.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Another settlement is Aldburg, capital of the Eastfold and original settlement of Eorl the Young. A third settlement is Snowbourne, named after the river of the same name which runs nearby. It is similar in appearance to the hill-fort of Edoras. Dunharrow is a refuge in the White Mountains. Helm's Deep is a valley in the White Mountains in which the Hornburg, a major fortress of Rohan, is located.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Internal history\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>In the thirteenth century of the Third Age (T.A.), the Kings of Gondor made close alliances with the Northmen of Rhovanion, a hosts said in The Lord of the Rings to be akin to the Three Houses of Men (later the D\\\\u00fanedain) from the First Age.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>In the twenty-first century, a remnant tribe of such Northmen calling itself the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od moved from the valleys of Anduin to the north west of Mirkwood, clearing out what remained of the recently defeated witch kingdom of Angmar, east of the Misty Mountains. While there, some dispute arose between them and the Dwarves over the treasure-hoard of Scatha the dragon.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Later, in 2509, Cirion the Steward of Gondor sent summons to the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od for aid in throwing off a combined invasion of Men from the north east of Middle-earth, and Orcs from Mordor.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Eorl the Young, king of the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od, answered the summons, and arrived unexpected at a decisive battle at the Field of Celebrant, routing the orc army, and then destroying it as it fled.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>As a reward, Eorl was given the plains of Calenardhon, and he moved his kingdom there. This land had earlier been part of Gondor proper, but had been devastated by the plague of 1636, and the survivors to a large extent slain in the invasion mentioned above.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"attribute_group\\": \\"Reciting a forgotten poem on Eorl the Young\\", \\"text\\": \\"Where now the horse and the rider? Where is the horn that was blowing?\\\\r\\\\nWhere is the helm and the hauberk, and the bright hair flowing?\\\\r\\\\nWhere is the hand on the harp-string, and the red fire glowing?\\\\r\\\\nWhere is the spring and the harvest and the tall corn growing?\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Aragorn\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<br/><p>The first line of kings lasted for 249 years, until the ninth king Helm Hammerhand died. His sons had been killed earlier, and his nephew Fr\\\\u00e9al\\\\u00e1f Hildeson began the second line of kings, which lasted until the end of the Third Age.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>In 2758, Rohan was invaded by Dunlendings under Wulf, son of Freca, of mixed Dunland and Rohan blood. The King, Helm Hammerhand, took refuge in the Hornburg until aid from Gondor and Dunharrow (a refuge of the Rohirrim) arrived a year later and defeated the invaders.<br/></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/SLxeNktacYs\\", \\"type\\": \\"embed\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>It was soon after this that Saruman arrived and took over Isengard, and was welcomed as a strong ally, since it would take Rohan close to 200 years to recover its strength after the invasion.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>In 3014, Saruman began using his influence to weaken the King, Th\\\\u00e9oden, as part of a campaign to invade or take over the kingdom. In 3019, he launched a great invasion of Rohan, with victory in the two first battles (at the Fords of Isen; Th\\\\u00e9oden's son, Th\\\\u00e9odred was killed during these attacks) and defeat at the Battle of the Hornburg, where the Huorns came to the aid of the Rohirrim.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>On the heels of this victory, Th\\\\u00e9oden rode with an army to Minas Tirith and helped break its siege in the Battle of the Pelennor Fields, where he was slain. \\\\u00c9omer, the nephew of King Th\\\\u00e9oden, then took up the reign, beginning the third line. Also in this battle, \\\\u00c9owyn, niece of King Th\\\\u00e9oden and sister of \\\\u00c9omer, slew the Lord of the Nazg\\\\u00fbl. \\\\u00c9omer rode with the armies of Gondor to the Black Gate of Mordor and took part in the Battle of the Morannon against the forces of Sauron, who were defeated when the Ruling Ring was destroyed.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>The rule of the Stewards of Gondor was then over. King \\\\u00c9omer and the new king of Gondor, Elessar, renewed their oath of alliance, and reaffirmed Cirion's grant of Calenardhon to the Rohirrim. At this time, \\\\u00c9owyn married Faramir, Prince of Ithilien and Steward of Gondor, thus joining the lines of Gondor and Rohan.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>In the Fourth Age, Rohan remained in peaceful coexistence with the Reunited Kingdom. A Dwarven community developed in the caves of Helm's Deep, which became prosperous from its mining of precious materials.<br/></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}]", "locked": false, "seo_title": "", "image": 12, "numchild": 0, "pk": 16, "content_type": 6, "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:00:16.547Z", "go_live_at": null}	\N	16	1
288	f	2018-01-26 04:05:02.244339+00	{"path": "0001000100030002", "go_live_at": null, "content_type": 6, "depth": 4, "show_in_menus": false, "image": 41, "numchild": 0, "first_published_at": "2017-01-09T10:57:05.960Z", "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "live": true, "slug": "inle", "expired": false, "title": "Inle", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Inle Lake is a shallow lake in the middle of Myanmar, south-east of Mandalay. The lake is 22km long, and is densely inhabited by many different tribes.<br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"style\\": \\"contain\\", \\"image\\": 69, \\"caption\\": \\"Inle Paungdaw Oo Pagoda\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The easiest way to get into Inle Lake (and the most comfortable) is by domestic flight. The closest airport is in Heho, which is a taxi-ride (about 1 hour) away from the lake itself (walking down the road from the airport, towards the highway, should see quoted fares drop, if not, try your luck hailing a taxi or passing pickup on the highway itself). Taking a taxi from the airport is expensive, as of January 2017 there is a fixed, non-bargainable price of 25,000 Kyats to go to Nyuang Shwe. If you baulk at the high fare, the taxi drivers will attempt to gather other travelers to share the taxi and split the fare, so there is a good chance you will end up paying a lot less by sharing your taxi. By comparison a taxi from Yangon airport to the city centre (45 min.) is just 8000 Kyats or 7 USD. A possible way to save money is to book a taxi in advance with your guesthouse, but seems like now they all charge the same 25,000 kyat fixed price. 15,000kyat is a good price to/from the airport that may be more difficult to reserve on your way in, but no issue to book for your return trip to Heho from any agency in town. When returning, you can often save by booking a shared taxi through your hotel or one of the many travel agents around. Check with them the day before you fly out.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Prices for flights are around US$110 from Yangon and US$75 from Mandalay, but unlike bus companies the government is heavily involved in the domestic air market, a good chunk of your money will be going into their hands.</p>\\"}]", "expire_at": null, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "latest_revision_created_at": "2018-01-26T04:04:25.266Z", "owner": 1, "pk": 12, "url_path": "/homepage/places/inle/", "locked": false}	\N	12	1
