180	f	2017-06-13 03:17:47.399+00	{"url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/rivendell/", "image": 45, "show_in_menus": false, "owner": 1, "locked": false, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "numchild": 0, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-05-07T02:33:11.971Z", "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "content_type": 6, "expire_at": null, "title": "Naypyidaw", "live": true, "search_description": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:16:17.742Z", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Rivendell is an Elven realm in Middle-earth, a fictional world created by J. R. R. Tolkien. It is an important place in Tolkien's legendarium, and is featured in The Hobbit, The Lord of the Rings, The Silmarillion, and Unfinished Tales. It was established and ruled by Elrond Half-elven in the Second Age of Middle-earth (four or five thousand years before the events of The Lord of the Rings), and was protected by the powers of its lord and his elven ring Vilya.</p><p>Elrond lived in Rivendell with his family \\\\u2014 his wife Celebr\\\\u00edan (until she departed for Valinor), their sons Elladan and Elrohir, and their daughter Arwen \\\\u2014 as well as a sizeable number of other Elves, both Noldor and Sindar. In addition to the family of Elrond, notable Elves who lived in Rivendell included Glorfindel, Gildor, and Erestor. In some writings, featured in Unfinished Tales, Galadriel and Celeborn also lived in Rivendell for a time before they became rulers of Lothl\\\\u00f3rien.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"image\\": 26, \\"style\\": \\"half\\", \\"caption\\": \\"Gandalf doing awesome things\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/t9L8Er_oqAQ\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Etymology\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Testing\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><i>Rivendell</i>\\\\u00a0is a direct translation or\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calque\\\\\\">calque</a>\\\\u00a0into English of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\\\\\">Sindarin</a>\\\\u00a0name\\\\u00a0<b>Imladris</b>, both meaning \\\\\\"deep valley of the cleft\\\\\\". The name Rivendell is formed by two English elements: \\\\\\"riven\\\\\\" (split, cloven) and \\\\\\"dell\\\\\\" (valley), making the whole word purport \\\\\\"deeply cloven valley\\\\\\". Imladris was also rendered \\\\\\"<i>Karningul</i>\\\\\\" in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Westron\\\\\\">Westron</a>, the \\\\\\"Common Tongue\\\\\\" of Middle-Earth represented as English in the text of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings.</i>\\\\u00a0It is also referred to as\\\\u00a0<i>The Last Homely House,</i>\\\\u00a0alluding to the elves' old cities, in Beleriand and Aman, and the wilderness (Rhovanion) that lies east of the Misty Mountains.<br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Legacy\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\", \\"value\\": {\\"text\\": \\"Evil things do not come into this valley... We are sitting in a fortress. Outside it is getting dark.\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Gandalf\\", \\"attribute_group\\": \\"Fellowship of the Ring\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the period of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Counterculture\\\\\\">counterculture</a>\\\\u00a0in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_World\\\\\\">Western World</a>\\\\u00a0of the 1960s and 1970s, a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commune\\\\\\">commune</a>\\\\u00a0called\\\\u00a0<i>Maos Lyst</i>\\\\u00a0(<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mao_Zedong\\\\\\">Mao</a>'s Delight) was founded in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denmark\\\\\\">Denmark</a>\\\\u00a0in 1968, its inhabitants replacing their surnames with\\\\u00a0<i>Kl\\\\u00f8vedal</i>, Danish for Rivendell, inspired by Tolkien's Elven outpost.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell#cite_note-6\\\\\\">[6]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0Several of them later became well-known cultural personalities in the country.</p><p>The Canadian progressive rock band\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rush_(band)\\\\\\">Rush</a>\\\\u00a0memorializes Rivendell in the song \\\\\\"Rivendell\\\\\\" on their second studio album\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fly_by_Night_(album)\\\\\\">Fly By Night</a></i>. The song focuses on the tranquillity and seemingly endless time a weary traveller could find there.</p><p>The Austrian folk band Rivendell takes the material for their lyrics almost entirely from Tolkien's books.</p><p>A Californian manufacturer of bicycles,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell_Bicycle_Works\\\\\\">Rivendell Bicycle Works</a>, also uses the name, inspired by the book and a United States backpacking supply company founded in the 1970s called\\\\u00a0Rivendell Mountain Works. They take many of the names of their bicycle models from Tolkien.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell#cite_note-7\\\\\\">[7]</a></sup></p>\\"}]", "depth": 4, "go_live_at": null, "path": "0001000100030008", "pk": 19, "slug": "naypyidaw"}	\N	19	1
183	f	2017-06-13 03:19:38.828+00	{"url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/isengard/", "image": 42, "show_in_menus": false, "owner": 1, "locked": false, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "numchild": 0, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-05-07T02:30:44.790Z", "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "content_type": 6, "expire_at": null, "title": "Bagan", "live": true, "search_description": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T19:45:42.890Z", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"image\\": 7, \\"style\\": \\"half\\", \\"caption\\": \\"A shield displaying the White Hand of Isengard\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In J. R. R. Tolkien's fictional universe of Middle-earth, Isengard ([\\\\u02c8a\\\\u026a\\\\u02d0.z\\\\u025bn.\\\\u0261\\\\u0251rd]), a translation of the Sindarin Angrenost, was a large fortress. Both names mean \\\\\\"Iron fortress\\\\\\" (cf. German Eisen and Old English is\\\\u00e6rn = iron),[1] though Isengard has a second meaning of \\\\\\"West Guard\\\\\\".</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Armour and emblems\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Orcs of Isengard bore upon their shields a White Hand on a black field, and on their helmets an S-rune (&lt;) to signify Saruman. A carved and painted White Hand of stone was set on a black pillar outside the gates of Isengard.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Orthanc\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Orthanc is the black tower of Isengard. Its name means both \\\\\\"Mount Fang\\\\\\" in Sindarin, and \\\\\\"Cunning Mind\\\\\\" in Old English, the language Tolkien uses to \\\\\\"translate\\\\\\" Rohirric.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Orthanc was, according to J. R. R. Tolkien's legendarium, built during the end of the Second Age by men of Gondor out of four many-sided columns of rock joined together by an unknown process and then hardened. No known weapon could harm it. Although the Ents could split ordinary stone with ease, their assault on the tower only left a few scratches and chips on its surface. Orthanc rose up to more than 500 feet (150 meters) above the plain of Isengard, and ended in four sharp peaks. Its only entrance was at the top of a high stair, and above that was a small window and balcony.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Orthanc housed one of the palant\\\\u00edri of the South Kingdom, and was guarded by a special warden. In the days of the early Stewards the tower was locked and its keys taken to Minas Tirith. When Isengard fell to the Dunlendings in T.A. 2710 they were unable to enter the tower.</p>\\"}]", "depth": 4, "go_live_at": null, "path": "0001000100030003", "pk": 14, "slug": "bagan"}	\N	14	1
207	f	2017-06-21 04:01:16.612+00	{"latest_revision_created_at": "2017-06-21T04:00:29.617Z", "seo_title": "", "url_path": "/homepage/", "pk": 2, "live": true, "featured_page_2": 7, "first_published_at": "2016-10-24T15:15:47.830Z", "owner": 1, "featured_page_3": 5, "locked": false, "expired": false, "go_live_at": null, "depth": 2, "show_in_menus": false, "copyright_notice": "Copyright for all the Lord of the Rings stuff is copyright New Line Cinema and JRR Tolkien. Text is from Wikipedia", "slug": "homepage", "title": "Home", "path": "00010001", "strapline": "The Road goes ever on and on, out from the door where it began.", "featured_page_1": 4, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "numchild": 4, "organisation_name": "Doolay", "content_type": 5, "search_description": "", "expire_at": null}	\N	2	1
181	f	2017-06-13 03:18:25.036+00	{"url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/fangorn/", "image": 44, "show_in_menus": false, "owner": 1, "locked": false, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "numchild": 0, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-05-07T02:32:06.423Z", "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "content_type": 6, "expire_at": null, "title": "Mawlamyine", "live": true, "search_description": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:05:17.882Z", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Fangorn (Sindarin: [Fangaorne]; \\\\\\"Beardtree\\\\\\") in J.R.R. Tolkien's Legendarium, was a forest located in the fictional world of Middle-earth and was the home of the tree shepherds, the Ents. It was named after the oldest Ent, Treebeard or Treebeard after it. Tolkien did, however, state that there was confusion about the two.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Forest of Fangorn provided an important role in The Lord of the Rings novel as did Mirkwood and Lothl\\\\u00f3rien in the Third Age, a time when Sauron challenged Middle-earth to battle and domination. The forest provided the means by where adventure expanded with the breaking up of the Fellowship. Merry Brandybuck and Peregrin Took were the first to discover the Ents were alive but were dwindling in numbers due to the loss of the Entwives. They were lost because of the events of the Last Alliance of Elves and Men. The forest was again severely damaged during the War of the Ring by the forces of Saruman who lived close by in the fortress of Isengard.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Etymology\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>\\\\\\"Fangorn\\\\\\" was the original name for the Ent Treebeard, who was the eldest of his species and who looked after vast areas of his home and the surrounding land which was named Fangorn Forest. Additionally, Fangorn translated in the fictional language of Sindarin from \\\\\\"fanga\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"beard\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"orne\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"tree\\\\\\". Sindarin was a language Tolkien created and described the Elves of Middle-Earth to possess; who \\\\\\"awoke\\\\\\" the Ents and taught them language. In other parts of Middle-earth Fangorn Forest was called the \\\\\\"Entwood\\\\\\" by the Rohirrim.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\", \\"value\\": {\\"text\\": \\"Some of us are still true Ents, and lively enough in our fashion, but many are growing sleepy, going tree-ish, as you might say. Most of the trees are just trees, of course; but many are half awake. Some are quite wide awake, and a few are, well, ah, well getting Entish. That is going on all the time.\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Treebeard\\", \\"attribute_group\\": \\"\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Fangorn Forest apparently had several names as told by Treebeard who referred to the forest by various Quenya names in Lord of the Rings, some of which were Ambar\\\\u00f3na, Tauremornal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb, Tauremorna and Aldal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb. \\\\\\"Ambar\\\\u00f3na\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"uprising, sunrise, orient\\\\\\" from \\\\\\"amba\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"upwards\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"r\\\\u00f3na\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"east\\\\\\". \\\\\\"Aldal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"tree twilight\\\\\\" from \\\\\\"alda\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"tree\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"l\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"dusk, twilight\\\\\\".[1] \\\\\\"Tauremorna\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"gloomy forest\\\\\\" from \\\\\\"taur\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"forest\\\\\\" and \\\\\\"morna\\\\\\" meaning \\\\\\"gloomy, somber\\\\\\".[1] \\\\\\"Tauremornal\\\\u00f3m\\\\u00eb\\\\\\" means \\\\\\"gloomy twilight forest\\\\\\".</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Geography\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Forest of Fangorn was located at the south-eastern end of the Misty Mountains near the Gap of Rohan. The mountains formed the western border of Fangorn. At the end of the mountain range stood the stronghold of Isengard near the southwestern corner of the forest and this was where Saruman lived.[citation needed] To the east and south of Fangorn was the land of Rohan, and Lothl\\\\u00f3rien lay to the north and slightly east. Fangorn Forest stretched for many miles and held many paths.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Tolkien stated that two significant rivers ran through the forest. To the north the Limlight flowed from the woods and then formed the northern border of Rohan. The river then merged into the larger Anduin. In the south, the Entwash spread deep into the forest arriving from Methedras, a mountainous region located near the Misty Mountains. The river then flowed from Fangorn and was directed through Rohan to the Anduin River. The valley of Derndingle was located to the south-west. There was a path where the Entwash passed into a region called Wellinghall and this was where the Entwash passed the home of Treebeard, the shepherd of the forest.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Fangorn Forest was said to be humid, and trunks and branches grew thick where very little light penetrated the forest. Similarly, Fangorn was said to be a dangerous and evil place like Mirkwood (where huge spiders roamed the forest and other evil creatures lay), but this was not the case following the events of The Lord of the Rings. The forest was home to many different kinds of trees. Huorns also lived in the forest, similar to Ents but more discreet. Most lived deep in the Forest of Fangorn. The Ents and Huorns drank from the river Entwash, and from it the Ents brewed their legendary drink, the Ent-draughts.</p>\\"}]", "depth": 4, "go_live_at": null, "path": "0001000100030006", "pk": 17, "slug": "mawlamyine"}	\N	17	1
182	f	2017-06-13 03:18:51.918+00	{"url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/edoras/", "image": 43, "show_in_menus": false, "owner": 1, "locked": false, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "numchild": 0, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-05-07T02:31:20.472Z", "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "content_type": 6, "expire_at": null, "title": "Ngwesaung", "live": true, "search_description": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:00:16.547Z", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"image\\": 11, \\"style\\": \\"half\\", \\"caption\\": \\"The Uffington White Horse, whence the banner and shield of the House of Eorl \\\\u2013 a \\\\\\"white horse upon green\\\\\\" \\\\u2013 is derived.\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The capital of Rohan is the hill fort of Edoras which is located on a hill in a valley of the White Mountains. Meduseld, the Golden Hall of the King of Rohan, is located there. \\\\\\"Edoras\\\\\\" is Old English for \\\\\\"enclosures\\\\\\",[4] which Tolkien held to be a translation of an unknown Rohirric name of the same meaning. The city of Edoras was built by Rohan's second King, Brego son of Eorl the Young. Before Edoras was completed, Rohan's capital was at Aldburg in the Folde. Meduseld is described as having a golden thatch. Edoras is built at the end of the valley of Harrowdale, which lies under the great mountain Starkhorn. The river Snowbourn flows past the city on its way east towards the Entwash. The city is protected only by a high wall of timber, and a one-way road allows access to the city. Just before the gates, two rows of mounds line the road, which are the graves of the former Kings of Rohan. \\\\\\"Meduseld\\\\\\", a modernised form of the Old English Maeduselde,[5] is similarly meant to be a translation of an unknown Rohirric name meaning \\\\\\"mead hall\\\\\\". Meduseld is a large hall with roof that appears golden from far off. The walls are richly decorated with tapestries depicting the history and legends of the Rohirrim, and it serves as a house for the King and his kin, a meeting hall for the King and his advisors, and a gathering hall.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Edoras is Rohan's only real city. It is at Meduseld that Aragorn, Gimli, Legolas, and Gandalf meet with King Th\\\\u00e9oden in the account of the early stages of the War of the Ring.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Another settlement is Aldburg, capital of the Eastfold and original settlement of Eorl the Young. A third settlement is Snowbourne, named after the river of the same name which runs nearby. It is similar in appearance to the hill-fort of Edoras. Dunharrow is a refuge in the White Mountains. Helm's Deep is a valley in the White Mountains in which the Hornburg, a major fortress of Rohan, is located.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Internal history\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the thirteenth century of the Third Age (T.A.), the Kings of Gondor made close alliances with the Northmen of Rhovanion, a hosts said in The Lord of the Rings to be akin to the Three Houses of Men (later the D\\\\u00fanedain) from the First Age.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the twenty-first century, a remnant tribe of such Northmen calling itself the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od moved from the valleys of Anduin to the north west of Mirkwood, clearing out what remained of the recently defeated witch kingdom of Angmar, east of the Misty Mountains. While there, some dispute arose between them and the Dwarves over the treasure-hoard of Scatha the dragon.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Later, in 2509, Cirion the Steward of Gondor sent summons to the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od for aid in throwing off a combined invasion of Men from the north east of Middle-earth, and Orcs from Mordor.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Eorl the Young, king of the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od, answered the summons, and arrived unexpected at a decisive battle at the Field of Celebrant, routing the orc army, and then destroying it as it fled.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>As a reward, Eorl was given the plains of Calenardhon, and he moved his kingdom there. This land had earlier been part of Gondor proper, but had been devastated by the plague of 1636, and the survivors to a large extent slain in the invasion mentioned above.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\", \\"value\\": {\\"text\\": \\"Where now the horse and the rider? Where is the horn that was blowing?\\\\r\\\\nWhere is the helm and the hauberk, and the bright hair flowing?\\\\r\\\\nWhere is the hand on the harp-string, and the red fire glowing?\\\\r\\\\nWhere is the spring and the harvest and the tall corn growing?\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Aragorn\\", \\"attribute_group\\": \\"Reciting a forgotten poem on Eorl the Young\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<br/><p>The first line of kings lasted for 249 years, until the ninth king Helm Hammerhand died. His sons had been killed earlier, and his nephew Fr\\\\u00e9al\\\\u00e1f Hildeson began the second line of kings, which lasted until the end of the Third Age.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In 2758, Rohan was invaded by Dunlendings under Wulf, son of Freca, of mixed Dunland and Rohan blood. The King, Helm Hammerhand, took refuge in the Hornburg until aid from Gondor and Dunharrow (a refuge of the Rohirrim) arrived a year later and defeated the invaders.<br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/SLxeNktacYs\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>It was soon after this that Saruman arrived and took over Isengard, and was welcomed as a strong ally, since it would take Rohan close to 200 years to recover its strength after the invasion.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In 3014, Saruman began using his influence to weaken the King, Th\\\\u00e9oden, as part of a campaign to invade or take over the kingdom. In 3019, he launched a great invasion of Rohan, with victory in the two first battles (at the Fords of Isen; Th\\\\u00e9oden's son, Th\\\\u00e9odred was killed during these attacks) and defeat at the Battle of the Hornburg, where the Huorns came to the aid of the Rohirrim.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>On the heels of this victory, Th\\\\u00e9oden rode with an army to Minas Tirith and helped break its siege in the Battle of the Pelennor Fields, where he was slain. \\\\u00c9omer, the nephew of King Th\\\\u00e9oden, then took up the reign, beginning the third line. Also in this battle, \\\\u00c9owyn, niece of King Th\\\\u00e9oden and sister of \\\\u00c9omer, slew the Lord of the Nazg\\\\u00fbl. \\\\u00c9omer rode with the armies of Gondor to the Black Gate of Mordor and took part in the Battle of the Morannon against the forces of Sauron, who were defeated when the Ruling Ring was destroyed.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The rule of the Stewards of Gondor was then over. King \\\\u00c9omer and the new king of Gondor, Elessar, renewed their oath of alliance, and reaffirmed Cirion's grant of Calenardhon to the Rohirrim. At this time, \\\\u00c9owyn married Faramir, Prince of Ithilien and Steward of Gondor, thus joining the lines of Gondor and Rohan.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the Fourth Age, Rohan remained in peaceful coexistence with the Reunited Kingdom. A Dwarven community developed in the caves of Helm's Deep, which became prosperous from its mining of precious materials.<br/></p>\\"}]", "depth": 4, "go_live_at": null, "path": "0001000100030005", "pk": 16, "slug": "ngwesaung"}	\N	16	1
179	f	2017-06-13 03:17:05.697+00	{"url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/helms-deep/", "image": 46, "show_in_menus": false, "owner": 1, "locked": false, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "numchild": 0, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-05-07T02:34:07.371Z", "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "content_type": 6, "expire_at": null, "title": "Taunggyi", "live": true, "search_description": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T19:51:43.011Z", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0J. R. R. Tolkien's\\\\u00a0Middle-earth\\\\u00a0high fantasy\\\\u00a0writings,\\\\u00a0<b>Helm's Deep</b>\\\\u00a0was a large valley in the north-western\\\\u00a0Ered Nimrais\\\\u00a0(White Mountains).</p><p>The valley was described as being blocked over its entire width by the natural series of hills called\\\\u00a0<b>Helm's Dike</b>\\\\u00a0and behind that lay the fortress of Aglarond or the\\\\u00a0<b>Hornburg</b>, at the entrance to the Glittering Caves.</p><p>In the Appendices of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings</i>, the history of the valley states that it was home to a small\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondorian</a>\\\\u00a0regiment, but after the place which was called\\\\u00a0Calenardhon\\\\u00a0became\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>, it became an encampment of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)#hosts\\\\\\">Rohirrim</a>, where the guards of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fords_of_Isen\\\\\\">Fords of Isen</a>\\\\u00a0lived.</p><p>It also states that during the war with the\\\\u00a0Dunlendings\\\\u00a0under\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wulf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Wulf</a>, the Rohirrim under King\\\\u00a0Helm Hammerhand\\\\u00a0and many of his hosts sought refuge in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keep\\\\\\">keep</a>, where they held out during the winter of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_Age\\\\\\">T.A.</a>\\\\u00a02758\\\\u20132759.</p><p>The castle itself was described as having a long causeway which wound up to the great gate of the fortress itself. Inside the keep there were stables and an armoury, as well as a great hall in the rear which was dug out of the mountainside. There also was a great tower (the Hornburg) the top of which consisted of the great horn of\\\\u00a0Helm Hammerhand. The Deep, which was described as standing next to the fortress, was barred by the long Deeping Wall, which was described as consisting of solid rock except for a small culvert which allowed water from the Deeping Stream to enter; this rendered a fresh supply in sieges of great length. The Deeping Wall itself is described as standing 20 feet tall; and also being wide enough for four men to stand side by side. Access to the fortress from within the Deep was made possible by a long stair which led to the Hornburg's rear gate.</p><p>In\\\\u00a0<i>The Two Towers</i>, the fortress guarding Helm's Deep becomes the refuge of the main army of the Rohirrim, under King\\\\u00a0Th\\\\u00e9oden\\\\u00a0during the\\\\u00a0War of the Ring. Th\\\\u00e9oden said that \\\\\\"the Hornburg has never fallen to assault\\\\\\" giving an impression of invulnerability. This was tested during the\\\\u00a0Battle of the Hornburg, as a massive army of\\\\u00a0Uruk-hai\\\\u00a0sent by\\\\u00a0Saruman\\\\u00a0almost overwhelmed the defences of the Rohirrim. Saruman's\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0used an explosive blast of fire within the culvert which, when detonated, breached the long Deeping Wall. The origin of this explosion is unclear and Tolkien denotes it as \\\\\\"Saruman's devilry\\\\\\". The Rohirrim defenders held out long enough in the fortress until dawn, giving Gandalf time to gather and lead a counter-attack, while Th\\\\u00e9oden led a cavalry charge that drove the Orcs from the fortress.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"image\\": 9, \\"style\\": \\"half\\", \\"caption\\": \\"Crest of Gondor, the original builders of the Helm\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Aglarond\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Aglarond and Angrenost (which later became Isengard) were the two fortresses built by Gondor to guard the approaches to the Fords of Isen. Like Angrenost to the north, it was initially well guarded, but as the population of Calenardhon (the later Rohan) dwindled it was not maintained and, losing importance, was left to a hereditary small guard who intermarried with Dunlendings.</p><p><br/></p><p>When Cirion, Steward of Gondor, gave Calenardhon to the \\\\u00c9oth\\\\u00e9od, Aglarond was transferred into the care of the Rohirrim, who named it S\\\\u00fathburg (southern burg in their language). The Gondorian guard was merged with that of Angrenost to the north, which remained in the keep of Gondor. Guard duty of the Fords was initially shared between Gondor and Rohan, but later maintained only by the Rohirrim.</p><p><br/></p><p>During the reign of Helm Hammerhand, Rohan was attacked by Dunlendings from across the river Isen. Edoras was taken, and Helm and many of his hosts retreated to S\\\\u00fathburg. Because Helm always blew a great horn before riding out to fight the beleaguering Dunlendings, the keep was renamed Hornburg. During the War of the Ring, the Hornburg was the refuge of the Rohirrim as they defended Helm's Deep.</p><p><br/></p><p>After the war, Gimli the Dwarf, who fought in that battle, established a colony of Durin's folk there. Aglarond lay in front of a huge and very beautiful cave system, which proved irresistible to him. Gimli became known as 'the Lord of the Glittering Caves', although this new realm was presumably under the overlordship of Thorin Stonehelm, his kinsman and heir of the lordship of all Durin's Folk. The dwarves of Aglarond restored the Hornburg following the War of the Ring, and it became a fortress they shared with the Rohirrim.</p>\\"}]", "depth": 4, "go_live_at": null, "path": "0001000100030004", "pk": 15, "slug": "taunggyi"}	\N	15	1
178	f	2017-06-13 03:16:44.07+00	{"url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/mordor/", "image": 47, "show_in_menus": false, "owner": 1, "locked": false, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "numchild": 0, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-05-07T02:34:40.909Z", "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "content_type": 6, "expire_at": null, "title": "Mandalay", "live": true, "search_description": "", "first_published_at": "2016-10-24T15:19:13.969Z", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_world\\\\\\">fictional world</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>,\\\\u00a0<b>Mordor</b>\\\\u00a0(pronounced\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA\\\\\\">[\\\\u02c8m\\\\u0254rd\\\\u0254r]</a>; from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\\\\\">Sindarin</a>\\\\u00a0<i>Black Land</i>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quenya\\\\\\">Quenya</a>\\\\u00a0<i>Land of Shadow</i>) was the region occupied and controlled by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>, in the southeast of northwestern Middle-earth to the East of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anduin\\\\\\">Anduin</a>, the great river.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orodruin\\\\\\">Orodruin</a>, a volcano in Mordor, was the goal of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>\\\\u00a0(and later\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee\\\\\\">Sam Gamgee</a>) in the quest to destroy the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>.</p><p>Mordor has three enormous mountain ranges surrounding it, from the north, from the west and from the south. The mountains both protected the land from an unexpected invasion by any of the hosts living in those directions and kept those living in Mordor from escaping. Tolkien was reported to have identified Mordor with the volcano of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stromboli\\\\\\">Stromboli</a>\\\\u00a0off Sicily, in terms of geographic equivalency with the real world.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"image\\": 16, \\"style\\": \\"contain\\", \\"caption\\": \\"Barad-d\\\\u00fbr looking over Mount Doom\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Geography\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Three sides of Mordor were bounded by mountain ranges, arranged in a rough rectangle: the Ered Lithui (translated as 'Ash Mountains') on the north, and the Ephel D\\\\u00faath (literally, \\\\\\"Fence of Shadow\\\\\\") on the west and the south. In the northwest the pass of Cirith Gorgor led into the enclosed plain of Ud\\\\u00fbn. Sauron built the Black Gate of Mordor (the Morannon) across the pass, joining the Towers of the Teeth, two earlier guard towers built by Gondor to keep a watch on this entrance. The passage through the inner side of Ud\\\\u00fbn into the interior of Mordor was guarded by another gate, the Isenmouthe. Outside the Morannon lay the Dagorlad or Battle Plain.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In the interior within this mountainous border lay Sauron's main fortress Barad-d\\\\u00fbr, the arid plateau of Gorgoroth, and Mount Doom. To the east lay the plain of Lithlad. A narrow pass led through the Ephel D\\\\u00faath, guarded by Minas Morgul (earlier Minas Ithil). A higher, more difficult pass, Cirith Ungol, just to the north, was guarded by a tower originally built by Gondor. This pass, \\\\\\"the pass of the spider\\\\\\", was also blockaded by Torech Ungol, the lair of the giant spider Shelob. The fortress Durthang lay in the northern Ephel D\\\\u00faath above Ud\\\\u00fbn.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/jk9wwlzuwJE\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>N\\\\u00farn, the southern part of Mordor, was less arid and more fertile. Streams here fed the salt Sea of N\\\\u00farnen. Sauron's slaves farmed this region to support his armies.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Inside the Ephel D\\\\u00faath ran a lower parallel ridge, the Morgai, separated from the Ephel D\\\\u00faath by a narrow valley that Frodo and Sam followed northward after escaping from Cirith Ungol. Water trickled into this vale from the Ephel D\\\\u00faath, and the text describes it as a \\\\\\"dying land not yet dead\\\\\\". The vegetation included \\\\\\"low scrubby trees\\\\\\", \\\\\\"coarse grey grass-tussocks\\\\\\", \\\\\\"withered mosses\\\\\\", \\\\\\"great writhing, tangled brambles\\\\\\", and thickets of briars with long, stabbing thorns. The fauna included maggots, midges, and flies marked with \\\\\\"a red eye-shaped blotch\\\\\\".</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Adjacent to Mordor were, to the west, the narrow land of Ithilien (a province of Gondor); to the northwest the Dead Marshes; to the northeast Rh\\\\u00fbn; to the southeast Khand; and to the south Harad.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In The Atlas of Middle-earth, Karen Wynn Fonstad assumed that the lands of Mordor, Khand, and Rh\\\\u00fbn lay where the inland Sea of Helcar had been, and that the Sea of Rh\\\\u00fbn and Sea of N\\\\u00farnen were its remnants. This assumption stemmed from a First Age world-map drawn by Tolkien in the Ambarkanta, where the Inland Sea of Helcar occupied a large area of Middle-earth between the Ered Luin and Orocarni, with the western end being close to the head of the Great Gulf (later the Mouths of Anduin).[2] The atlas was however published before The hostss of Middle-earth, in which the Sea of Rh\\\\u00fbn and Mordor exist already in the First Age.</p>\\"}]", "depth": 4, "go_live_at": null, "path": "0001000100030001", "pk": 8, "slug": "mandalay"}	\N	8	1
177	f	2017-06-13 03:16:09.661+00	{"url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/shire/", "image": 48, "show_in_menus": false, "owner": 1, "locked": false, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "numchild": 0, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-05-07T02:35:27.861Z", "expired": false, "seo_title": "", "content_type": 6, "expire_at": null, "title": "Yangon", "live": true, "search_description": "", "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:11:19.705Z", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Shire is a region of J. R. R. Tolkien's fictional Middle-earth, described in The Lord of the Rings and other works. The Shire refers to an area settled exclusively by Hobbits and largely removed from the goings-on in the rest of Middle-earth. It is located in the northwest of the continent, in the large region of Eriador and the Kingdom of Arnor. In the languages invented by Tolkien, its name in Westron was S\\\\u00fbza \\\\\\"Shire\\\\\\"[1] or S\\\\u00fbzat \\\\\\"The Shire\\\\\\",[2] while its name in Sindarin was i Drann.[3]</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Geography\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>According to Tolkien, the Shire measured 40 leagues (193 km, 120 miles[4]) from the Far Downs in the west to the Brandywine Bridge in the east, and 50 leagues (241 km, 150 miles) from the northern moors to the marshes in the south.[5] This is confirmed in an essay by Tolkien on translating The Lord of the Rings,[6] where he describes the Shire as having an area of 18,000 square miles (47,000 km2).[7]</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"embed\\", \\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/Ti5OaadrS9I\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The original territory of the Shire was bounded on the east by the Baranduin River, on the north by uplands rising to the old centre of Arnor, on the west by the White Downs, and on the south by marshland south of the River Shirebourn. After the original settlement, hobbits also expanded to the east into Buckland between the Baranduin and the Old Forest, and (much later) to the west into the Westmarch between the White Downs and the Tower Hills.[8]</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Shire was originally divided into four Farthings. The outlying lands of Buckland and the Westmarch were formally added after the War of the Ring.[5] Within the Farthings there are some smaller unofficial clan homelands: the Tooks nearly all live in or near Tuckborough in Tookland, for instance. A Hobbit surname often indicates where the family came from: Samwise Gamgee's last name derives from Gamwich, where the family originated. Buckland was named for the Oldbucks (later called the Brandybucks).</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The Shire is described as a small but beautiful, idyllic and fruitful land, beloved by its inhabitants. The Hobbits had an extensive agricultural system in the Shire but were not industrialised. The landscape included small pockets of forest (again similar to the English countryside). Various supplies were produced in the Shire, including cereals, fruit, wood and pipe-weed.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"header\\", \\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Regions of the Shire\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The original parts of the Shire were subdivided into four Farthings (\\\\\\"fourth-ings\\\\\\" or \\\\\\"quarterings\\\\\\").[9] The Three-Farthing Stone marked the tripoint where the borders of the Eastfarthing, Westfarthing and Southfarthing of the Shire came together, by the East Road.[10] (Iceland was traditionally also divided in Farthings, or \\\\\\"fourth parts\\\\\\", as the Shire is.) It is claimed that the Three-Farthing Stone was inspired by the Four shire stone.[11]</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Buckland, across the Baranduin River to the east, and the Westmarch, between the Far Downs and the Tower Hills to the west, were not part of the original grant to the hobbits by King Argeleb II of Arthedain. These were formally given to the hobbits as the East and West Marches of the Shire by King Elessar after the War of the Ring, in S.R. 1462 (F.A. 41).[9][12] Buckland had been long settled by then: Gorhendad Oldbuck led hobbits from the East Farthing across the river in T.A. 2340,[12] and Buckland became \\\\\\"sort of a colony of the Shire\\\\\\".[13] There is no mention of settlement in the Westmarch until Elessar's gift; Sam Gamgee's daughter Elanor and her husband Fastred later settled there, and Fastred was created Warden of Westmarch.</p>\\"}]", "depth": 4, "go_live_at": null, "path": "0001000100030007", "pk": 18, "slug": "yangon"}	\N	18	1
289	f	2018-01-26 04:05:28.70815+00	{"path": "0001000100030002", "go_live_at": null, "content_type": 6, "depth": 4, "show_in_menus": false, "image": 41, "numchild": 0, "first_published_at": "2017-01-09T10:57:05.960Z", "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "live": true, "slug": "inle", "expired": false, "title": "Inle", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Inle Lake is a shallow lake in the middle of Myanmar, south-east of Mandalay. The lake is 22km long, and is densely inhabited by many different tribes.<br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"style\\": \\"half\\", \\"image\\": 69, \\"caption\\": \\"Inle Paungdaw Oo Pagoda\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The easiest way to get into Inle Lake (and the most comfortable) is by domestic flight. The closest airport is in Heho, which is a taxi-ride (about 1 hour) away from the lake itself (walking down the road from the airport, towards the highway, should see quoted fares drop, if not, try your luck hailing a taxi or passing pickup on the highway itself). Taking a taxi from the airport is expensive, as of January 2017 there is a fixed, non-bargainable price of 25,000 Kyats to go to Nyuang Shwe. If you baulk at the high fare, the taxi drivers will attempt to gather other travelers to share the taxi and split the fare, so there is a good chance you will end up paying a lot less by sharing your taxi. By comparison a taxi from Yangon airport to the city centre (45 min.) is just 8000 Kyats or 7 USD. A possible way to save money is to book a taxi in advance with your guesthouse, but seems like now they all charge the same 25,000 kyat fixed price. 15,000kyat is a good price to/from the airport that may be more difficult to reserve on your way in, but no issue to book for your return trip to Heho from any agency in town. When returning, you can often save by booking a shared taxi through your hotel or one of the many travel agents around. Check with them the day before you fly out.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Prices for flights are around US$110 from Yangon and US$75 from Mandalay, but unlike bus companies the government is heavily involved in the domestic air market, a good chunk of your money will be going into their hands.</p>\\"}]", "expire_at": null, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "latest_revision_created_at": "2018-01-26T04:05:02.244Z", "owner": 1, "pk": 12, "url_path": "/homepage/places/inle/", "locked": false}	\N	12	1
