199	f	2017-06-17 04:42:23.549+00	{"body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>My trip started on Platform 7 of bustling Yangon Central Station, Myanmar\\\\u2019s largest train station, built by the British in 1877. Heading counterclockwise, the train crawled through sprawling rail depots and repair yards. Soon the larger, national trains branched off and headed north, and the six tracks thinned to two, servicing the Circle Line alone.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>As the train moved up Yangon\\\\u2019s east side, mildew-stained buildings started to give way to farmland. The carriages gradually emptied out as the train looped around the city\\\\u2019s northern reaches, past open fields, a golf course, a military base and palm huts where some of Yangon\\\\u2019s poorest live.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Railway employees are supposed to wear crisp, white Myanmar Railways shirts with epaulets. But at some of the route\\\\u2019s 38 stations, like Danyingon in the north, they frequently strip down to their undershirts to keep cool in the sweltering ticket booths and control rooms, which often do not have a working fan.</p>\\"}]", "seo_title": "", "path": "0001000100040001", "url_path": "/homepage/blog/first-blog-page/", "owner": 1, "slug": "first-blog-page", "numchild": 0, "intro": "Travelling Yangon by Train", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "show_in_menus": false, "latest_revision_created_at": null, "first_published_at": null, "locked": false, "pk": 40, "live": false, "go_live_at": null, "search_description": "", "depth": 4, "title": "First Blog Page", "date": "2017-06-16", "expire_at": null, "image": 50, "expired": false, "content_type": 42}	\N	40	1
