org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0and her mother died of grief. \\\\u00c9owyn and \\\\u00c9omer were raised in her uncle's household as if they were his own children.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Tolkien writes that she longed to win renown in battle\\\\u2014especially since she was royal\\\\u2014but being female, her duties were reckoned to be at Edoras.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-healing-2\\\\\\">[2]</a>\\\\u00a0When Th\\\\u00e9oden's mind was poisoned by his adviser\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr%C3%ADma_Wormtongue\\\\\\">Gr\\\\u00edma Wormtongue</a>, \\\\u00c9owyn was obliged to care for her uncle, and his deterioration pained her deeply. To make matters worse, she was constantly harassed by Gr\\\\u00edma, who lusted after her. However, when\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>\\\\u00a0arrived, he freed Th\\\\u00e9oden from Wormtongue's influence.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>\\\\u00c9owyn fell in love with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\\\\\">Aragorn</a>, but it soon became clear that he could not return her love although he did not mention his betrothal to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arwen\\\\\\">Arwen</a>, except by indirect allusion, and would not allow her to join him in going to war.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-grey-3\\\\\\">[3]</a>\\\\u00a0As Aragorn pointed out,<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-grey-3\\\\\\">[3]</a>\\\\u00a0her duty was with her hosts; she had to shoulder the responsibility of ruling Rohan in Th\\\\u00e9oden's stead when the war-host of Rohan went to war,<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-hall-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0a duty he deemed no less valiant.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-grey-3\\\\\\">[3]</a>\\\\u00a0Likening her situation to a \\\\\\"cage\\\\\\", \\\\u00c9owyn said she feared \\\\\\"[t]o stay behind bars, until use and old age accept them, and all chance of great deeds is gone beyond recall or desire.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-grey-3\\\\\\">[3]</a></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"text\\": \\"But who knows what she spoke to the darkness, alone, in the bitter watches of the night, when all her life seemed shrinking, and the walls of her bower closing in about her, a hutch to trammel some wild thing in?\\", \\"attribute_group\\": \\"\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Aragorn\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>In\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King\\\\\\">The Return of the King</a>\\\\u00a0</i>she disguised herself as a man and under the alias of\\\\u00a0<i>Dernhelm</i>\\\\u00a0(from Old English\\\\u00a0<i>dern</i>\\\\u00a0meaning \\\\\\"secret, concealed\\\\\\"), and she traveled with the Riders of Rohan to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_the_Pelennor_Fields\\\\\\">Battle of the Pelennor Fields</a>\\\\u00a0outside the White City of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith\\\\\\">Minas Tirith</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondor</a>, carrying with her\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>, who had also been ordered to remain behind, on her horse Windfola.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>During the battle of the Pelennor Fields, she confronted the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witch-king_of_Angmar\\\\\\">Witch-king of Angmar</a>, Lord of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl\\\\\\">Nazg\\\\u00fbl</a>, after Th\\\\u00e9oden was injured. The Witch-king threatened to \\\\\\"bear [her] away to the houses of lamentation, beyond all darkness, where [her] flesh shall be devoured, and [her] shriveled mind be left naked to the Lidless Eye.\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-pelennor-4\\\\\\">[4]</a>\\\\u00a0The Witch-king further boasted that \\\\\\"[n]o living man may hinder me,\\\\\\"<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-pelennor-4\\\\\\">[4]</a>\\\\u00a0referring to the 1,000-year-old\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prophecy\\\\\\">prophecy</a>\\\\u00a0by the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elf</a>-lord\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glorfindel\\\\\\">Glorfindel</a>, foretelling that the Witch-king would not fall \\\\\\"by the hand of man\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-glorfindel-5\\\\\\">[5]</a>\\\\u00a0\\\\u00c9owyn then removed her helmet and declared.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>But no living man am I! You look upon a woman. \\\\u00c9owyn I am, \\\\u00c9omund\\\\u2019s daughter. You stand between me and my lord and kin. Begone, if you be not deathless! For living or dark undead, I will smite you, if you touch him.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-pelennor-4\\\\\\">[4]</a></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>The Witch-king attacked \\\\u00c9owyn with his\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl#Steeds\\\\\\">steed</a>, but she slew it with her sword. He then shattered her shield and broke her shield-arm with his mace, but was distracted by Merry, who stabbed him behind the knee with a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrow-blade\\\\\\">barrow-blade</a>. \\\\u00c9owyn seized the opportunity to strike the Witch-king with a killing thrust \\\\\\"between crown and mantle\\\\\\".<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89owyn#cite_note-pelennor-4\\\\\\">[4]</a>\\\\u00a0Then, as her sword shattered, his withering form collapsed and he vanished with a final cry of anguish.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}]", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-04-29T23:00:41.991Z", "url_path": "/homepage/index-page/\\u00e9owyn/", "host_place_relationship": [{"pk": 6, "place": 15, "host_page": 28}], "owner": 1, "go_live_at": null, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "pk": 28, "host_language_relationship": [{"pk": 1, "host_languages": 1, "host_page": 28}, {"pk": 2, "host_languages": 8, "host_page": 28}, {"pk": 3, "host_languages": 2, "host_page": 28}], "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "live": true, "title": "\\u00c9owyn", "locked": false}	\N	28	1
229	f	2018-01-20 21:58:14.884053+00	{"host_language_relationship": [], "expired": false, "image": 57, "expire_at": null, "body": "[{\\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Samwise</b>\\\\u00a0\\\\\\"<b>Sam</b>\\\\\\"\\\\u00a0<b>Gamgee</b>\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English\\\\\\">/\\\\u02c8s\\\\u00e6m\\\\u02ccwa\\\\u026az\\\\u00a0\\\\u02c8\\\\u0261\\\\u00e6m\\\\u02ccd\\\\u0292i\\\\u02d0/</a>\\\\u00a0(later known as Samwise Gardner)<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samwise_Gamgee#cite_note-gardner-1\\\\\\">[1]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_character\\\\\\">fictional character</a>\\\\u00a0in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tolkien%27s_legendarium\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien's legendarium</a>. Samwise is one of the main characters of\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>, in which he fills an\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archetype\\\\\\">archetypical</a>\\\\u00a0role as the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sidekick\\\\\\">sidekick</a>\\\\u00a0of the primary\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protagonist\\\\\\">protagonist</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>. Sam is a member of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"size\\": \\"h2\\", \\"header_text\\": \\"Literature\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Samwise Gamgee is first introduced in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>. Sam is\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>' gardener, having inherited the position as Baggins' gardener from his father,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaffer_Gamgee\\\\\\">Hamfast \\\\\\"Gaffer\\\\\\" Gamgee</a>. At the time of the War of the Ring, Sam was living in Number 3,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Middle-earth_roads#Bagshot_Row\\\\\\">Bagshot Row</a>\\\\u00a0with his father.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>As \\\\\\"punishment\\\\\\" for\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eavesdropping\\\\\\">eavesdropping</a>\\\\u00a0on\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>'s conversation with Frodo regarding the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>, Sam was made Frodo's first companion on his journey to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>. They were joined by\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took\\\\\\">Peregrin Took</a>, Frodo's cousins, and journeyed together to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>, where the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_Elrond\\\\\\">Council of Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0took place and Sam joined the Fellowship of the Ring.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"text\\": \\"'Come, Mr. Frodo!' he cried. 'I can't carry it for you, but I can carry you.'\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Samwise Gamgee\\", \\"attribute_group\\": \\"Return of the King\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>When the Fellowship was split up at the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falls_of_Rauros\\\\\\">Falls of Rauros</a>, Sam insisted on accompanying Frodo. Sam protected and cared for Frodo, who was growing weaker under the Ring's influence, as they moved through the dangerous lands toward\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordor\\\\\\">Mordor</a>. Sam distrusted\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gollum\\\\\\">Gollum</a>, who became their guide into Mordor. His suspicions were proven right when Gollum betrayed them to the giant spider\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelob\\\\\\">Shelob</a>. After Shelob apparently killed Frodo, Sam drove her off. When a band of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">orcs</a>\\\\u00a0approached, Sam was forced to leave the apparently dead Frodo and take the Ring himself, and briefly became a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring-bearer\\\\\\">Ring-bearer</a>. He was momentarily tempted by its promise of power, but did not succumb to it, subsequently rescuing Frodo (who had only been paralysed) from the Orcs who held him captive. Sam also returned the Ring to Frodo, making him the only Ring-bearer to freely give up the Ring without intervention. The two then journeyed alone through Mordor and into the heart of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Doom\\\\\\">Mount Doom</a>, where Gollum attacked Frodo and reclaimed the Ring, only to inadvertently destroy both it and himself by falling into the mountain's lava.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/l1eLHoDxMNE\\", \\"type\\": \\"embed\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>After the hobbits' return home and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Bywater\\\\\\">Battle of Bywater</a>, Sam travelled the length and breadth of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0replanting trees that had been cut down during\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>'s brief reign. He used the gift of earth given to him by the Lady\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galadriel\\\\\\">Galadriel</a>, which caused the saplings he planted to grow at an accelerated rate. The small amount remaining he took to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-Farthing_Stone\\\\\\">Three-Farthing Stone</a>\\\\u00a0(roughly the centre of the Shire) and cast into the air, prompting the bountiful period of growth starting in the spring of the year 1420 (<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_Reckoning\\\\\\">Shire Reckoning</a>). The greatest wonder was a young\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mallorn\\\\\\">mallorn</a></i>\\\\u00a0tree sprouting in the Party Field: \\\\\\"the only\\\\u00a0<i>mallorn</i>\\\\u00a0west of the Mountains and east of the Sea\\\\\\" (grown from a nut included as part of Galadriel's gift).</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>After the War of the Ring, Sam married\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Hobbits#Rose_Cotton\\\\\\">Rose \\\\\\"Rosie\\\\\\" Cotton</a>\\\\u00a0and moved to\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bag_End\\\\\\">Bag End</a>\\\\u00a0with Frodo. Sam and Rosie had 13 children:\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elanor_the_Fair\\\\\\">Elanor the Fair</a>, Frodo, Rose, Merry, Pippin, Goldilocks, Hamfast, Daisy, Primrose, Bilbo, Ruby, Robin, and Tolman (Tom). Sam was elected\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mayor_of_the_Shire\\\\\\">Mayor of the Shire</a>\\\\u00a0for seven consecutive seven-year terms and came to be known as Samwise Gardner.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>After Sam and Rose's first child was born, Frodo told Sam he would leave\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle-earth\\\\\\">Middle-earth</a>, along with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilbo_Baggins\\\\\\">Bilbo Baggins</a>, Gandalf and most of the remaining High\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Elves</a>, for the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Undying_Lands\\\\\\">Undying Lands</a>. Before Frodo left, he gave the estate of Bag End to Sam, as well as the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Book_of_Westmarch\\\\\\">Red Book of Westmarch</a></i>\\\\u00a0for Sam to continue, hinting that Sam might also be allowed to travel into the West eventually.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>After the death of his wife in the year 62 of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourth_Age\\\\\\">Fourth Age</a>\\\\u00a0(<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_Calendar\\\\\\">Shire Reckoning</a>\\\\u00a01482), Sam entrusted the Red Book to Elanor and left the Shire at the age of 102. He was not seen again in Middle-earth, but Elanor and her descendants preserved the tradition that he went to the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_Havens\\\\\\">Grey Havens</a>\\\\u00a0and sailed into the West. As the last of the Ring-bearers, he was entitled to sail across the Sea and be reunited with Frodo in the Undying Lands.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}]", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-23T07:21:34.397Z", "owner": 1, "pk": 36, "path": "000100010001000D", "content_type": 10, "depth": 4, "slug": "samwise-gamgee", "search_description": "", "go_live_at": null, "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T22:13:58.009Z", "numchild": 0, "url_path": "/homepage/hosts/samwise-gamgee/", "seo_title": "", "email_address": "yan.pye.aung@gmail.com", "show_in_menus": false, "live": true, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "title": "Tin Oo", "locked": false}	\N	36	2
230	f	2018-01-20 21:59:11.083955+00	{"host_language_relationship": [], "expired": false, "image": 58, "expire_at": null, "body": "[{\\"value\\": \\"<p><b>Peregrin Took</b>, more commonly known as\\\\u00a0<b>Pippin</b>, is a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictional_character\\\\\\">fictional character</a>\\\\u00a0from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\\\\\\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s fantasy novel\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings\\\\\\">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. Pippin is introduced as a young\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobbit\\\\\\">Hobbit</a>, and plays a major role as one of the companions of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>, in his quest to destroy the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Ring\\\\\\">One Ring</a>. Pippin is a member of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>.</p><p></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"size\\": \\"h2\\", \\"header_text\\": \\"Overview\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Peregrin was the only son and heir of Paladin Took II, the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thain_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Thain</a>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shire_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">the Shire</a>. His best friend\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meriadoc_Brandybuck\\\\\\">Meriadoc Brandybuck</a>, more commonly known as Merry, was his cousin; another good friend was\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins\\\\\\">Frodo Baggins</a>.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>'Peregrin' means 'traveller in strange countries'.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took#cite_note-1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0Pippin indeed saw much more of Middle-earth than most Hobbits: he journeyed with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo\\\\\\">Frodo</a>\\\\u00a0and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship of the Ring</a>, and fought in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_of_the_Ring\\\\\\">War of the Ring</a>. Late in life he travelled again to the kingdoms of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>\\\\u00a0and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gondor\\\\\\">Gondor</a>.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Pippin's hair colour is mentioned as \\\\\\"almost golden\\\\\\" in\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_History_of_Middle-earth\\\\\\">The History of Middle-earth</a></i>, vol. IX,\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron_Defeated\\\\\\">Sauron Defeated</a></i>, through the eyes of Pippin Gamgee.<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peregrin_Took#cite_note-SD_-2\\\\\\">[2]</a>\\\\u00a0In the later drafts of this same section Tolkien omitted this statement, leaving the reader to envisage Pippin's appearance.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"size\\": \\"h2\\", \\"header_text\\": \\"The Great Years\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Pippin was the youngest of the four Hobbits who set out from the Shire and the only one who had not yet reached his 'coming of age' at age 33. He was therefore said to be still in his 'tweens' (twenties). He was 28 at the time, while Merry, the next youngest, was 36. At\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell\\\\\\">Rivendell</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elrond\\\\\\">Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0almost denied Pippin the chance to accompany Frodo, intending to send Pippin and Merry as messengers back to the Shire.\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gandalf\\\\\\">Gandalf</a>, however, supported his and Merry's claims of friendship and loyalty, and the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_Elrond\\\\\\">Council of Elrond</a>\\\\u00a0ultimately chose them as the last two members of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellowship_of_the_Ring_(characters)\\\\\\">Fellowship</a>.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/5cZ4ABUo6TU\\", \\"type\\": \\"embed\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>After remaining with the Fellowship until its breaking at\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amon_Hen\\\\\\">Amon Hen</a>, Pippin was captured along with Merry by an\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Orc</a>-band, which included some of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saruman\\\\\\">Saruman</a>'s\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uruk-hai\\\\\\">Uruk-hai</a>. While held captive by the Orcs, he purposefully dropped his elven brooch (a gift from\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lothl%C3%B3rien\\\\\\">L\\\\u00f3rien</a>) as a sign for\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragorn\\\\\\">Aragorn</a>,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legolas\\\\\\">Legolas</a>, and\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gimli_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Gimli</a>, who were in pursuit. During a skirmish among his captors, Pippin managed to cut his bonds using a sword held fast by a dead Uruk. In\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)\\\\\\">Rohan</a>, Pippin and Merry managed to escape when the Orcs were attacked by a company of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)#hosts\\\\\\">Rohirrim</a>, the local hosts. Upon their escape, he and Merry befriended\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treebeard\\\\\\">Treebeard</a>, leader of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ent\\\\\\">Ents</a>. They roused the other Ents to fight against Saruman, and they attacked his stronghold of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isengard\\\\\\">Isengard</a>, partially crippling his power. Due to a special \\\\\\"Ent-draught\\\\\\" that Treebeard made him and Merry drink, Pippin and his cousin became the tallest Hobbits in history, at four and a half feet, surpassing Pippin's ancestor,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullroarer_Took#Bandobras\\\\\\">Bullroarer Took</a>, who was four feet and five inches tall.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>Pippin picked up the\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palant%C3%ADr\\\\\\">palant\\\\u00edr</a></i>\\\\u00a0of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthanc\\\\\\">Orthanc</a>\\\\u00a0after\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr%C3%ADma_Wormtongue\\\\\\">Gr\\\\u00edma Wormtongue</a>\\\\u00a0threw it at them. Later, obsessed by the mysterious stone, Pippin took it out of Gandalf's hands while the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Istari\\\\\\">wizard</a>\\\\u00a0slept, putting a rock in its place. Looking into the stone, he had a terrifying encounter with\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauron\\\\\\">Sauron</a>\\\\u00a0himself. In fact, Pippin is the only character in the book who is shown to speak directly to Sauron. To keep Pippin safe from Sauron's forces, Gandalf brought him to the city of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minas_Tirith\\\\\\">Minas Tirith</a>, separating him from his friends.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}]", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-01-23T07:18:15.996Z", "owner": 1, "pk": 34, "path": "000100010001000B", "content_type": 10, "depth": 4, "slug": "pergrin-took", "search_description": "", "go_live_at": null, "first