285	f	2018-01-26 03:58:23.7526+00	{"path": "0001000100030008", "go_live_at": null, "content_type": 6, "depth": 4, "show_in_menus": false, "image": 45, "numchild": 0, "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:16:17.742Z", "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "live": true, "slug": "naypyidaw", "expired": false, "title": "Naypyidaw", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Naypyidaw is a unique city in the region. It is a fully constructed large city but with very few inhabitants compared to its size, so you can experience the amazing and unprecedented (for Asia) experience of never ever being stuck in traffic. It is between two mountain ranges so has little to offer in the way of day trips or activities. The city was constructed to be the capital by the military and lacks the dissarray and wonder found throughout the rest of Myanmar.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Naypyidaw was constructed in secret by the Myanmar Junta in the early 2000s. In November 2005 it was officially announced as the country's new capital. Government workers were given two months notice that they would have to move from Yangon, as all government offices and ministries were relocated. Embassies and international organisations like the UN have not yet relocated but are expected to at some point. The international retail chains found throughout all other capital cities are not present in Naypyidaw.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The city has wide boulevards/highways (still almost empty) and extravagant roundabouts. It has housing for government workers, but many still maintain residences for their families in Yangon as education and health infrastructure is not yet in place.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"style\\": \\"half\\", \\"image\\": 68, \\"caption\\": \\"Gandalf doing awesome things\\"}}]", "expire_at": null, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-06-13T03:17:47.399Z", "owner": 1, "pk": 19, "url_path": "/homepage/places/naypyidaw/", "locked": false}	\N	19	1
146	f	2017-05-06 04:18:12.278+00	{"has_unpublished_changes": false, "show_in_menus": false, "title": "Naypyidaw", "depth": 4, "owner": 1, "live": true, "url_path": "/homepage/place-index-page/rivendell/", "path": "0001000100030008", "slug": "rivendell", "search_description": "", "expired": false, "expire_at": null, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-05-06T04:14:21.594Z", "body": "[{\\"value\\": \\"<p>Rivendell is an Elven realm in Middle-earth, a fictional world created by J. R. R. Tolkien. It is an important place in Tolkien's legendarium, and is featured in The Hobbit, The Lord of the Rings, The Silmarillion, and Unfinished Tales. It was established and ruled by Elrond Half-elven in the Second Age of Middle-earth (four or five thousand years before the events of The Lord of the Rings), and was protected by the powers of its lord and his elven ring Vilya.</p><p>Elrond lived in Rivendell with his family \\\\u2014 his wife Celebr\\\\u00edan (until she departed for Valinor), their sons Elladan and Elrohir, and their daughter Arwen \\\\u2014 as well as a sizeable number of other Elves, both Noldor and Sindar. In addition to the family of Elrond, notable Elves who lived in Rivendell included Glorfindel, Gildor, and Erestor. In some writings, featured in Unfinished Tales, Galadriel and Celeborn also lived in Rivendell for a time before they became rulers of Lothl\\\\u00f3rien.</p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"image\\": 26, \\"caption\\": \\"Gandalf doing awesome things\\", \\"style\\": \\"half\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"image\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"https://youtu.be/t9L8Er_oqAQ\\", \\"type\\": \\"embed\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Etymology\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Testing\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p><i>Rivendell</i>\\\\u00a0is a direct translation or\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calque\\\\\\">calque</a>\\\\u00a0into English of the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sindarin\\\\\\">Sindarin</a>\\\\u00a0name\\\\u00a0<b>Imladris</b>, both meaning \\\\\\"deep valley of the cleft\\\\\\". The name Rivendell is formed by two English elements: \\\\\\"riven\\\\\\" (split, cloven) and \\\\\\"dell\\\\\\" (valley), making the whole word purport \\\\\\"deeply cloven valley\\\\\\". Imladris was also rendered \\\\\\"<i>Karningul</i>\\\\\\" in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Westron\\\\\\">Westron</a>, the \\\\\\"Common Tongue\\\\\\" of Middle-Earth represented as English in the text of\\\\u00a0<i>The Lord of the Rings.</i>\\\\u00a0It is also referred to as\\\\u00a0<i>The Last Homely House,</i>\\\\u00a0alluding to the elves' old cities, in Beleriand and Aman, and the wilderness (Rhovanion) that lies east of the Misty Mountains.<br/></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"header_text\\": \\"Legacy\\", \\"size\\": \\"h2\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"header\\"}, {\\"value\\": {\\"attribute_group\\": \\"Fellowship of the Ring\\", \\"text\\": \\"Evil things do not come into this valley... We are sitting in a fortress. Outside it is getting dark.\\", \\"attribute_name\\": \\"Gandalf\\"}, \\"type\\": \\"blockquote\\"}, {\\"value\\": \\"<p>In the period of\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Counterculture\\\\\\">counterculture</a>\\\\u00a0in the\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_World\\\\\\">Western World</a>\\\\u00a0of the 1960s and 1970s, a\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commune\\\\\\">commune</a>\\\\u00a0called\\\\u00a0<i>Maos Lyst</i>\\\\u00a0(<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mao_Zedong\\\\\\">Mao</a>'s Delight) was founded in\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denmark\\\\\\">Denmark</a>\\\\u00a0in 1968, its inhabitants replacing their surnames with\\\\u00a0<i>Kl\\\\u00f8vedal</i>, Danish for Rivendell, inspired by Tolkien's Elven outpost.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell#cite_note-6\\\\\\">[6]</a></sup>\\\\u00a0Several of them later became well-known cultural personalities in the country.</p><p>The Canadian progressive rock band\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rush_(band)\\\\\\">Rush</a>\\\\u00a0memorializes Rivendell in the song \\\\\\"Rivendell\\\\\\" on their second studio album\\\\u00a0<i><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fly_by_Night_(album)\\\\\\">Fly By Night</a></i>. The song focuses on the tranquillity and seemingly endless time a weary traveller could find there.</p><p>The Austrian folk band Rivendell takes the material for their lyrics almost entirely from Tolkien's books.</p><p>A Californian manufacturer of bicycles,\\\\u00a0<a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell_Bicycle_Works\\\\\\">Rivendell Bicycle Works</a>, also uses the name, inspired by the book and a United States backpacking supply company founded in the 1970s called\\\\u00a0Rivendell Mountain Works. They take many of the names of their bicycle models from Tolkien.<sup><a href=\\\\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivendell#cite_note-7\\\\\\">[7]</a></sup></p>\\", \\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\"}]", "locked": false, "seo_title": "", "image": 40, "numchild": 0, "pk": 19, "content_type": 6, "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:16:17.742Z", "go_live_at": null}	\N	19	1
292	f	2018-01-26 04:20:34.666378+00	{"path": "0001000100030005", "go_live_at": null, "content_type": 6, "depth": 4, "show_in_menus": false, "image": 43, "numchild": 0, "first_published_at": "2017-01-12T20:00:16.547Z", "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "live": true, "slug": "ngwesaung", "expired": false, "title": "Ngwesaung", "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>You can take a bus from Pathein or Yangon. The roads are better now , so for the about 260km from Yangon it will take about 5 hours, depending what bus you take. There are morning buses (i.e. 6:30am and 7:30am depending on demand, 10000 kyat) that depart from the western Yangon bus terminal (Hlaing Thar Yar Bus Terminal) which is 45 minutes by car taxi from the city centre. There is a bus service (4000 kyat) departing Pathein for Ngwe Saung at 2:00pm again depending on demand, if you miss that hire a moto taxi or jump in a jumbo for 5000 kyat or less (bargain hard!).</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Hiring a car is only worth it if you have missed the morning bus and do not want to ride by night. The difference in time is not big. It will cost around 120$.</p><p><br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"image\\", \\"value\\": {\\"style\\": \\"half\\", \\"image\\": 71, \\"caption\\": \\"Beautiful beach in Ngwe Saung\\"}}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>If you're travelling from Pathein, you can also catch a minivan. It departs from the bus station near Shwezigon Pagoda, the same bus station the local bus leaves from. It's a dark green Toyota Minivan with 'Beach Express' written in red writing on the front and sides. It leaves at 9am and 1pm and charges 3600 Kyat.</p><p><br/></p><p>There is no longer a requirement to remit a copy of your visa and passport prior at a military check point on the way to Ngwe Saung.</p><p><br/></p><p>Passports were handed to the bus operator who did have to show them to guards on the way to Ngwe Saung.</p><p><br/></p>\\